{"title_page": "Lucian Wintrich", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Lucian Wintrich\n| image        = Wintrich at the Yale Club of New York City.jpg\n| caption      = Wintrich at the [[Yale Club of New York City]]\n| birth_name   = Lucian Einhorn\n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| employer     = ''[[The Gateway Pundit]]'' (2016-2018)\n| education    = [[Bard College]]\n| occupation   = {{ubl | Writer}}\n| years_active = 2016\u2013present\n| notable_works = Twinks4Trump (2016, photo series)\n| website      = {{URL|lucianwintrich.com/}}\n}}\n'''Lucian Baxter Wintrich IV''' (n\u00e9 '''Einhorn''') is an American writer, speaker, and the former [[White House correspondent]] for the far-right news and opinion site ''[[The Gateway Pundit]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/gateway-pundits-lucian-wintrich-says-hes-on-sabbatical-appears-on-white-nationalists-podcast/|title=Gateway Pundit\u2019s Lucian Wintrich Says He\u2019s \u2018On Sabbatical,\u2019 Appears On White Nationalist\u2019s Podcast {{!}} Right Wing Watch|work=Right Wing Watch|access-date=August 13, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/controversial-twinks4trump-founder-joins-white-house-press-corps-n722791|title=Controversial 'Twinks4Trump' Founder Joins White House Press Corps|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-alt-right-branding-war-has-torn-the-movement-in-two|title=The Alt-Right Branding War Has Torn the Movement in Two|first=Andrew|last=Marantz|date=July 6, 2017|publisher=|via=www.newyorker.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Independent]]|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/white-power-hand-symbol-cassandra-fairbanks-mike-cernovich-alt-right-white-house-a7709446.html|title=Two members of alt-right accused of making white supremacist hand signs in White House after receiving press passes|date=April 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pagesix.com/2017/04/17/white-house-correspondent-once-played-clown-zombie/|work=[[New York Post#Page Six|Page Six]]|title=Alt-right journalist Lucian Wintrich once played clown-zombie|date=April 17, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ADL\">[https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/from-alt-right-to-alt-lite-naming-the-hate From Alt Right to Alt Lite: Naming the Hate]. [[Anti-Defamation League]].</ref>  He was among the first members of the [[White House press corps|White House Press Corps]] to be openly gay and one of the youngest.<ref>https://www.dailydot.com/irl/conservative-queers-lgbtq-trump/</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWintrich was born Lucian Einhorn in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], and grew up in the [[Squirrel Hill (Pittsburgh)|Squirrel Hill]] neighborhood.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-nation/2017/07/14/Lucian-Wintrich-White-House-correspondent-gateway-pundit-alt-right-twinks-for-trump-squirrel-hill-pittsburgh-heat-street/stories/201707160097|title=Lucian Wintrich is a White House correspondent better known for trolling than reporting|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=August 13, 2018|language=en}}</ref> He received his BA from [[Bard College]] in [[Annandale-on-Hudson]], [[New York (state)|New York]], where he majored in [[political science]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hac.bard.edu/lrc2017|title=Hannah Arendt Center Conferences & Events|website=hac.bard.edu}}</ref> Prior to high school, Wintrich attended the experimental prep school [[Fanny Edel Falk Laboratory School]], and then [[Taylor Allderdice High School]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thetartan.org/2006/10/30/news/pittsburgh_podcasting|title=Local high school students create popular podcast - The Tartan|access-date=June 3, 2017}}</ref> Wintrich's paternal grandfather, Jerzy Einhorn, was a medical doctor born in [[Sosnowiec]], Poland, who served as an officer in the [[Polish resistance movement in World War II|Polish resistance]].<ref name=\"post-gazette\">{{cite news|last1=Ove|first1=Torsten|title=Pittsburgh doctor, Polish warrior: The Jerzy Einhorn story|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/local/south/2011/07/24/The-Next-Page-Pittsburgh-doctor-Polish-warrior-The-Jerzy-Einhorn-story/stories/201107240235/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=July 24, 2011|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Einhorn|first1=Jerzy|title=Recollections of the End of an Era: Poland 1919-1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9WqTG8Oiv7cC&pg=PA172|accessdate=May 31, 2017|publisher=AuthorHouse|date=2005|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Scott|title=48 Hours With the Media Troll Who Is Now Part of the White House Press Corps|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/48-hours-media-troll-who-is-part-white-house-press-corps-997040|accessdate=May 28, 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=April 28, 2017}}</ref> Wintrich's own father is Jewish.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/48-hours-media-troll-who-is-part-white-house-press-corps-997040|title=48 Hours With the Media Troll Who Is Now Part of the White House Press Corps|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=August 13, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBy age 18, Wintrich had legally changed his name to Lucian Baxter Wintrich. He claims that he did so both to protect his relatives and to boost his public persona.<ref name=\":1\" /> Wintrich's adopted generational suffix is fictitious.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Career==\nWintrich gained public notice from his pro-[[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald Trump presidential candidacy]] series \"Twinks4Trump\", photographs of mostly shirtless gay [[Twink (gay slang)|twinks]] sporting  \"[[Make America Great Again]]\" baseball caps.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wintrich |first=Lucian B. |url=http://www.advocate.com/commentary/2016/8/02/twinks4trump-creator-5-things-media-gets-wrong-about-gay-conservatives |title=Twinks4Trump Creator: 5 Things the Media Gets Wrong About Gay Conservatives |website=Advocate.com |date=August 2, 2016 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> According to David Freedlander of ''[[The Daily Beast]],'' Wintrich was also organizer of a \"performance art show\" which Wintrich billed as \"the first pro-Trump art show in the nation's history\".<ref>{{cite web|author=David Freedlander |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/10/08/a-pro-trump-art-show-but-the-artists-are-interesting.html |title=A Pro-Trump Art Show\u2014But the \u2018Artists\u2019 Are\u2026Interesting |website=[[The Daily Beast]] |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mic.com/articles/168786/nyu-postpones-speech-by-twinks-4trump-creator-white-house-correspondent-lucian-wintrich#.agtxJQGY0|title=NYU postpones speech by Twinks4Trump creator, White House correspondent Lucian Wintrich|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nyulocal.com/lucian-wintrich-talk-to-nyu-college-republicans-postponed-717e69681cfb#.c4uhjbucl|title=Lucian Wintrich Talk to NYU College Republicans Postponed|date=February 14, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Wintrich has collaborated with [[Milo Yiannopoulos]], a former editor at ''[[Breitbart News]]''.<ref name=\"independent_T100_Hft_Wintrich\">{{citation |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/gateway-pundid-pro-donald-trump-blog-white-hosue-press-credentials-fake-news-hillary-clinton-health-a7580376.html |title=Gateway Pundit: Pro-Donald Trump blog granted White House press credentials |publisher=[[The Independent]] |language=en-GB |author=Andrew Buncombe |location=New York |date=February 14, 2017 |accessdate=February 14, 2017}}</ref> Although he was initially considered to be aligned with the [[alt-right]] movement, he later disavowed it, saying that [[Richard B. Spencer|Richard Spencer]] ruined the term.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Marantz|first1=Andrew|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-alt-right-branding-war-has-torn-the-movement-in-two|title=The Alt-Right Branding War Has Torn the Movement in Two|website=The New Yorker|publisher=The New Yorker|accessdate=November 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Michael|first1=Grynbaum|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/13/business/the-gateway-pundit-trump.html?_r=0&mtrref=www.google.com|title=White House Grants Press Credentials to a Pro-Trump Blog|website=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Justin|first1=Moyer|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/alt-right-and-alt-lite-conservatives-plan-dueling-conservative-rallies-sunday-in-dc/2017/06/22/242d8de2-56bd-11e7-9fb4-fa6b3df7bb8a_story.html|title='Alt-right' and 'alt-lite'? Conservatives plan dueling conservative rallies Sunday in D.C.|website=The Washington Post|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=June 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe day before [[Inauguration of Donald Trump|Donald Trump's inauguration]], Wintrich was named as the inaugural White House correspondent for ''The Gateway Pundit'', which was newly granted White House briefing credentials by the incoming administration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/02/fake-news-gateway-pundit-white-house-trump-briefing-room-214781|title=\u2018Real News\u2019 Joins the White House Briefing Room|newspaper=POLITICO Magazine|access-date=February 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220092529/http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/02/fake-news-gateway-pundit-white-house-trump-briefing-room-214781|archivedate=February 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/20/business/media/how-fake-news-spreads.html|title=How Fake News Goes Viral: A Case Study|last=Maheshwari|first=Sapna|date=November 20, 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=February 23, 2017|issn=0362-4331|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218210823/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/20/business/media/how-fake-news-spreads.html|archivedate=February 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/gateway-pundid-pro-donald-trump-blog-white-hosue-press-credentials-fake-news-hillary-clinton-health-a7580376.html |title=Gateway Pundit: Pro-Donald Trump blog granted White House press credentials |quote=Gateway Pundit published false reports about Hillary Clinton's health and voter fraud |publisher=[[The Independent]] |author=Andrew Buncombe |location=New York |date=February 14, 2017 |accessdate=February 14, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214185924/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/gateway-pundid-pro-donald-trump-blog-white-hosue-press-credentials-fake-news-hillary-clinton-health-a7580376.html |archivedate=February 14, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=White House Grants Press Credentials to a Pro-Trump Blog|date=February 13, 2017|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/13/business/the-gateway-pundit-trump.html|author=Michael M. Grynbaum|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 14, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214031407/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/13/business/the-gateway-pundit-trump.html|archivedate=February 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/02/fake-news-gateway-pundit-white-house-trump-briefing-room-214781|title='Real News' Joins the White House Briefing Room|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies===\nOn February 15, 2017, Wintrich was scheduled to speak to the [[College Republicans]] at [[New York University]] (NYU), but the talk was postponed over security concerns.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nyunews.com/2017/02/15/administration-postpones-nyucrs-guest-speaker-lucian-wintrich-due-to-security-concerns/|title=Administration Postpones NYUCR\u2019s Guest Speaker Lucian Wintrich Due to Security Concerns|first=Jemima|last=McEvoy|publisher=nyunews.com}}</ref> On March 23, 2017, he eventually spoke to the NYU College Republicans.<ref>{{cite web |author=Laura Casado |url=http://thetab.com/us/nyu/2017/02/14/exclusive-lucian-wintrich-speak-nyu-college-republicans-thursday-8385 |title=UPDATE: Lucian Wintrich talk to NYU College Republicans postponed |website=The Tab |date=February 14, 2017 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.nyunews.com/2017/03/24/lucian-wintrich-speaks-at-nyu-after-postponed-visit/ |title=Washington Square News : Lucian Wintrich Speaks at NYU After Postponed Visit |publisher=Nyunews.com |date=March 24, 2017 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, 2017, Wintrich was confronted by a fellow White House correspondent, [[Jon Decker]] of [[Fox News]] in the [[White House Briefing Room]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/gateway-pundit-lucian-wintrich-john-decker-fox-news-2017-3|title=Drama in White House press room as Fox reporter vehemently denies he assaulted right-wing blogger|work=Business Insider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/on-media/2017/03/fox-news-radio-correspondent-gateway-pundit-writer-235942|title=Fox News Radio correspondent confronts Gateway Pundit reporter in White House briefing room|work=Politico}}</ref> who loudly accused Wintrich of being a [[White supremacy|white supremacist]]. After the briefing, Wintrich was approached by [[April Ryan]] of [[American Urban Radio Networks]], who filmed him answering questions about whether or not he was a racist. [[Ben Jacobs (journalist)|Ben Jacobs]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' described Wintrich engaging with Ryan as him \"holding his own briefing because nothing matters.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/fake-news-trump-wages-war-on-traditional-media-a-1140173-2.html |title=Discrediting and Obstructing the Mainstream Media |work=Der Spiegel |date=March 24, 2017 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn November 28, 2017, Wintrich was arrested after an altercation in which he grabbed a woman who had snatched his papers from the speaker's lectern he was using during a talk at the [[University of Connecticut]] entitled \"[[It's OK to be white|It's OK to Be White]]\".  He was charged with [[breach of peace]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lurye|first1=Rebecca|title=Lucian Wintrich, White House Correspondent For Gateway Pundit, Arrested After Altercation At UConn Talk|url=http://www.courant.com/politics/hc-news-uconn-lucian-wintrich-speech-20171128-story.html|accessdate=November 29, 2017|work=Hartford Courant|date=November 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Quintana|first1=Chris|title=Far-Right Speaker Is Arrested at U. of Connecticut After Physical Confrontation|url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/Far-Right-Speaker-Is-Arrested/241915|accessdate=December 1, 2017|newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=November 29, 2017}}</ref> In December 2017, the charges against Wintrich were dropped and the woman who took the papers was charged with attempted sixth-degree [[larceny]] and [[disorderly conduct]]. She stated through her attorney that she took Wintrich's speech as a form of protest. The charges against her were later dropped after she agreed to a one year campus ban and a $500 donation to the university.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rondinone|first1=Nicholas|title=Quinebaug College Adviser Charged After Lucian Wintrich's UConn Event|url=http://www.courant.com/breaking-news/hc-br-catherine-gregory-lucian-wintrich-uconn-event-arrest-20171211-story.html|accessdate=December 11, 2017|publisher=Hartfort Courant|date=December 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Woman who stole 'OK To Be White' notes agrees to campus ban|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/education/article/Woman-who-stole-right-winger-s-speech-agrees-to-12519265.php|accessdate=February 4, 2018|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Wintrich tweeted the [[conspiracy theory]] that some survivors of the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]], who had spoken to the media about a need for gun reform in the wake of the tragedy, were \"trained actors who were recruited by [George] [[George Soros|Soros]]-linked organizations as spokespeople after a crisis.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-conspiracy-theories-20180221-story.html|title=Conspiracy theories about Florida school shooting survivors have gone mainstream|first=Matt|last=Pearce|website=latimes.com}}</ref> The tweet was liked by [[Donald Trump Jr.]] but was much criticized by others, including the shooting survivor [[David Hogg]], whom Wintrich had accused of being \"heavily coached\" for interviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/nation-world/article201199494.html|title=Florida shooting survivor, 17, calls out Donald Trump Jr. for liking conspiracy tweets|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2018, [[People for the American Way#Right Wing Watch|''Right Wing Watch'']] published an account of Wintrich's appearance on a podcast hosted by [[Nick Fuentes]] who has frequently been described as a [[White Nationalist]] (a label which Fuentes himself denies).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=Out.com>[https://www.out.com/news-opinion/2018/8/14/twinks4trump-founder-dropped-white-house-correspondent Twinks4Trump Founder Dropped As Gateway Pundit White House Correspondent Following Appearance on White Nationalist Podcast]. [[Out.com]], 14 August 2018</ref><ref name=Observer>[https://observer.com/2018/10/robert-mercer-bankrolled-pac-ali-alexander/ Robert Mercer Bankrolled PAC Advised By Notorious Fringe \u2018Philosopher\u2019 Ali Alexander]. [[Observer Media]], 30 October 2018</ref> According RWW During the podcast, Wintrich and Fuentes discussed among other topics, immigration, anti-white racism, and the alleged intellectual inferiority of certain ethnic groups.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nCoincidentally same day, ''The Gateway Pundit'' founder Jim Hoft announced via twitter that Wintrich had left the organization several weeks earlier.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/gatewaypundit/status/1027911988909879296?s=19|title=Jim Hoft on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=August 13, 2018|language=en}}</ref>  Later Wintrich appeared in a Periscope livestream where he conversed with admirers as he prepared to boil two lobsters; one of which he named for the Right Wing Watch reporter, Jared Holt, who had described his appearance on Fuentes's program.<ref name=\"Dumps\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/gateway-pundit-dumps-lucian-wintrich-after-he-went-on-white-nationalist-podcast |title=Gateway Pundit Dumps White House Reporter After He Went on White Nationalist Podcast |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |date=August 13, 2018 |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |author=Sommer, Will}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Wintrich held a \"coronavirus potluck,\" where the point was to spread the virus and build immunity. Wintrich himself said that the potluck was inspired by [[Pox party|chickenpox parties]]. Around twenty people attended the potluck in his New York city apartment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2020/03/twinks-trump-founder-held-corona-potluck-spread-virus/|title=\"Twinks for Trump\" founder held a \"corona potluck\" to spread the virus|last=Bollinger|first=Alex|date=2020-03-30|website=LGBTQ Nation|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/news/2020/3/30/lucian-wintrich-founder-twinks4trump-hosts-corona-potluck|title=Lucian Wintrich, Founder of 'Twinks4Trump,' Hosts 'Corona Potluck'|date=2020-03-30|website=www.advocate.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wintrich, Lucian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:People from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Bard College alumni]]\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:LGBT journalists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:Alt-right writers]]\n[[Category:Taylor Allderdice High School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Lucian Wintrich\n| image        = Wintrich at the Yale Club of New York City.jpg\n| caption      = Wintrich at the [[Yale Club of New York City]]\n| birth_name   = Lucian Einhorn\n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| employer     = ''[[The Gateway Pundit]]'' (2016-2018)\n| education    = [[Bard College]]\n| occupation   = {{ubl | Writer}}\n| years_active = 2016\u2013present\n| notable_works = Twinks4Trump (2016, photo series)\n| website      = {{URL|lucianwintrich.com/}}\n}}\n'''Lucian Baxter Wintrich IV''' (n\u00e9 '''Einhorn''') is an American writer, speaker, and the former [[White House correspondent]] for the far-right news and opinion site ''[[The Gateway Pundit]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/gateway-pundits-lucian-wintrich-says-hes-on-sabbatical-appears-on-white-nationalists-podcast/|title=Gateway Pundit\u2019s Lucian Wintrich Says He\u2019s \u2018On Sabbatical,\u2019 Appears On White Nationalist\u2019s Podcast {{!}} Right Wing Watch|work=Right Wing Watch|access-date=August 13, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/controversial-twinks4trump-founder-joins-white-house-press-corps-n722791|title=Controversial 'Twinks4Trump' Founder Joins White House Press Corps|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-alt-right-branding-war-has-torn-the-movement-in-two|title=The Alt-Right Branding War Has Torn the Movement in Two|first=Andrew|last=Marantz|date=July 6, 2017|publisher=|via=www.newyorker.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Independent]]|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/white-power-hand-symbol-cassandra-fairbanks-mike-cernovich-alt-right-white-house-a7709446.html|title=Two members of alt-right accused of making white supremacist hand signs in White House after receiving press passes|date=April 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pagesix.com/2017/04/17/white-house-correspondent-once-played-clown-zombie/|work=[[New York Post#Page Six|Page Six]]|title=Alt-right journalist Lucian Wintrich once played clown-zombie|date=April 17, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ADL\">[https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/from-alt-right-to-alt-lite-naming-the-hate From Alt Right to Alt Lite: Naming the Hate]. [[Anti-Defamation League]].</ref>  He was among the first members of the [[White House press corps|White House Press Corps]] to be openly gay and one of the youngest.<ref>https://www.dailydot.com/irl/conservative-queers-lgbtq-trump/</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWintrich was born '''Lucian Einhorn''' in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], and grew up in the [[Squirrel Hill (Pittsburgh)|Squirrel Hill]] neighborhood.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-nation/2017/07/14/Lucian-Wintrich-White-House-correspondent-gateway-pundit-alt-right-twinks-for-trump-squirrel-hill-pittsburgh-heat-street/stories/201707160097|title=Lucian Wintrich is a White House correspondent better known for trolling than reporting|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=August 13, 2018|language=en}}</ref> He received his BA from [[Bard College]] in [[Annandale-on-Hudson]], [[New York (state)|New York]], where he majored in [[political science]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hac.bard.edu/lrc2017|title=Hannah Arendt Center Conferences & Events|website=hac.bard.edu}}</ref> Prior to high school, Wintrich attended the experimental prep school [[Fanny Edel Falk Laboratory School]], and then [[Taylor Allderdice High School]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thetartan.org/2006/10/30/news/pittsburgh_podcasting|title=Local high school students create popular podcast - The Tartan|access-date=June 3, 2017}}</ref> Wintrich's paternal grandfather, Jerzy Einhorn, was a medical doctor born in [[Sosnowiec]], Poland, who served as an officer in the [[Polish resistance movement in World War II|Polish resistance]].<ref name=\"post-gazette\">{{cite news|last1=Ove|first1=Torsten|title=Pittsburgh doctor, Polish warrior: The Jerzy Einhorn story|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/local/south/2011/07/24/The-Next-Page-Pittsburgh-doctor-Polish-warrior-The-Jerzy-Einhorn-story/stories/201107240235/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=July 24, 2011|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Einhorn|first1=Jerzy|title=Recollections of the End of an Era: Poland 1919-1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9WqTG8Oiv7cC&pg=PA172|accessdate=May 31, 2017|publisher=AuthorHouse|date=2005|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Scott|title=48 Hours With the Media Troll Who Is Now Part of the White House Press Corps|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/48-hours-media-troll-who-is-part-white-house-press-corps-997040|accessdate=May 28, 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=April 28, 2017}}</ref> Wintrich's own father is Jewish.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/48-hours-media-troll-who-is-part-white-house-press-corps-997040|title=48 Hours With the Media Troll Who Is Now Part of the White House Press Corps|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=August 13, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBy age 18, Wintrich had legally changed his name to Lucian Baxter Wintrich. He claims that he did so both to protect his relatives and to boost his public persona.<ref name=\":1\" /> Wintrich's adopted generational suffix is fictitious.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Career==\nWintrich gained public notice from his pro-[[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald Trump presidential candidacy]] series \"Twinks4Trump\", photographs of mostly shirtless gay [[Twink (gay slang)|twinks]] sporting  \"[[Make America Great Again]]\" baseball caps.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wintrich |first=Lucian B. |url=http://www.advocate.com/commentary/2016/8/02/twinks4trump-creator-5-things-media-gets-wrong-about-gay-conservatives |title=Twinks4Trump Creator: 5 Things the Media Gets Wrong About Gay Conservatives |website=Advocate.com |date=August 2, 2016 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> According to David Freedlander of ''[[The Daily Beast]],'' Wintrich was also organizer of a \"performance art show\" which Wintrich billed as \"the first pro-Trump art show in the nation's history\".<ref>{{cite web|author=David Freedlander |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/10/08/a-pro-trump-art-show-but-the-artists-are-interesting.html |title=A Pro-Trump Art Show\u2014But the \u2018Artists\u2019 Are\u2026Interesting |website=[[The Daily Beast]] |date= |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mic.com/articles/168786/nyu-postpones-speech-by-twinks-4trump-creator-white-house-correspondent-lucian-wintrich#.agtxJQGY0|title=NYU postpones speech by Twinks4Trump creator, White House correspondent Lucian Wintrich|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nyulocal.com/lucian-wintrich-talk-to-nyu-college-republicans-postponed-717e69681cfb#.c4uhjbucl|title=Lucian Wintrich Talk to NYU College Republicans Postponed|date=February 14, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Wintrich has collaborated with [[Milo Yiannopoulos]], a former editor at ''[[Breitbart News]]''.<ref name=\"independent_T100_Hft_Wintrich\">{{citation |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/gateway-pundid-pro-donald-trump-blog-white-hosue-press-credentials-fake-news-hillary-clinton-health-a7580376.html |title=Gateway Pundit: Pro-Donald Trump blog granted White House press credentials |publisher=[[The Independent]] |language=en-GB |author=Andrew Buncombe |location=New York |date=February 14, 2017 |accessdate=February 14, 2017}}</ref> Although he was initially considered to be aligned with the [[alt-right]] movement, he later disavowed it, saying that [[Richard B. Spencer|Richard Spencer]] ruined the term.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Marantz|first1=Andrew|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-alt-right-branding-war-has-torn-the-movement-in-two|title=The Alt-Right Branding War Has Torn the Movement in Two|website=The New Yorker|publisher=The New Yorker|accessdate=November 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Michael|first1=Grynbaum|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/13/business/the-gateway-pundit-trump.html?_r=0&mtrref=www.google.com|title=White House Grants Press Credentials to a Pro-Trump Blog|website=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Justin|first1=Moyer|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/alt-right-and-alt-lite-conservatives-plan-dueling-conservative-rallies-sunday-in-dc/2017/06/22/242d8de2-56bd-11e7-9fb4-fa6b3df7bb8a_story.html|title='Alt-right' and 'alt-lite'? Conservatives plan dueling conservative rallies Sunday in D.C.|website=The Washington Post|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=June 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe day before [[Inauguration of Donald Trump|Donald Trump's inauguration]], Wintrich was named as the inaugural White House correspondent for ''The Gateway Pundit'', which was newly granted White House briefing credentials by the incoming administration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/02/fake-news-gateway-pundit-white-house-trump-briefing-room-214781|title=\u2018Real News\u2019 Joins the White House Briefing Room|newspaper=POLITICO Magazine|access-date=February 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170220092529/http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/02/fake-news-gateway-pundit-white-house-trump-briefing-room-214781|archivedate=February 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/20/business/media/how-fake-news-spreads.html|title=How Fake News Goes Viral: A Case Study|last=Maheshwari|first=Sapna|date=November 20, 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=February 23, 2017|issn=0362-4331|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218210823/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/20/business/media/how-fake-news-spreads.html|archivedate=February 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/gateway-pundid-pro-donald-trump-blog-white-hosue-press-credentials-fake-news-hillary-clinton-health-a7580376.html |title=Gateway Pundit: Pro-Donald Trump blog granted White House press credentials |quote=Gateway Pundit published false reports about Hillary Clinton's health and voter fraud |publisher=[[The Independent]] |author=Andrew Buncombe |location=New York |date=February 14, 2017 |accessdate=February 14, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214185924/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/gateway-pundid-pro-donald-trump-blog-white-hosue-press-credentials-fake-news-hillary-clinton-health-a7580376.html |archivedate=February 14, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=White House Grants Press Credentials to a Pro-Trump Blog|date=February 13, 2017|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/13/business/the-gateway-pundit-trump.html|author=Michael M. Grynbaum|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 14, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214031407/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/13/business/the-gateway-pundit-trump.html|archivedate=February 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/02/fake-news-gateway-pundit-white-house-trump-briefing-room-214781|title='Real News' Joins the White House Briefing Room|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies===\nOn February 15, 2017, Wintrich was scheduled to speak to the [[College Republicans]] at [[New York University]] (NYU), but the talk was postponed over security concerns.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nyunews.com/2017/02/15/administration-postpones-nyucrs-guest-speaker-lucian-wintrich-due-to-security-concerns/|title=Administration Postpones NYUCR\u2019s Guest Speaker Lucian Wintrich Due to Security Concerns|first=Jemima|last=McEvoy|publisher=nyunews.com}}</ref> On March 23, 2017, he eventually spoke to the NYU College Republicans.<ref>{{cite web |author=Laura Casado |url=http://thetab.com/us/nyu/2017/02/14/exclusive-lucian-wintrich-speak-nyu-college-republicans-thursday-8385 |title=UPDATE: Lucian Wintrich talk to NYU College Republicans postponed |website=The Tab |date=February 14, 2017 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.nyunews.com/2017/03/24/lucian-wintrich-speaks-at-nyu-after-postponed-visit/ |title=Washington Square News : Lucian Wintrich Speaks at NYU After Postponed Visit |publisher=Nyunews.com |date=March 24, 2017 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, 2017, Wintrich was confronted by a fellow White House correspondent, [[Jon Decker]] of [[Fox News]] in the [[White House Briefing Room]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/gateway-pundit-lucian-wintrich-john-decker-fox-news-2017-3|title=Drama in White House press room as Fox reporter vehemently denies he assaulted right-wing blogger|work=Business Insider}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/on-media/2017/03/fox-news-radio-correspondent-gateway-pundit-writer-235942|title=Fox News Radio correspondent confronts Gateway Pundit reporter in White House briefing room|work=Politico}}</ref> who loudly accused Wintrich of being a [[White supremacy|white supremacist]]. After the briefing, Wintrich was approached by [[April Ryan]] of [[American Urban Radio Networks]], who filmed him answering questions about whether or not he was a racist. [[Ben Jacobs (journalist)|Ben Jacobs]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' described Wintrich engaging with Ryan as him \"holding his own briefing because nothing matters.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/fake-news-trump-wages-war-on-traditional-media-a-1140173-2.html |title=Discrediting and Obstructing the Mainstream Media |work=Der Spiegel |date=March 24, 2017 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn November 28, 2017, Wintrich was arrested after an altercation in which he grabbed a woman who had snatched his papers from the speaker's lectern he was using during a talk at the [[University of Connecticut]] entitled \"[[It's OK to be white|It's OK to Be White]]\".  He was charged with [[breach of peace]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lurye|first1=Rebecca|title=Lucian Wintrich, White House Correspondent For Gateway Pundit, Arrested After Altercation At UConn Talk|url=http://www.courant.com/politics/hc-news-uconn-lucian-wintrich-speech-20171128-story.html|accessdate=November 29, 2017|work=Hartford Courant|date=November 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Quintana|first1=Chris|title=Far-Right Speaker Is Arrested at U. of Connecticut After Physical Confrontation|url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/Far-Right-Speaker-Is-Arrested/241915|accessdate=December 1, 2017|newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=November 29, 2017}}</ref> In December 2017, the charges against Wintrich were dropped and the woman who took the papers was charged with attempted sixth-degree [[larceny]] and [[disorderly conduct]]. She stated through her attorney that she took Wintrich's speech as a form of protest. The charges against her were later dropped after she agreed to a one year campus ban and a $500 donation to the university.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rondinone|first1=Nicholas|title=Quinebaug College Adviser Charged After Lucian Wintrich's UConn Event|url=http://www.courant.com/breaking-news/hc-br-catherine-gregory-lucian-wintrich-uconn-event-arrest-20171211-story.html|accessdate=December 11, 2017|publisher=Hartfort Courant|date=December 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Woman who stole 'OK To Be White' notes agrees to campus ban|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/education/article/Woman-who-stole-right-winger-s-speech-agrees-to-12519265.php|accessdate=February 4, 2018|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Wintrich tweeted the [[conspiracy theory]] that some survivors of the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]], who had spoken to the media about a need for gun reform in the wake of the tragedy, were \"trained actors who were recruited by [George] [[George Soros|Soros]]-linked organizations as spokespeople after a crisis.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-conspiracy-theories-20180221-story.html|title=Conspiracy theories about Florida school shooting survivors have gone mainstream|first=Matt|last=Pearce|website=latimes.com}}</ref> The tweet was liked by [[Donald Trump Jr.]] but was much criticized by others, including the shooting survivor [[David Hogg]], whom Wintrich had accused of being \"heavily coached\" for interviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/nation-world/article201199494.html|title=Florida shooting survivor, 17, calls out Donald Trump Jr. for liking conspiracy tweets|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn August 10, 2018, [[People for the American Way#Right Wing Watch|''Right Wing Watch'']] published an account of Wintrich's appearance on a podcast hosted by [[Nick Fuentes]] who has frequently been described as a [[White Nationalist]] (a label which Fuentes himself denies).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=Out.com>[https://www.out.com/news-opinion/2018/8/14/twinks4trump-founder-dropped-white-house-correspondent Twinks4Trump Founder Dropped As Gateway Pundit White House Correspondent Following Appearance on White Nationalist Podcast]. [[Out.com]], 14 August 2018</ref><ref name=Observer>[https://observer.com/2018/10/robert-mercer-bankrolled-pac-ali-alexander/ Robert Mercer Bankrolled PAC Advised By Notorious Fringe \u2018Philosopher\u2019 Ali Alexander]. [[Observer Media]], 30 October 2018</ref> According RWW During the podcast, Wintrich and Fuentes discussed among other topics, immigration, anti-white racism, and the alleged intellectual inferiority of certain ethnic groups.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nCoincidentally same day, ''The Gateway Pundit'' founder Jim Hoft announced via twitter that Wintrich had left the organization several weeks earlier.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/gatewaypundit/status/1027911988909879296?s=19|title=Jim Hoft on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=August 13, 2018|language=en}}</ref>  Later Wintrich appeared in a Periscope livestream where he conversed with admirers as he prepared to boil two lobsters; one of which he named for the Right Wing Watch reporter, Jared Holt, who had described his appearance on Fuentes's program.<ref name=\"Dumps\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/gateway-pundit-dumps-lucian-wintrich-after-he-went-on-white-nationalist-podcast |title=Gateway Pundit Dumps White House Reporter After He Went on White Nationalist Podcast |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |date=August 13, 2018 |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |author=Sommer, Will}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic]], Wintrich held a \"coronavirus potluck,\" where the point was to spread the virus and build immunity. Wintrich himself said that the potluck was inspired by [[Pox party|chickenpox parties]]. Around twenty people attended the potluck in his New York city apartment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2020/03/twinks-trump-founder-held-corona-potluck-spread-virus/|title=\"Twinks for Trump\" founder held a \"corona potluck\" to spread the virus|last=Bollinger|first=Alex|date=2020-03-30|website=LGBTQ Nation|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/news/2020/3/30/lucian-wintrich-founder-twinks4trump-hosts-corona-potluck|title=Lucian Wintrich, Founder of 'Twinks4Trump,' Hosts 'Corona Potluck'|date=2020-03-30|website=www.advocate.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wintrich, Lucian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:People from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Bard College alumni]]\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:LGBT journalists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:Alt-right writers]]\n[[Category:Taylor Allderdice High School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "CookieMonster755", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucian_Wintrich"}
{"title_page": "8th Daytime Emmy Awards", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name = 8th Daytime Emmy Awards\n| image = \n| caption = \n| date = May 21, 1981\n| location = [[Grand Hyatt New York]]\n| presenter = [[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]]\n| host = [[Dick Clark]]\n| network = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| previous = [[7th Daytime Emmy Awards|7th]]\n| main = {{nowrap|[[Daytime Emmy Award]]s}}\n| next = [[9th Daytime Emmy Awards|9th]]\n}}\nThe '''8th Daytime Emmy Awards''' were held on Thursday, May 21, 1981, to commemorate excellence in daytime programming from March 6, 1980-March 5, 1981. The eighth awards did not include the cameo category from the previous year, so only five awards were given, like in previous years.\n\nThe ceremony was telecast the following day on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]].\n\nWinners in each category are in '''bold'''.\n\n==Outstanding Daytime Drama Series==\n*''[[All My Children]]''\n*'''''[[General Hospital]]'''''\n*''[[Ryan's Hope]]''\n\n==Outstanding Actor in a Daytime Drama Series==\n*[[James Mitchell (actor)|James Mitchell]] (''Palmer Cortlandt, [[All My Children]]'')\n*'''[[Douglass Watson]]''' (''Mac Cory, [[Another World (TV series)|Another World]]'')\n*[[Larry Bryggman]] (''John Dixon, [[As the World Turns]]'')\n*[[Henderson Forsythe]] (''David Stewart, [[As the World Turns]]'')\n*[[Anthony Geary]] (''Luke Spencer, [[General Hospital]]'')\n\n==Outstanding Actress in a Daytime Drama Series==\n*[[Julia Barr]] (''Brooke English, [[All My Children]]'')\n*[[Susan Lucci]] (''[[Erica Kane]], [[All My Children]]'')\n*'''[[Judith Light]]''' (''[[Karen Wolek]], [[One Life to Live]]'')\n*[[Robin Strasser]] (''[[Dorian Lord]], [[One Life to Live]]'')\n*[[Helen Gallagher]] (''Maeve Ryan, [[Ryan's Hope]]'')\n\n==Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Daytime Drama Series==\n*[[Matthew Cowles]] (Billy Clyde Tuggle, ''[[All My Children]]'')\n*[[William Mooney]] (Paul Martin, ''[[All My Children]]'')\n*[[Justin Deas]] ([[Tom Hughes (As the World Turns)|Tom Hughes]], ''[[As the World Turns]]'')\n*[[Richard Backus]] (Barry Ryan, ''[[Ryan's Hope]]'')\n*'''[[Larry Haines]]''' (Stu Bergman, ''[[Search for Tomorrow]]'')\n\n==Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Daytime Drama Series==\n*Elizabeth Lawrence, (Myra Sloane, ''[[All My Children]]'')\n*[[Lois Kibbee]], (Geraldine Whitney Saxon, ''[[The Edge of Night]]'')\n*'''[[Jane Elliot]]''' ([[Tracy Quartermaine]], ''[[General Hospital]]'')\n*[[Randall Edwards (actress)|Randall Edwards]] (Delia Ryan, ''[[Ryan's Hope]]'')\n*[[Jacklyn Zeman]] ([[Bobbie Spencer]], ''[[General Hospital]]'')\n\n==Outstanding Daytime Drama Series Writing==\n* '''''Guiding Light'': [[Douglas Marland]], [[Robert Dwywer]], [[Nancy Franklin]] & [[Harding Lemay]]'''\n* ''All My Children'': [[Agnes Nixon]], [[Wisner Washam]], [[Jack Wood]]\n* ''General Hospital''\n* ''One Life to Live''\n\n==Outstanding Daytime Drama Series Directing==\n* ''All My Children''\n* '''''General Hospital'''''\n* ''One Life to Live''\n\n==Outstanding Game Show==\n*'''''[[The $20,000 Pyramid]]''''' \u2013 A Bob Stewart Production for ABC\n*''[[Family Feud]]'' \u2013 A Mark Goodson-Bill Todman Production for ABC\n*''[[The Hollywood Squares]]'' \u2013 A Heatter-Quigley Production for NBC\n\n==Outstanding Game Show Host==\n*'''[[Peter Marshall (game show host)|Peter Marshall]]''' (''The Hollywood Squares'')\n*[[Dick Clark]] (''The $20,000 Pyramid'')\n*[[Richard Dawson]] (''Family Feud'')\n\n==References==\n*{{cite web  | title =Daytime Emmy Awards  | publisher =[[Internet Movie Database]]  | date =| url =https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000206/1981}}\n\n{{EmmyAwardsbyYear}}\n\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award ceremonies|008]]\n[[Category:1981 television awards|D]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name = 8th Daytime Emmy Awards\n| image = \n| caption = \n| date = May 21, 1981\n| location = [[Grand Hyatt New York]]\n| presenter = [[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]]\n| host = [[Dick Clark]]\n| network = [[ABC]]\n| previous = [[7th Daytime Emmy Awards|7th]]\n| main = {{nowrap|[[Daytime Emmy Award]]s}}\n| next = [[9th Daytime Emmy Awards|9th]]\n}}\nThe '''8th Daytime Emmy Awards''' were held on Thursday, May 21, 1981, to commemorate excellence in daytime programming from March 6, 1980-March 5, 1981. The eighth awards did not include the cameo category from the previous year, so only five awards were given, like in previous years.\n\nThe ceremony was telecast the following day on [[ABC]].\n\nWinners in each category are in '''bold'''.\n\n==Outstanding Daytime Drama Series==\n*''[[All My Children]]''\n*'''''[[General Hospital]]'''''\n*''[[Ryan's Hope]]''\n\n==Outstanding Actor in a Daytime Drama Series==\n*[[James Mitchell (actor)|James Mitchell]] (''Palmer Cortlandt, [[All My Children]]'')\n*'''[[Douglass Watson]]''' (''Mac Cory, [[Another World (TV series)|Another World]]'')\n*[[Larry Bryggman]] (''John Dixon, [[As the World Turns]]'')\n*[[Henderson Forsythe]] (''David Stewart, [[As the World Turns]]'')\n*[[Anthony Geary]] (''Luke Spencer, [[General Hospital]]'')\n\n==Outstanding Actress in a Daytime Drama Series==\n*[[Julia Barr]] (''Brooke English, [[All My Children]]'')\n*[[Susan Lucci]] (''[[Erica Kane]], [[All My Children]]'')\n*'''[[Judith Light]]''' (''[[Karen Wolek]], [[One Life to Live]]'')\n*[[Robin Strasser]] (''[[Dorian Lord]], [[One Life to Live]]'')\n*[[Helen Gallagher]] (''Maeve Ryan, [[Ryan's Hope]]'')\n\n==Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Daytime Drama Series==\n*[[Matthew Cowles]] (Billy Clyde Tuggle, ''[[All My Children]]'')\n*[[William Mooney]] (Paul Martin, ''[[All My Children]]'')\n*[[Justin Deas]] ([[Tom Hughes (As the World Turns)|Tom Hughes]], ''[[As the World Turns]]'')\n*[[Richard Backus]] (Barry Ryan, ''[[Ryan's Hope]]'')\n*'''[[Larry Haines]]''' (Stu Bergman, ''[[Search for Tomorrow]]'')\n\n==Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Daytime Drama Series==\n*Elizabeth Lawrence, (Myra Sloane, ''[[All My Children]]'')\n*[[Lois Kibbee]], (Geraldine Whitney Saxon, ''[[The Edge of Night]]'')\n*'''[[Jane Elliot]]''' ([[Tracy Quartermaine]], ''[[General Hospital]]'')\n*[[Randall Edwards (actress)|Randall Edwards]] (Delia Ryan, ''[[Ryan's Hope]]'')\n*[[Jacklyn Zeman]] ([[Bobbie Spencer]], ''[[General Hospital]]'')\n\n==Outstanding Daytime Drama Series Writing==\n* '''''Guiding Light'': [[Douglas Marland]], [[Robert Dwywer]], [[Nancy Franklin]] & [[Harding Lemay]]'''''\n* ''All My Children'': [[Agnes Nixon]], [[Wisner Washam]], [[Jack Wood]]\n* ''General Hospital''\n* ''One Life to Live''\n\n==Outstanding Daytime Drama Series Directing==\n* ''All My Children''\n* '''''General Hospital'''''\n* ''One Life to Live''\n\n==Outstanding Game Show==\n*'''''[[The $20,000 Pyramid]]''''' \u2013 A Bob Stewart Production for ABC\n*''[[Family Feud]]'' \u2013 A Mark Goodson-Bill Todman Production for ABC\n*''[[The Hollywood Squares]]'' \u2013 A Heatter-Quigley Production for NBC\n\n==Outstanding Game Show Host==\n*'''[[Peter Marshall (game show host)|Peter Marshall]]''' (''The Hollywood Squares'')\n*[[Dick Clark]] (''The $20,000 Pyramid'')\n*[[Richard Dawson]] (''Family Feud'')\n\n==References==\n*{{cite web  | title =Daytime Emmy Awards  | publisher =[[Internet Movie Database]]  | date =| url =https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000206/1981}}\n\n{{EmmyAwardsbyYear}}\n\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award ceremonies|008]]\n[[Category:1981 television awards|D]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-ABC/WP:WCWproject (Missing end bold/italic)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/8th_Daytime_Emmy_Awards"}
{"title_page": "Naomi Watts", "text_new": "{{short description|English actress and film producer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Naomi Watts\n| image              = File:Naomi Watts (36037832511) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Watts at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic Con]]\n| birth_name         = Naomi Ellen Watts\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1968|9|28}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shoreham, Kent]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = British, Australian<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/entertainment/2007-04/29/content_863583.htm|title=Naomi Watts: I still consider myself British|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Actress\n*film producer\n}}\n| years_active       = 1986\u2013present\n| works              = [[Naomi Watts filmography|Filmography]]\n| partner            = [[Liev Schreiber]] (2005\u20132016) \n| children           = 2\n| father             = [[Peter Watts (road manager)|Peter Watts]]\n| relatives          = [[Ben Watts]] (brother)\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Naomi Watts|Full list]]\n}}\n\n'''Naomi Ellen Watts''' (born 28 September 1968) is a British-Australian<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/entertainment/2007-04/29/content_863583.htm|title=Naomi Watts: I still consider myself British|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> actress and film producer.<!--Please discuss on the talk page before changing this. Thank you.--><ref>{{cite news |first=Gill |last=Pringle |title=Naomi Watts on 'While We're Young', her roots and being a mum |date=30 March 2015 |work=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/naomi-watts-on-while-were-young-her-roots-and-being-a-mum-10144541.html |accessdate=30 April 2015 |quote=The truth is that I've spent more time in America out of all three countries. I spent the first 14 years in England, just under 10 in Australia and then the rest in America. I've still got only one passport and that's British and my mum still lives between there and Australia. I feel very much a part of both countries.}}</ref> She made her film debut in the Australian drama ''[[For Love Alone]]'' (1986) and then appeared in the Australian television series ''[[Hey Dad..!]]'' (1990), ''[[Brides of Christ]]'' (1991), ''[[Home and Away]]'' (1991), and the film ''[[Flirting (film)|Flirting]]'' (1991). After moving to the United States, Watts struggled as an actress for years, but managed to obtain parts in the films ''[[Tank Girl (film)|Tank Girl]]'' (1995), ''[[Children of the Corn IV: The Gathering]]'' (1996), and ''[[Dangerous Beauty]]'' (1998), and the television series ''[[Sleepwalkers (TV series)|Sleepwalkers]]'' (1997\u20131998).\n\nWatts rose to international prominence for playing an aspiring actress in [[David Lynch]]'s psychological thriller ''[[Mulholland Drive (film)|Mulholland Drive]]'' (2001) and a tormented journalist in the horror remake ''[[The Ring (2002 film)|The Ring]]'' (2002). She subsequently received a nomination for the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]] for her performance as a grief-stricken mother in [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]]'s [[neo-noir]] film ''[[21 Grams]]'' (2003). Her next films throughout the 2000s include ''[[I Heart Huckabees]]'' (2004), [[King Kong (2005 film)|''King Kong'']] (2005), ''[[Eastern Promises]]'' (2007), and ''[[The International (2009 film)|The International]]'' (2009).\n\nFor her role as [[Mar\u00eda Bel\u00f3n|Maria Bennett]] in the disaster film ''[[The Impossible (2012 film)|The Impossible]]'' (2012), Watts received another Academy Award for Best Actress nomination. In the 2010s, she starred in the well-received independent films ''[[Birdman (film)|Birdman]]'' (2014), for which she won a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] as part of the cast, ''[[St. Vincent (film)|St. Vincent]]'' (2014), ''[[While We're Young (film)|While We're Young]]'' (2015), and ''[[Luce (film)|Luce]]'' (2019). Watts also continued to act in blockbusters, with appearances in the [[The Divergent Series|''Divergent'' franchise]] (2015\u20132016), and ventured into television with the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] series ''[[Twin Peaks (season 3)|Twin Peaks]]'' (2017) and ''[[The Loudest Voice]]'' (2019).\n\nWatts is particularly known for her work in remakes and independent productions with dark or tragic themes, as well as portrayals of characters that endure loss or suffering.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jul/15/naomi-watts-wasnt-soul-destroyed-gypsy</ref>Magazines such as ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' and ''Maxim'' have included her on their lists of the world's most beautiful women. She has been an ambassador for [[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS]] and [[Pantene]]'s [[Pantene Beautiful Lengths|Beautiful Lengths]]. Despite significant media attention, Watts is reticent about her personal life. She had a relationship with American actor [[Liev Schreiber]] from 2005 to 2016, with whom she has two sons.\n\n==Early life==\nNaomi Ellen Watts was born on 28 September 1968, in [[Shoreham, Kent]], England.<ref name=contemporary /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/3671818/Naomi-Watts-on-Funny-Games.html |title=Naomi Watts on Funny Games |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |first=Sheila |last=Johnston |date=15 March 2008 |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref> She is the daughter of Myfanwy (\"Miv\") Edwards (''[[Given name|n\u00e9e]]'' Roberts), an antiques dealer and costume and set designer,<ref name=contemporary>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=FORkAAAAMAAJ&dq=naomi+watts+antiques+dealer+costume&q=antiques+dealer+costume#search_anchor|title=Contemporary Theatre, Film and Television: A Biographical Guide Featuring Performers, Directors, Writers, Producers, Designers, Managers, Choreographers, Technicians, Composers, Executives, Dancers|publisher=Gale/Cengage Learning|year=2005|isbn=978-0-7876-9037-3|page=340}}</ref> and [[Peter Watts (road manager)|Peter Watts]] (1946\u20131976), a road manager and sound engineer who worked with [[Pink Floyd]].<ref name=\"Sams, Christine\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/02/22/1077384633676.html|title=How Naomi told her mum about Oscar|accessdate=15 December 2008|author=Sams, Christine|date=23 February 2004|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]}}</ref><ref name=tca>Stated on ''[[Inside the Actors Studio]]'', 2003</ref> Miv was born in England but lived in Australia between the ages of one and seven. Watts's maternal grandfather was Welsh and her maternal grandmother was Australian.<ref name=\"smh\">{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/02/22/1077384633676.html?from=storyrhs|title=How Naomi told her mum about Oscar \u2013 SpecialsEntFilmOscars2004 \u2013 www.smh.com.au|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=30 May 2015|date=23 February 2004}}</ref><ref name=\"themorningbulletin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themorningbulletin.com.au/news/naomi-watts-while-were-young-her-roots-and-being-m/2592146/|title=Naomi Watts on 'While We're Young', her roots and being a mum &#124; Rockhampton Morning Bulletin|publisher=themorningbulletin.com.au|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nWatts's parents divorced when she was four years old.<ref name=tca/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2003/11/23/naomi_watts/|title=A role filled with rage and anguish reveals the fearless side of an actress who respects the power of emotion|work=Boston Globe |first=Scott|last=Heller|date=23 November 2003|accessdate=5 July 2011}}</ref> After the divorce, Watts and her elder brother, [[Ben Watts]], moved several times across [[South East England]] with their mother.<ref name=mymotto/> Peter Watts left Pink Floyd in 1974, and remarried in 1976. In August 1976, he was found dead in a flat in [[Notting Hill]], of an apparent heroin [[drug overdose|overdose]].<ref name=\"Talk Talk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.talktalk.co.uk/entertainment/film/biography/artist/naomi-watts/biography/157|title=Naomi Watts Biography|work=TalkTalk|publisher=Tiscali UK Limited trading|accessdate=5 July 2011| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516055536/http://www.talktalk.co.uk/entertainment/film/biography/artist/naomi-watts/biography/157| archive-date=16 May 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Numb\">{{Cite book| publisher = Di Capo Press| isbn = 978-0-306-81752-6| page = [https://archive.org/details/comfortablynumbi00mark/page/213 213]| last = Blake| first = Mark| title = Comfortably Numb - The Inside Story of Pink Floyd| year = 2008| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/comfortablynumbi00mark/page/213}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his death, Watts's mother moved the family to Llanfawr Farm in [[Llangefni]] and [[Llanfairpwllgwyngyll]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WwYAuvBcQ1Y |title=Naomi Watts' Unpronounceable Town Name |via=YouTube |date=6 March 2015 |accessdate=7 March 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.moviefone.com/2015/03/06/best-of-late-night-tv-chris-hemsworths-musical-beers/ |title=Best of Late Night TV: Chris Hemsworth's Musical Beers and Naomi Watts' Crazy Hometown (VIDEO) |publisher=Moviefone |date=6 March 2015 |accessdate=7 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150307103200/http://news.moviefone.com/2015/03/06/best-of-late-night-tv-chris-hemsworths-musical-beers/ |archive-date=7 March 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> towns on the island of [[Anglesey]] in [[North Wales]], where they lived with Watts's maternal grandparents, Nikki and Hugh Roberts, for three years. During this time, Watts attended a [[Welsh language]] school, [[Ysgol Gyfun Llangefni]].<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> She later said of her time in Wales: \"We took Welsh lessons in a school in the middle of nowhere while everyone else was taking English. Wherever we moved, I would adapt and pick up the regional accent. It's obviously significant now, me being an actress. Anyway, there was quite a lot of sadness in my childhood, but no lack of love.\"<ref name=bbcprofile>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northwest/halloffame/showbiz/naomiwatts.shtml|title=Naomi Watts|work=BBC North West Wales|publisher=BBC|date=November 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207172543/http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northwest/halloffame/showbiz/naomiwatts.shtml|archivedate=7 December 2008}}</ref> In 1978, her mother remarried (though she would later be divorced again)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2003/09/15/naomi_watts_le_divorce_interview.shtml|title=Naomi Watts|publisher=BBC|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref> and Watts and her brother then moved to [[Suffolk]], where she attended [[Thomas Mills High School]].<ref name=mymotto>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2007/oct/19/londonfilmfestival2007.londonfilmfestival|title=Work begets work: that is my motto|newspaper=The Guardian|date=19 October 2007|first=Emma|last=Brockes|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> Watts has stated that she wanted to become an actress after seeing her mother performing on stage and from the time she watched the 1980 film ''[[Fame (1980 film)|Fame]]''.<ref name=tca/><ref name=people>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/naomi_watts|title=Naomi Watts|work=People|accessdate=5 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, when Watts was 14, she moved to Sydney in Australia with her mother, brother and stepfather.<ref name=tca/><ref name=biochannel>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/naomi-watts.html|title=Naomi Watts Biography|work=The Biography Channel UK|publisher=A&E Television Networks|accessdate=5 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104172344/http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/naomi-watts.html|archivedate=4 January 2014}}</ref> Myfanwy established a career in the burgeoning film business, working as a stylist for television commercials, then turning to costume design, ultimately working for the soap opera ''[[Return to Eden]]''.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> After emigrating, Watts was enrolled in acting lessons by her mother; she auditioned for numerous television advertisements, where she met and befriended actress [[Nicole Kidman]]. Watts obtained her first role in the 1986 drama film, ''[[For Love Alone]]'', based on the novel of the same name by [[Christina Stead]], and produced by [[Margaret Fink]].<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/>\n\nIn Australia, Watts attended [[Mosman High School]] and [[North Sydney Girls High School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mosman-daily.whereilive.com.au/news/story/lower-north-shores-top-aussie-legends/|title=Lower North Shore's top Aussie legends|date=21 January 2010|accessdate=5 July 2011|work=The Mosman Daily|publisher=News Community Media}}</ref> She failed to graduate from school, afterwards working as a papergirl, a [[negative cutter]] and managing a Delicacies store in Sydney's affluent [[North Shore (Sydney)|North Shore]].<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/>\n\nShe decided to become a model when she was 18. She signed with a models agency that sent her to Japan, but after several failed auditions, she returned to Sydney.<ref name=tca/> There, she was hired to work in advertising for a department store, that exposed her to the attention of ''[[Follow Me (magazine)|Follow Me]]'', a magazine which hired her as an assistant fashion editor.<ref name=tca/><ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> A casual invitation to participate in a drama workshop inspired Watts to quit her job and to pursue her acting ambitions.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/><ref name=interviewmag>{{cite web|url=http://www.lynchnet.com/mdrive/wattsint.html|title=For Anyone who Ever Needed a reminder of what can happen when you hold onto your dreams \u2013 here she is|accessdate=31 August 2010|last=Sischy|first=Ingrid|date=December 2003|publisher=Brandt Publications}}</ref>\n\nRegarding her nationality, Watts has stated: \"I consider myself British and have very happy memories of the UK. I spent the first 14 years of my life in England and [[Wales]] and never wanted to leave. When I was in Australia I went back to England a lot.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/anglophenia/2011/07/warning-naomi-watts-is-secretly-british|title=Warning: Naomi Watts Is&nbsp;... Secretly British|first=MacKenzie|last=Wilson|accessdate=28 July 2014|date=5 July 2011|publisher=BBC America}}</ref> She also has expressed her ties to Australia, declaring: \"I consider myself very connected to Australia, in fact when people say where is home, I say Australia, because those are my most powerful memories.\"<ref>{{cite video|people=Aspen, Richard (Interviewer); Watts, Naomi (Interviewee)|date=11 September 2007|title=Eastern Promises Interview|work=[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early roles and struggling career (1986\u20132000)===\nWatts's career began in television, where she made brief appearances in commercials.<ref name=biochannel/> The 1986 film ''[[For Love Alone]]'', set in the 1930s and based on [[Christina Stead]]'s 1945 best-selling novel of the same name, marked her debut in film.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/18132/For-Love-Alone/overview|title=For Love Alone (1986) Overview|work=The New York Times|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> She then appeared in two episodes of the [[List of Hey Dad..! episodes#Season 4 (1990-1991)|fourth season]] of the Australian sitcom ''[[Hey Dad..!]]'' in 1990. After a five-year absence from films, Watts met director [[John Duigan]] during the 1989 premiere of her friend Nicole Kidman's film ''[[Dead Calm (film)|Dead Calm]]'' and he invited her to take a supporting role in his 1991 indie film ''[[Flirting (film)|Flirting]]''.<ref name=biochannel/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iofilm.co.uk/feats/interviews/n/naomi_watts_divorce.shtml |title=Naomi enjoys her shot|publisher=Iofilm.co.uk|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> The film received critical acclaim and was featured on [[Roger Ebert]]'s list of the 10 best films of 1992.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19921231/COMMENTARY/40308026/1023|first=Roger|last=Ebert|title=The Best 10 Movies of 1992 |work=Chicago Sun-Times|date=31 December 1992|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> Also in 1991, she took the part of Frances Heffernan, a girl who struggles to find friends behind the walls of a Sydney Catholic school,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australiantelevision.net/brides-of-christ/episodes.html|title=Brides of Christ: episode guide|work=Australian Television Information Archive's Official Site|publisher=Australian Television Information Archive|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> in the award-winning mini-series ''[[Brides of Christ]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shop.abc.net.au/browse/product.asp?productid=721188|title=Brides of Christ description on Australian Broadcasting Corporation's shop|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=6 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110401034613/http://shop.abc.net.au/browse/product.asp?productid=721188|archivedate=1 April 2011}}</ref> and had a recurring role in the soap opera ''[[Home and Away]]'' as the handicapped [[Julie Gibson (Home and Away)|Julie Gibson]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kent|first=Melissa|work=The Age |location=Australia|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/entertainment/tv--radio/cast-and-fans-of-home-and-away-well-on-the-way-to-belonging-foreverand-ever/2009/02/07/1233423560588.html|title=Cast and fans of Home and Away well on the way to belonging forever and ever|date=8 February 2009|accessdate=28 August 2011}}</ref> Watts was then offered a role in the drama series ''[[A Country Practice]]'' but turned it down, not wanting to \"get stuck on a soap for two or three years\", a decision she later called \"na\u00efve\".<ref name=biochannel/><ref name=interviewmag/>\n\nWatts then took a year off to travel, visiting Los Angeles and being introduced to agents through Kidman.<ref name=mymotto/><ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> Encouraged, Watts decided to move to America, to pursue her career further. In 1993 she had a small role in the [[John Goodman]] film ''[[Matinee (1993 film)|Matinee]]'' and temporarily returned to Australia to star in three Australian films: another of Duigan's pictures, ''[[Wide Sargasso Sea (1993 film)|Wide Sargasso Sea]]''; the drama ''[[The Custodian]]''; and had her first leading role in the film ''[[Gross Misconduct (film)|Gross Misconduct]]'', as a student who accuses one of her teachers (played by [[Jimmy Smits]]) of raping her.<ref name=biochannel/> Watts then moved back to America for good but the difficulty of finding agents, producers and directors willing to hire her during that period frustrated her initial efforts.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> Though her financial situation never led her to taking a job out of the film industry, she experienced problems like being unable to pay the rent of her apartment and losing her medical insurance.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/><ref name=bloomer/> \"At first, everything was fantastic and doors were opened to me. But some people who I met through Nicole [Kidman], who had been all over me, had difficulty remembering my name when we next met. There were a lot of promises, but nothing actually came off. I ran out of money and became quite lonely, but Nic gave me company and encouragement to carry on.\"<ref name=sundaytimes>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidlynch.de/wattssunday.html|title=Film: Naomi Watts interview|work=The Sunday Times|first=Garth|last=Pearce|date=6 January 2002|accessdate=14 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328140104/http://www.davidlynch.de/wattssunday.html|archive-date=28 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|When I came to America there was so much promise of good stuff and I thought, I've got it made here. I'm going to kick ass. Then I went back to Australia and did one or two more jobs. When I returned to Hollywood, all those people who'd been so encouraging before weren't interested. You take all their flattery seriously when you don't know any better. I basically had to start all over again. I get offered some things without auditioning today, but back then they wouldn't even fax me the pages of a script because it was too much of an inconvenience. I had to drive for hours into [[San Fernando Valley|the Valley]] to pick up three bits of paper for some horrendous piece of shit, then go back the next day and line up for two hours to meet the casting director who would barely give me eye contact. It was humiliating.<br>{{endash}}Watts on her early struggles<ref name=interviewmag/>}}\n\nShe then won a supporting role in the futuristic 1995 film ''[[Tank Girl (film)|Tank Girl]]'', winning the role of \"Jet Girl\" after nine auditions.<ref name=tca/> The film was met with mixed reviews and flopped at the box office, although it has gone on to become something of a cult classic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/tank_girl/|title=Tank Girl (1995) on Rotten Tomatoes|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster, Inc|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> Throughout the rest of the decade, she took mostly supporting roles in films<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/naomi-watts/bio/167538|title=Naomi Watts: Biography|work=TV Guide|publisher=TV Guide Online Holdings LLC|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> and occasionally considered leaving the business, but: \"there were always little bites. Whenever I felt I was at the end of my rope, something would come up. Something bad. But for me it was 'work begets work'; that was my motto.\"<ref name=mymotto/><ref name=bloomer>{{cite web|url=http://www.backstage.com/news/late-bloomer_4/|title=Late Bloomer|publisher=Backstage.com|date=24 November 2003 |first=Cassie |last=Carpenter |accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> In 1996, she starred alongside [[Joe Mantegna]], [[Kelly Lynch]] and [[J.T. Walsh]] in [[George Hickenlooper]]'s action-thriller ''Persons Unknown''; alongside [[James Earl Jones]], [[Kevin Kilner]] and [[Ellen Burstyn]] in the period drama ''Timepiece''; in ''Bermuda Triangle'', a TV pilot that was not picked up for a full series, where she played a former documentary filmmaker who disappears in the [[Bermuda Triangle]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eofftv.com/kim_newman_archive/b/bermuda_triangle_1996_review.htm|title=Bermuda Triangle (1996)|work=Encyclopedia of fantastic Film and television|publisher=Kim Newman|accessdate=28 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324092645/http://www.eofftv.com/kim_newman_archive/b/bermuda_triangle_1996_review.htm|archivedate=24 March 2012}}</ref> and as the lead role in ''[[Children of the Corn IV: The Gathering]]'', in which children in a small town become possessed under the command of a wrongfully murdered [[child preacher]].<ref name=tca/>\n\nIn 1997, she starred in the Australian ensemble romantic drama ''[[Under the Lighthouse Dancing]]'' starring [[Jack Thompson (actor)|Jack Thompson]] and [[Jacqueline McKenzie]]. She also played the lead role in the short-lived television series ''[[Sleepwalkers (TV series)|Sleepwalkers]]''.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> In 1998, she starred alongside [[Neil Patrick Harris]] and [[Debbie Reynolds]] in the TV film ''[[The Christmas Wish (film)|The Christmas Wish]]'', played the supporting role of Giulia De Lezze in ''[[Dangerous Beauty]]'',<ref name=biochannel/> and provided some voice work for ''[[Babe: Pig in the City]]''.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> She said in an interview in 2012, \"That really should not be on my r\u00e9sum\u00e9! I think that was early on in the day, when I was trying to beef up my r\u00e9sum\u00e9. I came in and did a couple days' work of voiceovers and we had to suck on [helium] and then do a little mouse voice. But I was one in a hundred, so I'm sure you would never be able to identify my voice. I probably couldn't either!\"<ref name=weirdest>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2012/12/naomi-watts-on-the-impossible-controversy.html|title=Naomi Watts on The Impossible and Her Weirdest Film Credit|publisher=Vulture.com|first=Kyle|last=Buchanan|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref> In 1999, she played Alice in the romantic comedy ''[[Strange Planet]]'' and the Texan student [[Holly Maddux]] in ''[[The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer]]'', which was based on the real life effort to capture [[Ira Einhorn]], who was charged with Maddux's murder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/strange-planet-v181000|title=Strange Planet (1999)|work=AllRovi|accessdate=28 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120718191443/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/strange-planet-v181000|archivedate=18 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-hunt-for-the-unicorn-killer-v180100|title=The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer (1999)|work=AllRovi|accessdate=28 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120724203706/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-hunt-for-the-unicorn-killer-v180100|archivedate=24 July 2012}}</ref> In 2000, while [[David Lynch]] was expanding the rejected pilot of ''[[Mulholland Drive (film)|Mulholland Drive]]'' into a feature film, Watts starred alongside [[Derek Jacobi]], [[Jack Davenport]] and [[Iain Glen]] in the [[BBC]] TV film ''[[The Wyvern Mystery]]'', an adaptation of the novel of the same name by [[Sheridan Le Fanu]] that was broadcast in March of that year.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/>\n\nMuch of her early career is filled with near misses in casting, as she was up for significant roles in films such as 1997's ''[[The Postman (film)|The Postman]]'' and ''[[The Devil's Advocate (1997 film)|The Devil's Advocate]]'' and 2000's ''[[Meet the Parents]]'', which eventually went to other actresses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2006-Ra-Z/Watts-Naomi.html|title=Naomi Watts: Biography|work=Encyclopedia of World Biography|publisher=Advameg, Inc.|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> In an interview in 2012, Watts said, \"I came to New York and auditioned at least five times for ''Meet the Parents''. I think the director liked me but the studio didn't. I heard every piece of feedback you could imagine, and in this case, it was 'not sexy enough'.\"<ref name=dailybeast>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/12/21/naomi-watts-on-the-impossible-personal-tragedy-and-playing-princess-diana.html|title=Naomi Watts on 'The Impossible,' Personal Tragedy, and Playing Princess Diana|newspaper=The Daily Beast|date=21 December 2012|accessdate=14 March 2013|last1=Stern|first1=Marlow}}</ref> Watts recalled her early career in an interview in 2002, saying, \"It is a tough town. I think my spirit has taken a beating. The most painful thing has been the endless auditions. Knowing that you have something to offer, but not being able to show it, is so frustrating. As an unknown, you get treated badly. I auditioned and waited for things I did not have any belief in, but I needed the work and had to accept horrendous pieces of shit.\"<ref name=sundaytimes/> Watts studied the [[Meisner Technique]].\n\n===Rise to fame (2001\u20132002)===\n[[File:Naomi Watts \u00e9s David Lynch--.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Watts with filmmaker [[David Lynch]] at the [[2001 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\n\nIn 1999, director [[David Lynch]] began casting for his psychological thriller ''[[Mulholland Drive (film)|Mulholland Drive]]''. He interviewed Watts after looking at her headshot,<ref name=dailybeast/> without having seen any of her previous work,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Twin Piques|first=Anna|last=David|date=November 2001|journal=Premiere Magazine|pages=80\u201381|volume=15|issue=3}}</ref> and offered her the lead role.<ref name=dailybeast/> Lynch later said about his selection of Watts, \"I saw someone that I felt had a tremendous talent, and I saw someone who had a beautiful soul, an intelligence\u2014possibilities for a lot of different roles, so it was a beautiful full package.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=It's a Road She Knows Well; 'Mulholland Dr.' star Naomi Watts has lived the Hollywood metaphor behind the fabled highway|first=Scarlet|last=Cheng|date=12 October 2001|journal=Los Angeles Times|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/12/entertainment/ca-56239|accessdate=7 July 2011|page=20}}</ref> Conceived as a pilot for a television series, Lynch shot a large portion of it in February 1999, planning to keep it open-ended for a potential series. However, the pilot was rejected. Watts recalled thinking at the time, \"just my dumb luck, that I'm in the only David Lynch programme that never sees the light of day.\"<ref name=mymotto/> Instead, Lynch filmed an ending in October 2000, turning it into a feature film which was picked up for distribution.\n\nThe film, which also starred [[Laura Harring]] and [[Justin Theroux]], was highly acclaimed by critics and would become Watts's breakthrough. She was praised by critics, including Peter Bradshaw from ''[[The Guardian]]'', who said, \"Watts's face metamorphoses miraculously from fresh-faced beauty to a frenzied, teary scowl of ugliness.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2002/jan/04/1 |first=Peter |last=Bradshaw |title=''Mulholland Drive'' review|work=The Guardian|date=4 January 2002|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref> and [[Emanuel Levy]], who wrote, \"...&nbsp;Naomi Watts, in a brilliant performance, a young, wide-eyed and grotesquely cheerful blonde, full of high hopes to make it big in Hollywood.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emanuellevy.com/review/mulholland-drive-3/|first=Emanuel|last=Levy|title=Mulholland Drive review by Emanuel Levy|work=Emanuel Levy|publisher=Emanuel Levy's Official Site|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref> The film premiered at the 2001 [[Cannes Film Festival]] and received a large number of awards and nominations, including the Best Actress Award for Watts from the [[National Society of Film Critics]] and a nomination for Best Actress from the [[American Film Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/mulholland-dr-v246240 |title=Mulholland Dr. (2001) Awards |work=AllRovi |accessdate=7 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110701113344/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/mulholland-dr-v246240 |archivedate=1 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> The surrealist film following the story of the aspiring actress Betty Elms, played by Watts, attracted controversy with its strong lesbian theme.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/2001/10/05/2001-10-05_dangerous_curves_on_lynch_s_.html|first=Jami|last=Bernard|title=Dangerous curves on Lynch's 'Drive'|work=Daily News|publisher=Daily News, L.P.|date=10 April 2001|accessdate=7 July 2011}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/07/23/1027332361018.html|first=Red|last=Symons|title=Man in spirit-led, Mulholland-riddle miracle!|work=The Age|date=6 July 2002|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2001, she starred in two short films, ''Never Date an Actress'' and ''[[Ellie Parker]]'', and the horror film ''[[Down (film)|The Shaft]]'', director [[Dick Maas]]' remake of his 1983 film ''[[De Lift]]''.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> In 2002, she starred in one of the biggest box office hits of that year,<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> ''[[The Ring (2002 film)|The Ring]]'', the English language remake of the [[J-Horror|Japanese horror film]] ''[[Ring (film)|Ringu]]''. Directed by [[Gore Verbinski]], the film, which also starred [[Martin Henderson]] and [[Brian Cox (actor)|Brian Cox]], received favourable reviews and grossed around US$129&nbsp;million domestically (equivalent to US${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|129|2002|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ring.htm|title=The Ring at Box Office Mojo|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref> Watts portrayed [[Rachel Keller]], a journalist investigating the strange deaths of her niece and other teenagers after watching a mysterious videotape, and receiving a phone call announcing their deaths in seven days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ring/|title=The Ring (2002)|work=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> Her performance was praised by critics, including Paul Clinton of ''[[CNN.com]]'', who stated that she \"is excellent in this leading role, which proves that her stellar performance in ''Mulholland Drive'' was not a fluke. She strikes a perfect balance between scepticism and the slow realisation of the truth in regard to the deadly power of the videotape.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2002/SHOWBIZ/Movies/10/18/review.the.ring/index.html|title=Review: 'The Ring' gets under your skin|publisher=CNN |first=Paul|last=Clinton|accessdate=8 December 2010|date=18 October 2002}}</ref> That year, she also starred in ''[[Rabbits (film)|Rabbits]]'', a series of short films directed by David Lynch; alongside several other famous British actors in the black comedy ''[[Plots with a View]]''; and with [[Tim Daly]] in the western ''[[The Outsider (2002 film)|The Outsider]]''.\n\n===Established career (2003\u20132007)===\n[[File:Naomi Watts (6800617073).jpg|alt=|thumb|309x309px|Watts in [[Sydney]] in 2012]]\nIn 2003, Watts took the part of Julia Cook in [[Gregor Jordan]]'s Australian film ''[[Ned Kelly (2003 film)|Ned Kelly]]'' opposite [[Heath Ledger]], [[Orlando Bloom]] and [[Geoffrey Rush]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/ned-kelly-v283385|title=Ned Kelly (2003)|work=AllRovi|accessdate=7 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120719112415/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/ned-kelly-v283385|archivedate=19 July 2012}}</ref> as well as starring in the [[Merchant Ivory Productions|Merchant-Ivory]] film ''[[Le Divorce]]'', portraying Roxeanne de Persand, a poet who is pregnant and abandoned by her husband Charles-Henri de Persand. Roxeanne and her sister Isabel (played by [[Kate Hudson]]) dispute the ownership of a painting by [[Georges de La Tour]] with the family of Charles-Henri's lover. ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a \"C\" rating and lamented Watts's performance: \"I'm disappointed to report that Hudson and Watts have no chemistry as sisters, perhaps because Watts never seems like the expatriate artiste she's supposed to be playing\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Gleiberman|first = Owen |title = Le Divorce | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]]| date = 5 August 2003 | url = https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,472427,00.html |accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nConversely, her performance opposite [[Sean Penn]] and [[Benicio del Toro]] in director [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]]'s 2003 drama ''[[21 Grams]]'' earned Watts numerous award nominations, including an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]], later that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/76nominees.html |title=Nominees & Winners for the 76th Academy Awards |work=Academy Awards- Official Site |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |accessdate=7 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727154929/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/76nominees.html |archivedate=27 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> In the story, told in a non-linear manner, she portrayed Cristina Peck, a grief-stricken woman living a suburban life after the killing of her husband and two children by Jack Jordan (Benicio del Toro), who became involved in a relationship with the critically ill academic mathematician Paul Rivers (Sean Penn). She has said of the nomination, \"It's far beyond what I ever dreamed for \u2013 that would have been too far fetched\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/02/11/1076388374177.html|title=Watts bath to fame|work=The Age |first=Paul|last=Clinton|accessdate=7 July 2011|date=11 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/21-grams-v290208|title=21 Grams (2003) Awards|work=AllRovi|accessdate=7 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110603085706/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/21-grams-v290208|archivedate=3 June 2011}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' praised her: \"Because Ms. Watts reinvents herself with each performance, it's easy to forget how brilliant she is. She has a boldness that comes from a lack of overemphasis, something actresses sometimes do to keep up with Mr. Penn\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B02EEDB153EF93BA25753C1A9659C8B63|first=Elvis|last=Mitchell|title=21 Grams (2003) movie review|work=The New York Times|date=18 October 2003|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref> ''The San Francisco Chronicle'' wrote: \"Watts is riveting, but she's much better in scenes of extreme emotion than in those requiring subtlety.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/chronicle/reviews/movies/21GRAMS.DTL|first=Carla|last=Meyer|title=Gloomy '21 Grams' for weighty souls|work=San Francisco Chronicle|publisher=Hearst Communications Inc.|date=26 November 2003|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Watts starred alongside [[Mark Ruffalo]] in the independent film ''[[We Don't Live Here Anymore]]'',<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> based on short stories by [[Andre Dubus]], which depicts the crisis of two married couples,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/287908/We-Don-t-Live-Here-Anymore/overview|title=We Don't Live Here Anymore (2004)|work=The New York Times|accessdate=7 July 2011|first=A. O.|last=Scott}}</ref> reunited with Sean Penn in ''[[The Assassination of Richard Nixon]]'', playing the wife of the would-be presidential assassin [[Samuel Byck]] (Penn),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-assassination-of-richard-nixon-v304506|title=The Assassination of Richard Nixon|work=AllRovi|accessdate=7 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027221436/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-assassination-of-richard-nixon-v304506|archivedate=27 October 2011}}</ref> and teamed up with [[Jude Law]] and [[Dustin Hoffman]] in [[David O. Russell]]'s ensemble comedy ''[[I Heart Huckabees]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.tvguide.com/heart-huckabees/cast/137660|title=I Heart Huckabees: Cast & Details|work=TV Guide|publisher=TV Guide Online Holdings LLC|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref> She headlined and produced the semi-autobiographical drama ''[[Ellie Parker]]'' (2005), which depicted the struggle of an Australian actress in Hollywood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/ellie-parker-v318905|title=Ellie Parker Synopsis|work=AllRovie|accessdate=7 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120730014257/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/ellie-parker-v318905|archivedate=30 July 2012}}</ref> The film began as a short film that was screened at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] in 2001 and was expanded into a feature-length production over the next four years. Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] praised Watts's performance: \"The character is played by Watts with courage, fearless observation and a gift for timing that is so uncanny it can make points all by itself.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20051215/REVIEWS/51205003/1023|title=Ellie Parker|date=16 December 2005|first=Roger|last=Ebert|work=Chicago-Sun Times|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nWatts starred in the sequel to ''The Ring'', ''[[The Ring Two]]'' (2005), which despite a negative critical response,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ring_two/|title=The Ring Two (2005)|work=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> made over US$161&nbsp;million worldwide gross (equivalent to US${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|161|2005|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ring2.htm|title=The Ring Two|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> In 2005, Watts also headlined the [[King Kong (2005 film)|remake]] of ''[[King Kong (1933 film)|King Kong]]'' as Ann Darrow. She was the first choice for the role, portrayed by [[Fay Wray]] in the original film, with no other actors considered.<ref name=beg>{{cite book | author = [[Brian Sibley]] | title = Peter Jackson: A Film-maker's Journey | publisher = [[HarperCollins]] | pages = 526\u2013542 | year = 2006 | isbn = 978-0-00-717558-1 | location = London}}</ref> In preparation for her role, Watts met with Wray,<ref name=fi>{{cite news|author=Ian Spelling |url=http://www.scifi.com/sfw/issue452/interview.html |title=Peter Jackson proves with King Kong that the director, not the beast, is the true eighth wonder of the world |work=[[Science Fiction Weekly]] |date=December 2005 |accessdate=1 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060619091002/http://www.scifi.com/sfw/issue452/interview.html |archivedate=19 June 2006 |df= }}</ref> who was to make a [[cameo appearance]] and say the final line of dialogue, but she died during pre-production at the age of 96.<ref name=Ray>{{cite book | author = Paul A. Woods | title = Peter Jackson: From Gore to Mordor | publisher = Plexus Books | year = 2005 | isbn = 978-0-85965-356-5 | pages = 176\u2013187 | chapter = Kong Cometh! | location = London}}</ref> ''King Kong'' proved to be Watts's most commercially successful film yet. Helmed by ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'' director [[Peter Jackson]], the film won high praise and [[revenue|grossed]] US$550&nbsp;million worldwide (equivalent to US${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|550|2005|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=kingkong05.htm|title=King Kong BoxOffice|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=naomiwatts.htm|title=Naomi Watts BoxOffice|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> The ''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]'' praised her performance: \"The third act becomes a star-crossed, \"Beauty and the Beast\" parable far more operatic and tragic than anything the original filmmakers could have imagined, exquisitely pantomimed by Watts with a poignancy and passion that rates Oscar consideration.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=A bigger, better 'Kong'|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/ae/movies/article/A-bigger-better-Kong-1189771.php|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|accessdate=7 August 2011|date=13 December 2005|first=William|last=Arnold}}</ref> Alongside the movie, she reprised her role as Darrow in the [[Peter Jackson's King Kong|video game adaptation]] of ''King Kong''.<ref>[https://www.gamespot.com/articles/king-kong-cast-bananas-for-game/1100-6140029/ King Kong cast bananas for game] Retrieved 17 May 2019]</ref> She was nominated for Best Performance by a Female at the [[Spike Video Game Awards#2005 Awards|2005 Spike Video Game Awards]] for her role as Darrow, as well as winning the Best Cast award with the rest of the game's voice cast.<ref>[https://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=6947/ Spike TV Announces Award Nominees, Presenters] Retrieved 15 May 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.awn.com/news/spike-tv-video-game-awards-2005-winners-announced/ Spike TV Video Game Awards 2005 Winners Announced] Retrieved 15 May 2019</ref> Her other 2005 film release was [[Marc Forster]]'s psychological thriller ''[[Stay (2005 film)|Stay]]'', alongside [[Ewan McGregor]], [[Ryan Gosling]] and [[Bob Hoskins]].<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> At this point in her career, Watts stated the following:\n\n{{cquote|You'd better know why you're here as an actor&nbsp;... I'm here to work out my shit, what my problems are and know who I am, so by cracking open these characters perhaps that shines a light on it a little bit better&nbsp;... I know myself. I mean, of course I know myself better but the journey and search continue because hopefully we're evolving and growing all the time.<ref name=Girl.com.au>{{cite web |url=http://www.girl.com.au/naomi-watts-king-kong-interview.htm |title=Naomi Watts \u2013 King Kong Interview |publisher=girl.com.au |last=Fischer|first=Paul |accessdate=July 2, 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nThe romantic drama ''[[The Painted Veil (2006 film)|The Painted Veil]]'' (2006), with [[Edward Norton]] and [[Liev Schreiber]], featured Watts as the daughter of a lawyer who marries a man for his reputation as a physician and [[bacteriology|bacteriologist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-painted-veil-v323785|title=The Painted Veil|work=AllRovie|publisher=Rovi Corpotation|accessdate=7 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118202342/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-painted-veil-v323785|archivedate=18 January 2012}}</ref> Comparing her portrayal with [[Greta Garbo]]'s in the original movie, the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' wrote \"Watts makes the role work on her own terms \u2013 her Kitty is more desperate, more foolish, more miserable and more driven . . . and her spiritual journey is greater.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/12/29/DDG4MN9CKF1.DTL&type=movies|title=Will you marry me? And live unhappily ever after in China?|first=Mick|last=LaSalle|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=29 December 2006|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> Watts also provided the voice of a small role, Suzie Rabbit, in David Lynch's [[psychological thriller]] ''[[Inland Empire (film)|Inland Empire]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/inland-empire-v326849 |title=Inland Empire |work=AllRovie |accessdate=7 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110627113340/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/inland-empire-v326849 |archivedate=27 June 2011 |df= }}</ref> That year, she was announced as the new face of the jewellers [[David Yurman]] and completed a photoshoot which was featured in the 2007 [[Pirelli Calendar]].<ref name=people/>\n\nWatts portrayed a Russian-British midwife who delivers the baby of a drug-addicted 14-year old prostitute in [[David Cronenberg]]'s ''[[Eastern Promises]]'' (2007), with [[Viggo Mortensen]].<ref name=Eastern>{{cite web|url=http://www.viewlondon.co.uk/films/eastern-promises-film-review-20671.html|title=Eastern Promises|work=View London|first=Matthew|last=Turner|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> In its review, ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' magazine observed that she \"brings a wounded radiance to the overcurious midwife Anna. Though it's a bit of a one-note role, it's a note she's long specialised in, a kind of flustered moral aggrievement\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2007/09/eastern_promises.html|title=David Cronenberg's Eastern Promises reviewed.|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=13 September 2007}}</ref> ''Eastern Promises'' grossed US$56&nbsp;million worldwide, (equivalent to US${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|56|2005|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=easternpromises.htm|title=Eastern Promises|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Eastern-Promises|title=Eastern Promises|publisher=The-numbers.com|accessdate=27 October 2015}}</ref> She was one of the producers and starred as a mother who, along with her family, are held hostage by a pair of sociopathic teenagers in [[Michael Haneke]]'s ''[[Funny Games (2007 film)|Funny Games]]'' (also 2007), a remake of Haneke's 1997 film [[Funny Games (1997 film)|of the same name]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/827/827704p3.html|title=Top 10 Films at the London Film Festival|last=Tilly|first=Chris|date=17 October 2007|work=IGN UK|accessdate=25 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025040623/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/827/827704p3.html|archivedate=25 October 2007}}</ref> The director said that he agreed to make the film on condition that he be allowed to cast Watts, according to UK's ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/3672273/Film-review-Funny-Games.html|title=Film review: Funny Games|author=Sukhdev Sandhu|date=4 April 2008|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Film-Review/eastern-promises-naomi-watts-interview|title=Eastern Promises \u2013 Naomi Watts interview|publisher=IndieLondon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moviesonline.ca/movienews_14320.html|title=Naomi Watts Interview, Funny Games|publisher=MoviesOnline}}</ref> but it went largely unnoticed by critics and audiences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1175174-funny_games/|title=Funny Games|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|date=14 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=funnygames.htm|title=Funny Games (2008)|publisher=Box Office Mojo}}</ref> Nevertheless, ''[[Newsweek]]'' felt that Watts \"hurls herself into her physically demanding role with heroic conviction\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Ansen|first=David|url=http://www.newsweek.com/rottweiler-now-english-83715|title=A Rottweiler, Now in English|work=Newsweek|date=15 March 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Biographical and independent films (2009\u20132014)===\nAfter a short hiatus from acting following the birth of her two children, Watts returned to acting in 2009, starring alongside [[Clive Owen]] in the political thriller ''[[The International (2009 film)|The International]]'', in which she played a [[Manhattan]] assistant district attorney who partners with an [[Interpol]] agent to take down a [[merchant bank]].<ref name=\"naomifilm\">{{Cite news|first=Kit |last=Borys |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i47021a7b93e54966cb8af7e263c109c8 |title=Watts has passport for Col's 'Int'l' |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=13 July 2007 |accessdate=8 December 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715164550/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i47021a7b93e54966cb8af7e263c109c8 |archivedate=15 July 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The production was a moderate commercial success,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/international/|title=The International (2009)|work=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> grossing over US$60&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|60|2009|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}) worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=international.htm|title=The International|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> She next appeared in the drama ''[[Mother and Child (2009 film)|Mother and Child]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2009/film/markets-festivals/mother-and-child-2-1200476120/|title=Review: 'Mother and Child'|first=Todd|last=McCarthy|date=16 September 2009|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> portraying the role of a lawyer who never knew her biological mother.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mother and Child \u2013 Cast and Crew|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/mother-and-child-v499195|work=Allrovie|publisher=Rovie Corporation|accessdate=8 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111129035518/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/mother-and-child-v499195 |archivedate=29 November 2011}}</ref> ''ViewLondon'' found her to be \"terrific as [her character], delivering a powerful performance that [...] isn't afraid to be unsympathetic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viewlondon.co.uk/films/mother-and-child-film-review-44349.html|title=Mother and Child|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> She was nominated for the [[Australian Film Institute International Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] award at the [[Australian Film Institute Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.org.au/AFI_Award_Winners_and_Nominees/AM/ContentManagerNet/ContentDisplay.aspx?ContentID=11996&Section=AFI_Award_Winners_and_Nominees|title=2010 Samsung Mobile AFI Awards Nominees & Winners|work=AFI Awards|publisher=Australian Film Institute|accessdate=8 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613074712/http://www.afi.org.au/AFI_Award_Winners_and_Nominees/AM/ContentManagerNet/ContentDisplay.aspx?ContentID=11996&Section=AFI_Award_Winners_and_Nominees|archivedate=13 June 2011}}</ref> and for the [[Independent Spirit Award]] for [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Supporting Female|Best Supporting Female]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/mother-and-child-v499195|title=Mother and Child \u2013 Awards|work=Allrovie|publisher=Rovie Corporation|accessdate=8 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111129035518/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/mother-and-child-v499195|archivedate=29 November 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Naomi Watts.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Watts at the [[Deauville American Film Festival]] in 2011]]\nHer next film, the [[Woody Allen]] [[dramedy]] ''[[You Will Meet a Tall Dark Stranger]]'', opened at the [[2010 Cannes Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/11019455/year/2010.html |title=Cannes Film Festival \u2013 Selection List |publisher=Le Festival International du Film de Cannes|accessdate=8 October 2010}}</ref> and saw her portray Sally, a woman who has a troubled marriage with author Roy (played by [[Josh Brolin]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/you-will-meet-a-tall-dark-stranger|title=You Will Meet a Tall Dark Stranger|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=8 October 2010}}</ref> It made over US$26&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|26|2010|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=talldarkstranger.htm|title=You Will Meet a Tall Dark Stranger|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> Her portrayal of [[Valerie Plame]] in the biographical thriller ''[[Fair Game (2010 film)|Fair Game]]'' followed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/11022739/year/2010.html|title=Fair Game|publisher=Le Festival International du Film de Cannes|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> and marked the third pairing of Watts with Sean Penn after ''21 Grams'' and ''The Assassination of Richard Nixon''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118000481.html?categoryid=1236&cs=1|first=Michael|last=Fleming |title=Sean Penn in talks for Plame 'Game' |work=Variety|date=23 February 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemagazine.com/reviews/theatrical/2010-05-fair-game?q=fair+game|title=A taut retelling of the scandal that exposed Valerie Plame|work=Box Office magazine|publisher=Box Office Media|date=22 May 2010|accessdate=8 August 2011|first=Pete|last=Hammond|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921025527/http://www.boxofficemagazine.com/reviews/theatrical/2010-05-fair-game?q=fair+game|archivedate=21 September 2011}}</ref> The film earned Watts a [[Satellite Award]] nomination for [[Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Best Actress]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://extratv.warnerbros.com/2010/11/winters_bone_tops_independent_spirit_award_nominations.php |title='Winter's Bone' Tops Indie Spirit Award Noms |work=Warner Bros.|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> In 2011, she appeared with [[Daniel Craig]] and [[Rachel Weisz]] in [[Jim Sheridan]]'s psychological horror film ''[[Dream House (2011 film)|Dream House]]'', as the neighbour of a murdered family,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/dream-house-trailer-starring-daniel-craig-and-naomi-watts|title=Dream House Trailer Starring Daniel Craig and Naomi Watts|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=20 July 2011|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dream_house_2011/|title=Dream House|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> and with [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] in [[Clint Eastwood]]'s biographical drama ''[[J. Edgar]]'', playing secretary [[Helen Gandy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/03/idUS53343025320110803|title='J. Edgar' Slips into Theaters Nov. 9 With Limited Bow|date=3 August 2011|first=Joshua|last=Weinstein|work=The Wrap News, Inc|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2011/11/box-office-j-edgar-immortals-jack-jill.html|title=Movie Projector: 'Immortals' poised to conquer box office|work=Los Angeles Times|date=10 November 2011}}</ref> While ''Dream House'' flopped,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3282&p=.htm|title=Weekend Report: 'Dolphin Tale' Leaps Into Lead \u2013 Box Office Mojo|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref>  ''J. Edgar'' had a more favorable reception.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=jedgar.htm|title=J. Edgar (2011)|publisher=Box Office Mojo}}</ref>\n\nWatts starred in ''[[The Impossible (2012 film)|The Impossible]]'' (2012), a [[disaster film|disaster]] [[drama film|drama]] based on the true story of [[Mar\u00eda Bel\u00f3n]] and her family's experience of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|2004 Indian Ocean tsunami]]; she played the lead role, with her name changed to Maria Bennett. The film was a critical darling, had the highest-grossing opening weekend for a film in Spain,<ref>https://www.boxofficemojo.com/intl/spain/?yr=2012&wk=43&p=new</ref> and made US$180.2 million (equivalent to ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|180|2012|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}) globally.<ref>{{cite news | title=The Impossible | url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20121219/REVIEWS/121219990/1023 | work=Chicago Sun-Times | date=19 December 2012}}</ref> Deborah Young of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' stated that \"Watts packs a huge charge of emotion as the battered, ever-weakening Maria whose tears of pain and fear never appear fake or idealised,\"<ref name=\"Young\">{{cite web |author=Young, Deborah |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/impossible-naomi-watts-ewan-mcgregor-369260 |title=The Impossible: Toronto Review |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=10 September 2012 |accessdate=15 October 2012}}</ref> while Justin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' magazine remarked that she \"has few equals at conveying physical and emotional extremis, something she again demonstrates in a mostly bedridden role.\"<ref name=\"Chang\">{{cite web \n|author=Chang, Justin |url=https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117948281?refcatid=31 |title=The Impossible |work=Variety |publisher=Reed Elsevier Properties Inc |date=10 September 2012 |accessdate=15 October 2012}}</ref> Damon Wise of ''[[The Guardian]]'' felt that \"Watts is both brave and vulnerable, and her scenes with the young Lucas&nbsp;[...] are among the film's best.\"<ref name=\"Wise\">{{cite news |author=Wise, Damon |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/sep/12/impossible-review |title=The Impossible |newspaper=The Guardian |date=12 September 2012 |accessdate=15 October 2012}}</ref> Watts went on to be nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Academy Award]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe]] and [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role|Screen Actors Guild Award]] for Best Actress.<ref name=allmovie>{{cite web |title=Naomi Watts|work=[[Allmovie]] |url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/naomi-watts-p75056/awards |accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Adore (film)|Adore]]'' (2013), Watts starred with [[Robin Wright]] as two childhood friends who fall in love with each other's sons. On the film, critics concluded that Watts and Wright \"give it their all, but they can't quite make ''Adore'''s trashy, absurd plot believable\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/adore_2013/|title=Adore|date=6 September 2013}}</ref> She obtained the [[Film Critics Circle of Australia|FCCA Award]] for Best Actress in 2014 for her role. The anthology comedy ''[[Movie 43]]'' (2013) featured Watts as a devoted mother, alongside Liev Schreiber.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmofilia.com/movie-43-tv-spot-no3-130141/|title=MOVIE 43 TV Spot No3 \u2013 FilmoFilia|first=Aleksandar|last=Popovic|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> ''Movie 43'' was universally panned by critics, with [[Richard Roeper]] calling it \"the ''[[Citizen Kane]]'' of awful\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/movie-43-2013|title=Movie 43 Movie Review & Film Summary (2013) \u2013 Roger Ebert|first=Richard|last=Roeper|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Laurie Collyer]]'s independent drama ''[[Sunlight Jr.]]'' (2013), Watts starred with [[Matt Dillon]] as a struggling working-class couple.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/sunlight-jr-tribeca-review-443635|title=Sunlight Jr.: Tribeca Review|author=Frank Scheck|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribecafilm.com/stories/5-norman-reedus-performances-sunlight-jr-the-walking-dead|title=5 Norman Reedus Performances You Need to Seek Out \u2013 Tribeca|accessdate=27 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822011518/https://tribecafilm.com/stories/5-norman-reedus-performances-sunlight-jr-the-walking-dead|archive-date=22 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/urbanite-1.812039/movie-review-sunlight-jr-3-stars-1.6437713 |title=Movie review: 'Sunlight Jr.' \u2013 3 stars |last=Levin |first=Robert |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20141201234719/http://www.newsday.com/urbanite-1.812039/movie-review-sunlight-jr-3-stars-1.6437713 |archivedate=1 December 2014 |date=14 November 2013 |df= }}</ref> ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', praising Watts and Dillon, wrote in its review for the film that they are \"formidable actors at the top of their game here [...] exhibiting a remarkable chemistry\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Sunlight-Jr-review-Love-in-dismal-surroundings-4983883.php|title='Sunlight Jr.' review: Love in dismal surroundings|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=14 November 2013}}</ref> Watts portrayed the title role in [[Oliver Hirschbiegel]]'s ''[[Diana (film)|Diana]]'' (her last 2013 film),<ref name=allmovie/> a biographical drama about the last two years of the life of [[Diana, Princess of Wales]]. Released amid much controversy given its subject, the film was a critical and commercial flop.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-23985665|title=Diana film slammed by British press|work=BBC News|date=6 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/diana_2013/|title=Diana|date=1 November 2013|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes}}</ref> [[James Berardinelli]] found the film to be a \"dull, pointless\" production and remarked that while Watts did a \"decent job encapsulating the look and feel of Diana\", her portrayal was \"a two-dimensional recreation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/diana|title=Diana \u2013 Reelviews Movie Reviews|first=James|last=Berardinelli|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]]'s dark comedy ''[[Birdman (film)|Birdman or (The Unexpected Virtue of Ignorance)]]'' (2014) featured Watts as the actress of a play mounted by a faded Hollywood actor (played by [[Michael Keaton]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/naomi-watts-trades-oscarbait-for-a-lighter-career-20141030-11dzto.html.|title=Naomi Watts trades Oscar-bait for a lighter career|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=30 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/10/birdman-venice-film-festival-opening-night|title=Birdman to hatch on opening night of Venice film festival|first=Xan|last=Brooks|date=10 July 2014|accessdate=27 September 2016 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3926&p=.htm |title=Weekend Report: 'Fury' Topples 'Gone Girl,' 'Birdman' Soars in Limited Release \u2013 Box Office Mojo |accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/birdman_2014/?search=birdman|title=Birdman|date=17 October 2014|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes}}</ref> The film was the subject of widespread acclaim,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Birdman-review-Inarritu-s-fine-showbiz-5842625.php|title='Birdman' review: Inarritu's fine showbiz satire of ex-superhero|accessdate=27 September 2016|date=23 October 2014}}</ref> and won four awards at the [[87th Academy Awards]] including Best Picture;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/oscar-winners-2015-academy-award-winner-list-1201439020/|title=Oscar Winners 2015: Complete List|first=Variety|last=Staff|date=23 February 2015|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> Watts and the other cast members earned the [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Cast in a Motion Picture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-sag-awards-2015-birdman-wins-cast-motion-picture-story.html|title=SAG Awards 2015: 'Birdman' wins for cast in a motion picture|first=Los Angeles|last=Times|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref>  Her other two awaiting projects were screened at the [[2014 Toronto International Film Festival]]. The dramedy ''[[St. Vincent (film)|St. Vincent]]'' starred Watts as a Russian prostitute. She learnt the accent by spending time with Russian women in a [[West Village]] spa during a six-week period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/naomi-watts-on-preparing-for-st-vincent-with-bill-murray-and-melissa-mccarthy|title=Naomi Watts on how she conquered fear of working with Bill Murray|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> ''Los Angeles Times'' reported a dividing reaction towards her performance, asserting that her part \"put off some critics with its outrageousness\", but \"earned plenty of plaudits too\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-naomi-watts-comedies-demolition-st-vincent-birdman-20141029-story.html#page=1|title=Naomi Watts chooses comedic roles to lighten up her career|date=29 October 2014|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> Watts nabbed a Screen Actors Guild Award nomination for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role|Outstanding Supporting Actress]]. In ''[[While We're Young (film)|While We're Young]]'', Watts starred with [[Ben Stiller]] as a New York City-based married couple who begin hanging out with a couple in their 20s. That film was an [[arthouse]] success and Watts received praise for her on-screen chemistry with Stiller.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/were-young-toronto-review-730802|title='While We're Young': Toronto Review|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/festivals/toronto-film-festival-while-were-young-1201299916/|title=Toronto Film Review: 'While We're Young'|first=Peter|last=Debruge|date=7 September 2014|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/27/movies/review-in-while-were-young-a-coupling-of-gen-x-and-y.html|title=Review: In 'While We're Young,' a Coupling of Gen X and Y|date=27 March 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=27 September 2016|last1=Scott|first1=A. O.}}</ref>\n\n===Film and television balance (2015\u2013present)===\n[[File:Naomi Watts Cannes 2015 2.jpg|thumb|upright|right| Watts at the [[2015 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\n\nWatts played rebel leader [[List of The Divergent trilogy characters#Evelyn Johnson-Eaton|Evelyn Johnson-Eaton]] in ''[[The Divergent Series: Insurgent|Insurgent]]'' (2015), the second film in ''[[The Divergent Series]]'', which is based on [[Veronica Roth]]'s best-selling [[Divergent (novel)|young adult novel of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Jessica Derschowitz|title=Naomi Watts joins cast of \"Divergent\" sequels \"Insurgent,\" \"Allegiant\"|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/naomi-watts-joins-cast-of-divergent-sequels-insurgent-allegiant/|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=30 June 2014|date=4 June 2014}}</ref> Despite mixed reviews, the film was a commercial success, grossing US$274.5&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref name=\"BOOM\">{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=insurgent.htm |title=The Divergent Series: Insurgent (2015) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teen.com/2015/03/18/movies/insurgent-movie-bad-reviews/|title=33 Horrible Insurgent Reviews That'll Piss Fans the Eff Off|accessdate=20 March 2015|date=18 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827003628/http://www.teen.com/2015/03/18/movies/insurgent-movie-bad-reviews/|archive-date=27 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Watts reprised her role in the series' third instalment, ''[[The Divergent Series: Allegiant|Allegiant]]'', released on 18 March 2016, to negative reviews and lackluster box office sales.<ref name=Variety>{{cite web|first1=Marc |last1=Graser |first2=Tatiana |last2=Siegel |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117974282.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|title=Naomi Watts set for 'Birds' remake|work=Variety|date=18 October 2007|accessdate=21 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://downriversundaytimes.com/2014/08/04/celebrity-extra-262/|title=Celebrity Extra|last=Elavsky|first=Cindy|publisher=[[King Features]]|date=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nWatts starred in [[Gus Van Sant]]'s mystery drama ''[[The Sea of Trees]]'', opposite [[Matthew McConaughey]], as the wife of an American man who attempts suicide in [[Mount Fuji]]'s \"[[Suicide Forest]]\". The film premiered at the [[2015 Cannes Film Festival]] where it competed for the [[Palme d'Or]], but was heavily panned by both critics and audiences, who reportedly booed and laughed during its screening.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gus Van Sant's 'Sea of Trees' Booed at Cannes Premiere|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/gus-van-sants-sea-of-trees-booed-at-cannes-premiere-1201497795/|accessdate=15 May 2015|work=Variety|date=15 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Reinstein|first1=Mara|title=Matthew McConaughey's Film The Sea of Trees Booed, Laughed at During Cannes Film Festival|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/matthew-mcconaugheys-the-sea-of-trees-booed-at-cannes-film-festival-2015165|work=Us Weekly|accessdate=15 May 2015|date=15 May 2015}}</ref> Critic Richard Mowe stated the audience reaction should \"give the film's creative team pause for reflection about exactly where they went so badly awry.\"<ref name=\"The Sea of Trees 2015 Review\">{{cite web|last1=Mowe|first1=Richard|title=The Sea of Trees (2015) Review|url=http://www.eyeforfilm.co.uk/review/the-sea-of-trees-2015-film-review-by-richard-mowe|publisher=eyeforefilm.co.uk|accessdate=15 May 2015|date=15 May 2015}}</ref> Justin Chang of ''Variety'' also criticised the film, but commended Watts's performance for being \"solidly moving and sometimes awesomely passive-aggressive.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chang|first1=Justin|title=Cannes Film Review: 'The Sea of Trees'|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/the-sea-of-trees-review-matthew-mcconaughey-cannes-1201495483/|work=Variety|accessdate=15 May 2015|date=15 May 2015}}</ref> ''The Sea of Trees'' did not find an audience in theaters.<ref>https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=theseaoftrees.htm</ref>\n\nLike ''St. Vincent'' and ''While We're Young'' the previous year, Watts had two starring vehicles \u2014''[[Demolition (2015 film)|Demolition]]'' and ''[[Three Generations]]''\u2014 screening at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]], in 2015. In ''Demolition'', directed by [[Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]] and opposite [[Jake Gyllenhaal]], Watts played a customer service representative and the interest of a grieving [[investment banker]] (Gyllenhaal).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/demolition_2016/|title=Demolition}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=demolition.htm|title=Demolition (2016) \u2013 Box Office Mojo}}</ref> ''The Wrap'' felt that she \"empathetically captures [her] harried single mom\" role as she played \"both the wit and the sadness with grace\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/demolition-review-jake-gyllenhaal/|title='Demolition' Review: Jake Gyllenhaal Grapples With Delayed Grief in Dark Dramedy|date=8 April 2016}}</ref> In ''Three Generations'', directed by [[Gaby Dellal]], she appeared with [[Susan Sarandon]] and [[Elle Fanning]] as the mother of a young [[transgender]] man (Fanning). Pulled from the schedule days before its intended initial release,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/09/about-ray-susan-sarandon-elle-fanning-transgender-film-release-date-change-1201528419/|title='About Ray' Pushed From This Weekend's Release Schedule By TWC|first=Anita Busch, Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=15 September 2015}}</ref> the film subsequently opened on selected theatres in May 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/weinstein-finally-puts-transgender-teen-drama-three-generations-back-schedule-973463|title=Weinstein Co. Finally Puts Transgender Teen Drama 'Three Generations' Back on Schedule (Exclusive)|last=Siegel|first=Tatiana|date=13 February 2017|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\nWatts played Linda, the second wife of heavyweight boxer [[Chuck Wepner]] (played by Liev Schreiber) in the biographical [[sport film|sport drama]] ''[[The Bleeder]]'' (2016), revolving around the life of Wepner and his 1975 fight with [[Muhammad Ali]]. ''Variety'' wrote in its review: \"Slightly out of place as the feisty bartender who gives Wepner a second chance at his downest and outest, a spirited Naomi Watts nonetheless gives proceedings her best [[Amy Adams]] in ''[[The Fighter]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/the-bleeder-review-liev-schreiber-1201850979/|title=Film Review: 'The Bleeder'|first=Guy|last=Lodge|date=2 September 2016}}</ref> She headlined the thriller ''[[Shut In (2016 film)|Shut In]]'' (also 2016), playing a psychologist insolated with her child in a rural house during a winter storm. The film received largely negative reviews and made US$8&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/shut_in|title=Shut In}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=shutin.htm|title=Shut In (2016) \u2013 Box Office Mojo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=shutin.htm|title=Shut In (2016) \u2013 International Box Office Results \u2013 Box Office Mojo}}</ref>\n\nWatts appeared in ''[[Twin Peaks (season 3)|Twin Peaks]]'', a limited event television series and a continuation of the [[Twin Peaks|1990 show of the same name]]. It was broadcast on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] in 2017, to critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/twin-peaks-naomi-watts-tom-sizemore-david-lynch-cast-showtime-1201694524/|title=Twin Peaks: Naomi Watts|publisher=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=1 February 2016|date=15 May 2015}}</ref> Watts starred as \"a therapist who begins to develop dangerous and intimate relationships with the people in her patients' lives\" in the [[Netflix]] drama series ''[[Gypsy (TV series)|Gypsy]]'' (also 2017), and served as one of its executive producers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/08/billy-crudup-cast-netflix-psychological-thriller-series-gypsy-1201804855/|title=Billy Crudup To Star in Netflix Drama Series 'Gypsy'|publisher=Deadline Hollywood|date=17 August 2016|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/naomi-watts-star-gypsy-netflix-series-1201739078/|title=Naomi Watts To Star in Netflix Psychological Thriller Series 'Gypsy'|publisher=Deadline Hollywood|date=18 April 2016|accessdate=18 April 2016}}</ref> While response was mixed, ''Gypsy'' was cancelled by Netflix after one season.<ref>{{cite web|title='Gypsy' Canceled By Netflix After 1 Season|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/gypsy-canceled-netflix-naomi-watts-one-season-1202146744/|publisher=Deadline Hollywood|date=11 August 2017}}</ref> In ''[[The Book of Henry]]'' (2017), Watts portrayed the mother of young genius who plans save the girl next door from abuse. The film polarized critics and audiences, but ''Rolling Stone'' described her as \"a plus in any movie\" and found her to be \"excellent\" in the role.<ref>https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/the-book-of-henry-review-boy-meets-girl-ends-up-in-wtf-tearjerker-thriller-199301/</ref> In her other 2017 film, ''[[The Glass Castle (film)|The Glass Castle]]'', an adaptation of [[Jeannette Walls]]' best selling memoir of the same name, Watts played the nonconformist mother of the author.<ref>https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=theglasscastle.htm</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Watts portrayed [[Gretchen Carlson]] in the Showtime miniseries ''[[The Loudest Voice]]'' based on the book ''[[The Loudest Voice in the Room]]'' about [[Roger Ailes]]'s sexual harassment of Carlson.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\">{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=Russell Crowe To Star As Roger Ailes In Limited Series Greenlighted By Showtime |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/russell-crowe-star-roger-ailes-showtime-limited-series-the-loudest-voice-in-the-room-1202416042/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=23 August 2018 |date=25 June 2018}}</ref> She was cast in the ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' spin-off ''Bloodmoon'' as \"a charismatic socialite hiding a dark secret\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/game-of-thrones-prequel-pilot-naomi-watts-hbo-1202977630/|title='Game of Thrones' Prequel Casts Naomi Watts in Lead Role|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|date=30 October 2018|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=31 October 2018|last2=Otterson|first2=Joe}}</ref> but development on the series was cancelled in October 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/game-thrones-naomi-watts-led-prequel-dead-at-hbo-1250795|title='Game of Thrones': Naomi Watts-Led Prequel Dead at HBO|last1=Wigler|first1=Josh|date=29 October 2019|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=29 October 2019|last2=Lesley|first2=Goldberg}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn 2006, Watts became a goodwill ambassador for [[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS]], which helps raise awareness of issues related to the disease. She has used her high profile and celebrity to call attention to the needs of people living with this disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/media/unaids/contentassets/documents/aboutunaids/unaidsgoodwillambassadors/GWA_Watts_en.pdf|title=UNAIDS goodwill ambassador Naomi Watts|work=UNAIDS|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=28 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013042105/http://www.unaids.org/en/media/unaids/contentassets/documents/aboutunaids/unaidsgoodwillambassadors/GWA_Watts_en.pdf|archivedate=13 October 2011}}</ref> Watts has in campaigns for fundraising, events and activities, including the 21st Annual AIDS Walk.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.acqc.org/pdf/Voices5_sum_06.pdf|title=UNAIDS goodwill ambassador Naomi Watts|work=ACQC Voices|publisher=AIDS Center of Queens County|date=Summer 2006|accessdate=28 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706113953/http://acqc.org/pdf/Voices5_sum_06.pdf|archivedate=6 July 2011}}</ref> On 1 December 2009, Watts met with [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|United Nations Secretary-General]] [[Ban Ki-moon]] at a public event commemorating World AIDS Day 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.amfar.org/community/article.aspx?id=8226|title=Light for rights: World AIDS day 2009|work=The Foundation for AIDS Research|publisher=The Foundation for AIDS Research's Official Site|date=3 December 2009|accessdate=28 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Watts attended a charity polo match in New York City along with Australian actors [[Hugh Jackman]] and [[Isla Fisher]], which was intended to raise money to help victims of the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/hugh-jackman-isla-fisher-and-naomi-watts-attend-charity-polo-match-in-new-york/story-e6frewz0-1226070384290|first=Kate|last=McMahon|title=Hugh Jackman, Isla Fisher and Naomi Watts attend charity polo match in New York|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=6 June 2011|accessdate=28 July 2011}}</ref> In 2012, she became an  ambassador for [[Pantene]]'s [[Pantene Beautiful Lengths|Beautiful Lengths]], a program that donates real-hair wigs to women with cancer. She has visited the [[St Vincent's Hospital, Sydney|St Vincent's Hospital]] in [[Sydney]] to meet some of the women the program helps.<ref>https://www.bodyandsoul.com.au/health/celebrity-profiles/naomi-watts-on-health-fitness-and-motherhood/news-story/406d64e3a8dda46793f9e0ae77a2c143</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Watts collaborated with [[Sportscraft]] and children's charity [[Barnardos]] to produce a range of namesake coats, with a percentage of sales going to the charity,<ref>https://www.vogue.com.au/fashion/news/this-is-the-most-valuable-beauty-lesson-naomi-watts-learnt-from-her-mum/news-story/c5d7e416f98accc66fb81753164d7351</ref> and was one the public figures photographed by Italian photographer Fabrizio Ferri for [[Bulgari]]'s digital campaign \"Raise Your Hand\".<ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/declaneytan/2016/07/11/naomi-watts-meg-ryan-and-other-celebrities-raise-their-hand-for-charity/#cab12e258fa7</ref> In November 2018, she hosted the Worldwide Orphans 14th Annual Gala in NYC, and teamed up with [[McDonald's]], to serve as a McHappy Day ambassador, making a special appearance and stepping behind the counter in Haberfield, Sydney.<ref>https://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/actress-naomi-watts-heading-to-australia-as-mchapp/3553288/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Naomi Watts, Liev Schreiber.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Watts with her then-boyfriend [[Liev Schreiber]] in 2012]] \n\nWatts is pictured in her mother's arms with her father, brother, the band and other crew members, in the hardback/softcover edition of Pink Floyd drummer [[Nick Mason]]'s autobiography of the band ''Inside Out''.<ref name=\"Mason\">{{Cite book| publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson Illustrated | isbn = 978-0-297-84387-0| pages = 360 p. : ill.; 29&nbsp;cm| last = Mason| first = Nick| title = Inside out a personal history of Pink Floyd| location = London| year = 2004 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, it was reported that she had agreed to become the honorary president of [[Glantraeth F.C.]], a small football club in [[Malltraeth]], [[Anglesey]], Wales, near her grandparents' farm, where she spent time as a child.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-35473354|title=A-lister Naomi Watts links up with Anglesey football club|work=BBC News|date=2 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Relationships===\nWatts had a relationship with Australian actor [[Heath Ledger]] from August 2002 to May 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/naomi-watts-opens-about-loss-ledger-wbna28920319 |title=Scoop: Watts opens up about loss of Ledger |publisher=Today.com |date=29 January 2009 |accessdate=22 February 2011}}</ref> In the spring of 2005, Watts began a relationship with American actor [[Liev Schreiber]]. The couple's first son, Alexander \"Sasha\" Pete, was born in July 2007 in Los Angeles, and their second son, Samuel \"Sammy\" Kai, in December 2008 in New York City.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20013570,00.html |title = Liev Schreiber: 'I'm going to be a dad'|accessdate =15 December 2008 |first=Stephen|last=Silverman|date=27 February 2007 |work=People}}</ref> On 26 September 2016, Watts and Schreiber announced their split after 11 years together.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nessif|first1=Bruno|title=Liev Schreiber and Naomi Watts Split After 11 Years Together|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/797780/liev-schreiber-and-naomi-watts-split-after-11-years-together|accessdate=26 September 2016|work=[[E! News]]|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|date=26 September 2016|location=United States}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nShe considered converting to [[Buddhism]] after having gained an interest in that religion during the shooting of ''The Painted Veil'' (2006). She said of her religious beliefs, \"I have some belief but I am not a strict Buddhist or anything yet\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/entertainment/watts-trying-out-buddhism/|title=Watts drawn to Buddhism}}</ref>\n\n===Politics ===\nIn July 2019, Naomi Watts donated to the Congressional Election Campaign of [[Valerie Plame]]  for [[New Mexico's 3rd congressional district]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/breaking-bad-star-and-holocaust-denier-donate-to-former-cia-officer-valerie-plame-campaign Breaking Bad star and Holocaust denier donate to former CIA officer Valerie Plame campaign] by Caitlin Yilek, 5 August 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.krwg.org/post/ex-cia-operative-plames-house-bid-gets-many-small-donors Ex-CIA operative Plame's House bid gets many small donors] NEWS EDITOR AND PARTNERS \u2022 17 July 2019</ref>\n\n==Filmography and awards==\n{{main|Naomi Watts filmography|List of awards and nominations received by Naomi Watts}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q132616|n=no|s=no|v=no|voy=no|b=no|wikt=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|c=category:Naomi Watts}}\n* {{IMDb name|0915208}}\n* {{people.com}}\n* [http://www.unaids.org/en/aboutunaids/unaidsambassadors/naomiwatts Naomi Watts at UNAIDS.org]\n* {{Instagram|naomiwatts|Naomi Watts}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Naomi Watts|Awards for Naomi Watts]]\n|list =\n{{London Film Critics Circle Award for Actress of the Year}}\n{{Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Actress 2001\u2013present}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Breakthrough Performance}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Actress}}\n{{San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Actress}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Actress}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watts, Naomi}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Kent]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:English film producers]]\n[[Category:English people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS activists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at North Sydney Girls High School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ysgol Gyfun Llangefni]]\n[[Category:People from Shoreham, Kent]]\n[[Category:Transcendental Meditation practitioners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English actress and film producer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Naomi Watts\n| image              = File:Naomi Watts (36037832511) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Watts at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic Con]]\n| birth_name         = Naomi Ellen Watts\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1968|9|28}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shoreham, Kent]], England\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = British, Australian<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/entertainment/2007-04/29/content_863583.htm|title=Naomi Watts: I still consider myself British|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Actress\n*film producer\n}}\n| years_active       = 1986\u2013present\n| works              = [[Naomi Watts filmography|Filmography]]\n| partner            = [[Liev Schreiber]] (2005\u20132016) \n| children           = 2\n| father             = [[Peter Watts (road manager)|Peter Watts]]\n| relatives          = [[Ben Watts]] (brother)\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Naomi Watts|Full list]]\n}}\n\n'''Naomi Ellen Watts''' (born 28 September 1968) is a British-Australian<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/entertainment/2007-04/29/content_863583.htm|title=Naomi Watts: I still consider myself British|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> actress and film producer.<!--Please discuss on the talk page before changing this. Thank you.--><ref>{{cite news |first=Gill |last=Pringle |title=Naomi Watts on 'While We're Young', her roots and being a mum |date=30 March 2015 |work=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/naomi-watts-on-while-were-young-her-roots-and-being-a-mum-10144541.html |accessdate=30 April 2015 |quote=The truth is that I've spent more time in America out of all three countries. I spent the first 14 years in England, just under 10 in Australia and then the rest in America. I've still got only one passport and that's British and my mum still lives between there and Australia. I feel very much a part of both countries.}}</ref> She made her film debut in the Australian drama ''[[For Love Alone]]'' (1986) and then appeared in the Australian television series ''[[Hey Dad..!]]'' (1990), ''[[Brides of Christ]]'' (1991), ''[[Home and Away]]'' (1991), and the film ''[[Flirting (film)|Flirting]]'' (1991). After moving to the United States, Watts struggled as an actress for years, but managed to obtain parts in the films ''[[Tank Girl (film)|Tank Girl]]'' (1995), ''[[Children of the Corn IV: The Gathering]]'' (1996), and ''[[Dangerous Beauty]]'' (1998), and the television series ''[[Sleepwalkers (TV series)|Sleepwalkers]]'' (1997\u20131998).\n\nWatts rose to international prominence for playing an aspiring actress in [[David Lynch]]'s psychological thriller ''[[Mulholland Drive (film)|Mulholland Drive]]'' (2001) and a tormented journalist in the horror remake ''[[The Ring (2002 film)|The Ring]]'' (2002). She subsequently received a nomination for the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]] for her performance as a grief-stricken mother in [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]]'s [[neo-noir]] film ''[[21 Grams]]'' (2003). Her next films throughout the 2000s include ''[[I Heart Huckabees]]'' (2004), [[King Kong (2005 film)|''King Kong'']] (2005), ''[[Eastern Promises]]'' (2007), and ''[[The International (2009 film)|The International]]'' (2009).\n\nFor her role as [[Mar\u00eda Bel\u00f3n|Maria Bennett]] in the disaster film ''[[The Impossible (2012 film)|The Impossible]]'' (2012), Watts received another Academy Award for Best Actress nomination. In the 2010s, she starred in the well-received independent films ''[[Birdman (film)|Birdman]]'' (2014), for which she won a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] as part of the cast, ''[[St. Vincent (film)|St. Vincent]]'' (2014), ''[[While We're Young (film)|While We're Young]]'' (2015), and ''[[Luce (film)|Luce]]'' (2019). Watts also continued to act in blockbusters, with appearances in the [[The Divergent Series|''Divergent'' franchise]] (2015\u20132016), and ventured into television with the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] series ''[[Twin Peaks (season 3)|Twin Peaks]]'' (2017) and ''[[The Loudest Voice]]'' (2019).\n\nWatts is particularly known for her work in remakes and independent productions with dark or tragic themes, as well as portrayals of characters that endure loss or suffering.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jul/15/naomi-watts-wasnt-soul-destroyed-gypsy</ref>Magazines such as ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' and ''Maxim'' have included her on their lists of the world's most beautiful women. She has been an ambassador for [[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS]] and [[Pantene]]'s [[Pantene Beautiful Lengths|Beautiful Lengths]]. Despite significant media attention, Watts is reticent about her personal life. She had a relationship with American actor [[Liev Schreiber]] from 2005 to 2016, with whom she has two sons.\n\n==Early life==\nNaomi Ellen Watts was born on 28 September 1968, in [[Shoreham, Kent]], England.<ref name=contemporary /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/3671818/Naomi-Watts-on-Funny-Games.html |title=Naomi Watts on Funny Games |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |first=Sheila |last=Johnston |date=15 March 2008 |accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref> She is the daughter of Myfanwy (\"Miv\") Edwards (''[[Given name|n\u00e9e]]'' Roberts), an antiques dealer and costume and set designer,<ref name=contemporary>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=FORkAAAAMAAJ&dq=naomi+watts+antiques+dealer+costume&q=antiques+dealer+costume#search_anchor|title=Contemporary Theatre, Film and Television: A Biographical Guide Featuring Performers, Directors, Writers, Producers, Designers, Managers, Choreographers, Technicians, Composers, Executives, Dancers|publisher=Gale/Cengage Learning|year=2005|isbn=978-0-7876-9037-3|page=340}}</ref> and [[Peter Watts (road manager)|Peter Watts]] (1946\u20131976), a road manager and sound engineer who worked with [[Pink Floyd]].<ref name=\"Sams, Christine\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/02/22/1077384633676.html|title=How Naomi told her mum about Oscar|accessdate=15 December 2008|author=Sams, Christine|date=23 February 2004|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]}}</ref><ref name=tca>Stated on ''[[Inside the Actors Studio]]'', 2003</ref> Miv was born in England but lived in Australia between the ages of one and seven. Watts's maternal grandfather was Welsh and her maternal grandmother was Australian.<ref name=\"smh\">{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/02/22/1077384633676.html?from=storyrhs|title=How Naomi told her mum about Oscar \u2013 SpecialsEntFilmOscars2004 \u2013 www.smh.com.au|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=30 May 2015|date=23 February 2004}}</ref><ref name=\"themorningbulletin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themorningbulletin.com.au/news/naomi-watts-while-were-young-her-roots-and-being-m/2592146/|title=Naomi Watts on 'While We're Young', her roots and being a mum &#124; Rockhampton Morning Bulletin|publisher=themorningbulletin.com.au|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nWatts's parents divorced when she was four years old.<ref name=tca/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2003/11/23/naomi_watts/|title=A role filled with rage and anguish reveals the fearless side of an actress who respects the power of emotion|work=Boston Globe |first=Scott|last=Heller|date=23 November 2003|accessdate=5 July 2011}}</ref> After the divorce, Watts and her elder brother, [[Ben Watts]], moved several times across [[South East England]] with their mother.<ref name=mymotto/> Peter Watts left Pink Floyd in 1974, and remarried in 1976. In August 1976, he was found dead in a flat in [[Notting Hill]], of an apparent heroin [[drug overdose|overdose]].<ref name=\"Talk Talk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.talktalk.co.uk/entertainment/film/biography/artist/naomi-watts/biography/157|title=Naomi Watts Biography|work=TalkTalk|publisher=Tiscali UK Limited trading|accessdate=5 July 2011| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516055536/http://www.talktalk.co.uk/entertainment/film/biography/artist/naomi-watts/biography/157| archive-date=16 May 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Numb\">{{Cite book| publisher = Di Capo Press| isbn = 978-0-306-81752-6| page = [https://archive.org/details/comfortablynumbi00mark/page/213 213]| last = Blake| first = Mark| title = Comfortably Numb - The Inside Story of Pink Floyd| year = 2008| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/comfortablynumbi00mark/page/213}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his death, Watts's mother moved the family to Llanfawr Farm in [[Llangefni]] and [[Llanfairpwllgwyngyll]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WwYAuvBcQ1Y |title=Naomi Watts' Unpronounceable Town Name |via=YouTube |date=6 March 2015 |accessdate=7 March 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.moviefone.com/2015/03/06/best-of-late-night-tv-chris-hemsworths-musical-beers/ |title=Best of Late Night TV: Chris Hemsworth's Musical Beers and Naomi Watts' Crazy Hometown (VIDEO) |publisher=Moviefone |date=6 March 2015 |accessdate=7 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150307103200/http://news.moviefone.com/2015/03/06/best-of-late-night-tv-chris-hemsworths-musical-beers/ |archive-date=7 March 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> towns on the island of [[Anglesey]] in [[North Wales]], where they lived with Watts's maternal grandparents, Nikki and Hugh Roberts, for three years. During this time, Watts attended a [[Welsh language]] school, [[Ysgol Gyfun Llangefni]].<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> She later said of her time in Wales: \"We took Welsh lessons in a school in the middle of nowhere while everyone else was taking English. Wherever we moved, I would adapt and pick up the regional accent. It's obviously significant now, me being an actress. Anyway, there was quite a lot of sadness in my childhood, but no lack of love.\"<ref name=bbcprofile>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northwest/halloffame/showbiz/naomiwatts.shtml|title=Naomi Watts|work=BBC North West Wales|publisher=BBC|date=November 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207172543/http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/northwest/halloffame/showbiz/naomiwatts.shtml|archivedate=7 December 2008}}</ref> In 1978, her mother remarried (though she would later be divorced again)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2003/09/15/naomi_watts_le_divorce_interview.shtml|title=Naomi Watts|publisher=BBC|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref> and Watts and her brother then moved to [[Suffolk]], where she attended [[Thomas Mills High School]].<ref name=mymotto>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2007/oct/19/londonfilmfestival2007.londonfilmfestival|title=Work begets work: that is my motto|newspaper=The Guardian|date=19 October 2007|first=Emma|last=Brockes|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> Watts has stated that she wanted to become an actress after seeing her mother performing on stage and from the time she watched the 1980 film ''[[Fame (1980 film)|Fame]]''.<ref name=tca/><ref name=people>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/naomi_watts|title=Naomi Watts|work=People|accessdate=5 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982, when Watts was 14, she moved to Sydney in Australia with her mother, brother and stepfather.<ref name=tca/><ref name=biochannel>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/naomi-watts.html|title=Naomi Watts Biography|work=The Biography Channel UK|publisher=A&E Television Networks|accessdate=5 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104172344/http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/naomi-watts.html|archivedate=4 January 2014}}</ref> Myfanwy established a career in the burgeoning film business, working as a stylist for television commercials, then turning to costume design, ultimately working for the soap opera ''[[Return to Eden]]''.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> After emigrating, Watts was enrolled in acting lessons by her mother; she auditioned for numerous television advertisements, where she met and befriended actress [[Nicole Kidman]]. Watts obtained her first role in the 1986 drama film, ''[[For Love Alone]]'', based on the novel of the same name by [[Christina Stead]], and produced by [[Margaret Fink]].<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/>\n\nIn Australia, Watts attended [[Mosman High School]] and [[North Sydney Girls High School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mosman-daily.whereilive.com.au/news/story/lower-north-shores-top-aussie-legends/|title=Lower North Shore's top Aussie legends|date=21 January 2010|accessdate=5 July 2011|work=The Mosman Daily|publisher=News Community Media}}</ref> She failed to graduate from school, afterwards working as a papergirl, a [[negative cutter]] and managing a Delicacies store in Sydney's affluent [[North Shore (Sydney)|North Shore]].<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/>\n\nShe decided to become a model when she was 18. She signed with a models agency that sent her to Japan, but after several failed auditions, she returned to Sydney.<ref name=tca/> There, she was hired to work in advertising for a department store, that exposed her to the attention of ''[[Follow Me (magazine)|Follow Me]]'', a magazine which hired her as an assistant fashion editor.<ref name=tca/><ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> A casual invitation to participate in a drama workshop inspired Watts to quit her job and to pursue her acting ambitions.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/><ref name=interviewmag>{{cite web|url=http://www.lynchnet.com/mdrive/wattsint.html|title=For Anyone who Ever Needed a reminder of what can happen when you hold onto your dreams \u2013 here she is|accessdate=31 August 2010|last=Sischy|first=Ingrid|date=December 2003|publisher=Brandt Publications}}</ref>\n\nRegarding her nationality, Watts has stated: \"I consider myself British and have very happy memories of the UK. I spent the first 14 years of my life in England and [[Wales]] and never wanted to leave. When I was in Australia I went back to England a lot.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/anglophenia/2011/07/warning-naomi-watts-is-secretly-british|title=Warning: Naomi Watts Is&nbsp;... Secretly British|first=MacKenzie|last=Wilson|accessdate=28 July 2014|date=5 July 2011|publisher=BBC America}}</ref> She also has expressed her ties to Australia, declaring: \"I consider myself very connected to Australia, in fact when people say where is home, I say Australia, because those are my most powerful memories.\"<ref>{{cite video|people=Aspen, Richard (Interviewer); Watts, Naomi (Interviewee)|date=11 September 2007|title=Eastern Promises Interview|work=[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early roles and struggling career (1986\u20132000)===\nWatts's career began in television, where she made brief appearances in commercials.<ref name=biochannel/> The 1986 film ''[[For Love Alone]]'', set in the 1930s and based on [[Christina Stead]]'s 1945 best-selling novel of the same name, marked her debut in film.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/18132/For-Love-Alone/overview|title=For Love Alone (1986) Overview|work=The New York Times|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> She then appeared in two episodes of the [[List of Hey Dad..! episodes#Season 4 (1990-1991)|fourth season]] of the Australian sitcom ''[[Hey Dad..!]]'' in 1990. After a five-year absence from films, Watts met director [[John Duigan]] during the 1989 premiere of her friend Nicole Kidman's film ''[[Dead Calm (film)|Dead Calm]]'' and he invited her to take a supporting role in his 1991 indie film ''[[Flirting (film)|Flirting]]''.<ref name=biochannel/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iofilm.co.uk/feats/interviews/n/naomi_watts_divorce.shtml |title=Naomi enjoys her shot|publisher=Iofilm.co.uk|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> The film received critical acclaim and was featured on [[Roger Ebert]]'s list of the 10 best films of 1992.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19921231/COMMENTARY/40308026/1023|first=Roger|last=Ebert|title=The Best 10 Movies of 1992 |work=Chicago Sun-Times|date=31 December 1992|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> Also in 1991, she took the part of Frances Heffernan, a girl who struggles to find friends behind the walls of a Sydney Catholic school,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australiantelevision.net/brides-of-christ/episodes.html|title=Brides of Christ: episode guide|work=Australian Television Information Archive's Official Site|publisher=Australian Television Information Archive|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> in the award-winning mini-series ''[[Brides of Christ]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shop.abc.net.au/browse/product.asp?productid=721188|title=Brides of Christ description on Australian Broadcasting Corporation's shop|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=6 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110401034613/http://shop.abc.net.au/browse/product.asp?productid=721188|archivedate=1 April 2011}}</ref> and had a recurring role in the soap opera ''[[Home and Away]]'' as the handicapped [[Julie Gibson (Home and Away)|Julie Gibson]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kent|first=Melissa|work=The Age |location=Australia|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/entertainment/tv--radio/cast-and-fans-of-home-and-away-well-on-the-way-to-belonging-foreverand-ever/2009/02/07/1233423560588.html|title=Cast and fans of Home and Away well on the way to belonging forever and ever|date=8 February 2009|accessdate=28 August 2011}}</ref> Watts was then offered a role in the drama series ''[[A Country Practice]]'' but turned it down, not wanting to \"get stuck on a soap for two or three years\", a decision she later called \"na\u00efve\".<ref name=biochannel/><ref name=interviewmag/>\n\nWatts then took a year off to travel, visiting Los Angeles and being introduced to agents through Kidman.<ref name=mymotto/><ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> Encouraged, Watts decided to move to America, to pursue her career further. In 1993 she had a small role in the [[John Goodman]] film ''[[Matinee (1993 film)|Matinee]]'' and temporarily returned to Australia to star in three Australian films: another of Duigan's pictures, ''[[Wide Sargasso Sea (1993 film)|Wide Sargasso Sea]]''; the drama ''[[The Custodian]]''; and had her first leading role in the film ''[[Gross Misconduct (film)|Gross Misconduct]]'', as a student who accuses one of her teachers (played by [[Jimmy Smits]]) of raping her.<ref name=biochannel/> Watts then moved back to America for good but the difficulty of finding agents, producers and directors willing to hire her during that period frustrated her initial efforts.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> Though her financial situation never led her to taking a job out of the film industry, she experienced problems like being unable to pay the rent of her apartment and losing her medical insurance.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/><ref name=bloomer/> \"At first, everything was fantastic and doors were opened to me. But some people who I met through Nicole [Kidman], who had been all over me, had difficulty remembering my name when we next met. There were a lot of promises, but nothing actually came off. I ran out of money and became quite lonely, but Nic gave me company and encouragement to carry on.\"<ref name=sundaytimes>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidlynch.de/wattssunday.html|title=Film: Naomi Watts interview|work=The Sunday Times|first=Garth|last=Pearce|date=6 January 2002|accessdate=14 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328140104/http://www.davidlynch.de/wattssunday.html|archive-date=28 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|When I came to America there was so much promise of good stuff and I thought, I've got it made here. I'm going to kick ass. Then I went back to Australia and did one or two more jobs. When I returned to Hollywood, all those people who'd been so encouraging before weren't interested. You take all their flattery seriously when you don't know any better. I basically had to start all over again. I get offered some things without auditioning today, but back then they wouldn't even fax me the pages of a script because it was too much of an inconvenience. I had to drive for hours into [[San Fernando Valley|the Valley]] to pick up three bits of paper for some horrendous piece of shit, then go back the next day and line up for two hours to meet the casting director who would barely give me eye contact. It was humiliating.<br>{{endash}}Watts on her early struggles<ref name=interviewmag/>}}\n\nShe then won a supporting role in the futuristic 1995 film ''[[Tank Girl (film)|Tank Girl]]'', winning the role of \"Jet Girl\" after nine auditions.<ref name=tca/> The film was met with mixed reviews and flopped at the box office, although it has gone on to become something of a cult classic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/tank_girl/|title=Tank Girl (1995) on Rotten Tomatoes|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster, Inc|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> Throughout the rest of the decade, she took mostly supporting roles in films<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/naomi-watts/bio/167538|title=Naomi Watts: Biography|work=TV Guide|publisher=TV Guide Online Holdings LLC|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> and occasionally considered leaving the business, but: \"there were always little bites. Whenever I felt I was at the end of my rope, something would come up. Something bad. But for me it was 'work begets work'; that was my motto.\"<ref name=mymotto/><ref name=bloomer>{{cite web|url=http://www.backstage.com/news/late-bloomer_4/|title=Late Bloomer|publisher=Backstage.com|date=24 November 2003 |first=Cassie |last=Carpenter |accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> In 1996, she starred alongside [[Joe Mantegna]], [[Kelly Lynch]] and [[J.T. Walsh]] in [[George Hickenlooper]]'s action-thriller ''Persons Unknown''; alongside [[James Earl Jones]], [[Kevin Kilner]] and [[Ellen Burstyn]] in the period drama ''Timepiece''; in ''Bermuda Triangle'', a TV pilot that was not picked up for a full series, where she played a former documentary filmmaker who disappears in the [[Bermuda Triangle]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eofftv.com/kim_newman_archive/b/bermuda_triangle_1996_review.htm|title=Bermuda Triangle (1996)|work=Encyclopedia of fantastic Film and television|publisher=Kim Newman|accessdate=28 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324092645/http://www.eofftv.com/kim_newman_archive/b/bermuda_triangle_1996_review.htm|archivedate=24 March 2012}}</ref> and as the lead role in ''[[Children of the Corn IV: The Gathering]]'', in which children in a small town become possessed under the command of a wrongfully murdered [[child preacher]].<ref name=tca/>\n\nIn 1997, she starred in the Australian ensemble romantic drama ''[[Under the Lighthouse Dancing]]'' starring [[Jack Thompson (actor)|Jack Thompson]] and [[Jacqueline McKenzie]]. She also played the lead role in the short-lived television series ''[[Sleepwalkers (TV series)|Sleepwalkers]]''.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> In 1998, she starred alongside [[Neil Patrick Harris]] and [[Debbie Reynolds]] in the TV film ''[[The Christmas Wish (film)|The Christmas Wish]]'', played the supporting role of Giulia De Lezze in ''[[Dangerous Beauty]]'',<ref name=biochannel/> and provided some voice work for ''[[Babe: Pig in the City]]''.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> She said in an interview in 2012, \"That really should not be on my r\u00e9sum\u00e9! I think that was early on in the day, when I was trying to beef up my r\u00e9sum\u00e9. I came in and did a couple days' work of voiceovers and we had to suck on [helium] and then do a little mouse voice. But I was one in a hundred, so I'm sure you would never be able to identify my voice. I probably couldn't either!\"<ref name=weirdest>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2012/12/naomi-watts-on-the-impossible-controversy.html|title=Naomi Watts on The Impossible and Her Weirdest Film Credit|publisher=Vulture.com|first=Kyle|last=Buchanan|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref> In 1999, she played Alice in the romantic comedy ''[[Strange Planet]]'' and the Texan student [[Holly Maddux]] in ''[[The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer]]'', which was based on the real life effort to capture [[Ira Einhorn]], who was charged with Maddux's murder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/strange-planet-v181000|title=Strange Planet (1999)|work=AllRovi|accessdate=28 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120718191443/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/strange-planet-v181000|archivedate=18 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-hunt-for-the-unicorn-killer-v180100|title=The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer (1999)|work=AllRovi|accessdate=28 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120724203706/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-hunt-for-the-unicorn-killer-v180100|archivedate=24 July 2012}}</ref> In 2000, while [[David Lynch]] was expanding the rejected pilot of ''[[Mulholland Drive (film)|Mulholland Drive]]'' into a feature film, Watts starred alongside [[Derek Jacobi]], [[Jack Davenport]] and [[Iain Glen]] in the [[BBC]] TV film ''[[The Wyvern Mystery]]'', an adaptation of the novel of the same name by [[Sheridan Le Fanu]] that was broadcast in March of that year.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/>\n\nMuch of her early career is filled with near misses in casting, as she was up for significant roles in films such as 1997's ''[[The Postman (film)|The Postman]]'' and ''[[The Devil's Advocate (1997 film)|The Devil's Advocate]]'' and 2000's ''[[Meet the Parents]]'', which eventually went to other actresses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2006-Ra-Z/Watts-Naomi.html|title=Naomi Watts: Biography|work=Encyclopedia of World Biography|publisher=Advameg, Inc.|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> In an interview in 2012, Watts said, \"I came to New York and auditioned at least five times for ''Meet the Parents''. I think the director liked me but the studio didn't. I heard every piece of feedback you could imagine, and in this case, it was 'not sexy enough'.\"<ref name=dailybeast>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/12/21/naomi-watts-on-the-impossible-personal-tragedy-and-playing-princess-diana.html|title=Naomi Watts on 'The Impossible,' Personal Tragedy, and Playing Princess Diana|newspaper=The Daily Beast|date=21 December 2012|accessdate=14 March 2013|last1=Stern|first1=Marlow}}</ref> Watts recalled her early career in an interview in 2002, saying, \"It is a tough town. I think my spirit has taken a beating. The most painful thing has been the endless auditions. Knowing that you have something to offer, but not being able to show it, is so frustrating. As an unknown, you get treated badly. I auditioned and waited for things I did not have any belief in, but I needed the work and had to accept horrendous pieces of shit.\"<ref name=sundaytimes/> Watts studied the [[Meisner Technique]].\n\n===Rise to fame (2001\u20132002)===\n[[File:Naomi Watts \u00e9s David Lynch--.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Watts with filmmaker [[David Lynch]] at the [[2001 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\n\nIn 1999, director [[David Lynch]] began casting for his psychological thriller ''[[Mulholland Drive (film)|Mulholland Drive]]''. He interviewed Watts after looking at her headshot,<ref name=dailybeast/> without having seen any of her previous work,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Twin Piques|first=Anna|last=David|date=November 2001|journal=Premiere Magazine|pages=80\u201381|volume=15|issue=3}}</ref> and offered her the lead role.<ref name=dailybeast/> Lynch later said about his selection of Watts, \"I saw someone that I felt had a tremendous talent, and I saw someone who had a beautiful soul, an intelligence\u2014possibilities for a lot of different roles, so it was a beautiful full package.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=It's a Road She Knows Well; 'Mulholland Dr.' star Naomi Watts has lived the Hollywood metaphor behind the fabled highway|first=Scarlet|last=Cheng|date=12 October 2001|journal=Los Angeles Times|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2001/oct/12/entertainment/ca-56239|accessdate=7 July 2011|page=20}}</ref> Conceived as a pilot for a television series, Lynch shot a large portion of it in February 1999, planning to keep it open-ended for a potential series. However, the pilot was rejected. Watts recalled thinking at the time, \"just my dumb luck, that I'm in the only David Lynch programme that never sees the light of day.\"<ref name=mymotto/> Instead, Lynch filmed an ending in October 2000, turning it into a feature film which was picked up for distribution.\n\nThe film, which also starred [[Laura Harring]] and [[Justin Theroux]], was highly acclaimed by critics and would become Watts's breakthrough. She was praised by critics, including Peter Bradshaw from ''[[The Guardian]]'', who said, \"Watts's face metamorphoses miraculously from fresh-faced beauty to a frenzied, teary scowl of ugliness.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2002/jan/04/1 |first=Peter |last=Bradshaw |title=''Mulholland Drive'' review|work=The Guardian|date=4 January 2002|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref> and [[Emanuel Levy]], who wrote, \"...&nbsp;Naomi Watts, in a brilliant performance, a young, wide-eyed and grotesquely cheerful blonde, full of high hopes to make it big in Hollywood.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emanuellevy.com/review/mulholland-drive-3/|first=Emanuel|last=Levy|title=Mulholland Drive review by Emanuel Levy|work=Emanuel Levy|publisher=Emanuel Levy's Official Site|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref> The film premiered at the 2001 [[Cannes Film Festival]] and received a large number of awards and nominations, including the Best Actress Award for Watts from the [[National Society of Film Critics]] and a nomination for Best Actress from the [[American Film Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/mulholland-dr-v246240 |title=Mulholland Dr. (2001) Awards |work=AllRovi |accessdate=7 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110701113344/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/mulholland-dr-v246240 |archivedate=1 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> The surrealist film following the story of the aspiring actress Betty Elms, played by Watts, attracted controversy with its strong lesbian theme.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/2001/10/05/2001-10-05_dangerous_curves_on_lynch_s_.html|first=Jami|last=Bernard|title=Dangerous curves on Lynch's 'Drive'|work=Daily News|publisher=Daily News, L.P.|date=10 April 2001|accessdate=7 July 2011}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/07/23/1027332361018.html|first=Red|last=Symons|title=Man in spirit-led, Mulholland-riddle miracle!|work=The Age|date=6 July 2002|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2001, she starred in two short films, ''Never Date an Actress'' and ''[[Ellie Parker]]'', and the horror film ''[[Down (film)|The Shaft]]'', director [[Dick Maas]]' remake of his 1983 film ''[[De Lift]]''.<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> In 2002, she starred in one of the biggest box office hits of that year,<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> ''[[The Ring (2002 film)|The Ring]]'', the English language remake of the [[J-Horror|Japanese horror film]] ''[[Ring (film)|Ringu]]''. Directed by [[Gore Verbinski]], the film, which also starred [[Martin Henderson]] and [[Brian Cox (actor)|Brian Cox]], received favourable reviews and grossed around US$129&nbsp;million domestically (equivalent to US${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|129|2002|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ring.htm|title=The Ring at Box Office Mojo|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref> Watts portrayed [[Rachel Keller]], a journalist investigating the strange deaths of her niece and other teenagers after watching a mysterious videotape, and receiving a phone call announcing their deaths in seven days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ring/|title=The Ring (2002)|work=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> Her performance was praised by critics, including Paul Clinton of ''[[CNN.com]]'', who stated that she \"is excellent in this leading role, which proves that her stellar performance in ''Mulholland Drive'' was not a fluke. She strikes a perfect balance between scepticism and the slow realisation of the truth in regard to the deadly power of the videotape.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2002/SHOWBIZ/Movies/10/18/review.the.ring/index.html|title=Review: 'The Ring' gets under your skin|publisher=CNN |first=Paul|last=Clinton|accessdate=8 December 2010|date=18 October 2002}}</ref> That year, she also starred in ''[[Rabbits (film)|Rabbits]]'', a series of short films directed by David Lynch; alongside several other famous British actors in the black comedy ''[[Plots with a View]]''; and with [[Tim Daly]] in the western ''[[The Outsider (2002 film)|The Outsider]]''.\n\n===Established career (2003\u20132007)===\n[[File:Naomi Watts (6800617073).jpg|alt=|thumb|309x309px|Watts in [[Sydney]] in 2012]]\nIn 2003, Watts took the part of Julia Cook in [[Gregor Jordan]]'s Australian film ''[[Ned Kelly (2003 film)|Ned Kelly]]'' opposite [[Heath Ledger]], [[Orlando Bloom]] and [[Geoffrey Rush]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/ned-kelly-v283385|title=Ned Kelly (2003)|work=AllRovi|accessdate=7 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120719112415/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/ned-kelly-v283385|archivedate=19 July 2012}}</ref> as well as starring in the [[Merchant Ivory Productions|Merchant-Ivory]] film ''[[Le Divorce]]'', portraying Roxeanne de Persand, a poet who is pregnant and abandoned by her husband Charles-Henri de Persand. Roxeanne and her sister Isabel (played by [[Kate Hudson]]) dispute the ownership of a painting by [[Georges de La Tour]] with the family of Charles-Henri's lover. ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a \"C\" rating and lamented Watts's performance: \"I'm disappointed to report that Hudson and Watts have no chemistry as sisters, perhaps because Watts never seems like the expatriate artiste she's supposed to be playing\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Gleiberman|first = Owen |title = Le Divorce | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]]| date = 5 August 2003 | url = https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,472427,00.html |accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nConversely, her performance opposite [[Sean Penn]] and [[Benicio del Toro]] in director [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]]'s 2003 drama ''[[21 Grams]]'' earned Watts numerous award nominations, including an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]], later that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/76nominees.html |title=Nominees & Winners for the 76th Academy Awards |work=Academy Awards- Official Site |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |accessdate=7 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727154929/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/oscarlegacy/2000-present/76nominees.html |archivedate=27 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> In the story, told in a non-linear manner, she portrayed Cristina Peck, a grief-stricken woman living a suburban life after the killing of her husband and two children by Jack Jordan (Benicio del Toro), who became involved in a relationship with the critically ill academic mathematician Paul Rivers (Sean Penn). She has said of the nomination, \"It's far beyond what I ever dreamed for \u2013 that would have been too far fetched\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/02/11/1076388374177.html|title=Watts bath to fame|work=The Age |first=Paul|last=Clinton|accessdate=7 July 2011|date=11 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/21-grams-v290208|title=21 Grams (2003) Awards|work=AllRovi|accessdate=7 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110603085706/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/21-grams-v290208|archivedate=3 June 2011}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' praised her: \"Because Ms. Watts reinvents herself with each performance, it's easy to forget how brilliant she is. She has a boldness that comes from a lack of overemphasis, something actresses sometimes do to keep up with Mr. Penn\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B02EEDB153EF93BA25753C1A9659C8B63|first=Elvis|last=Mitchell|title=21 Grams (2003) movie review|work=The New York Times|date=18 October 2003|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref> ''The San Francisco Chronicle'' wrote: \"Watts is riveting, but she's much better in scenes of extreme emotion than in those requiring subtlety.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/chronicle/reviews/movies/21GRAMS.DTL|first=Carla|last=Meyer|title=Gloomy '21 Grams' for weighty souls|work=San Francisco Chronicle|publisher=Hearst Communications Inc.|date=26 November 2003|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Watts starred alongside [[Mark Ruffalo]] in the independent film ''[[We Don't Live Here Anymore]]'',<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> based on short stories by [[Andre Dubus]], which depicts the crisis of two married couples,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/287908/We-Don-t-Live-Here-Anymore/overview|title=We Don't Live Here Anymore (2004)|work=The New York Times|accessdate=7 July 2011|first=A. O.|last=Scott}}</ref> reunited with Sean Penn in ''[[The Assassination of Richard Nixon]]'', playing the wife of the would-be presidential assassin [[Samuel Byck]] (Penn),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-assassination-of-richard-nixon-v304506|title=The Assassination of Richard Nixon|work=AllRovi|accessdate=7 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027221436/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-assassination-of-richard-nixon-v304506|archivedate=27 October 2011}}</ref> and teamed up with [[Jude Law]] and [[Dustin Hoffman]] in [[David O. Russell]]'s ensemble comedy ''[[I Heart Huckabees]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.tvguide.com/heart-huckabees/cast/137660|title=I Heart Huckabees: Cast & Details|work=TV Guide|publisher=TV Guide Online Holdings LLC|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref> She headlined and produced the semi-autobiographical drama ''[[Ellie Parker]]'' (2005), which depicted the struggle of an Australian actress in Hollywood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/ellie-parker-v318905|title=Ellie Parker Synopsis|work=AllRovie|accessdate=7 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120730014257/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/ellie-parker-v318905|archivedate=30 July 2012}}</ref> The film began as a short film that was screened at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] in 2001 and was expanded into a feature-length production over the next four years. Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] praised Watts's performance: \"The character is played by Watts with courage, fearless observation and a gift for timing that is so uncanny it can make points all by itself.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20051215/REVIEWS/51205003/1023|title=Ellie Parker|date=16 December 2005|first=Roger|last=Ebert|work=Chicago-Sun Times|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nWatts starred in the sequel to ''The Ring'', ''[[The Ring Two]]'' (2005), which despite a negative critical response,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ring_two/|title=The Ring Two (2005)|work=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> made over US$161&nbsp;million worldwide gross (equivalent to US${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|161|2005|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ring2.htm|title=The Ring Two|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> In 2005, Watts also headlined the [[King Kong (2005 film)|remake]] of ''[[King Kong (1933 film)|King Kong]]'' as Ann Darrow. She was the first choice for the role, portrayed by [[Fay Wray]] in the original film, with no other actors considered.<ref name=beg>{{cite book | author = [[Brian Sibley]] | title = Peter Jackson: A Film-maker's Journey | publisher = [[HarperCollins]] | pages = 526\u2013542 | year = 2006 | isbn = 978-0-00-717558-1 | location = London}}</ref> In preparation for her role, Watts met with Wray,<ref name=fi>{{cite news|author=Ian Spelling |url=http://www.scifi.com/sfw/issue452/interview.html |title=Peter Jackson proves with King Kong that the director, not the beast, is the true eighth wonder of the world |work=[[Science Fiction Weekly]] |date=December 2005 |accessdate=1 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060619091002/http://www.scifi.com/sfw/issue452/interview.html |archivedate=19 June 2006 |df= }}</ref> who was to make a [[cameo appearance]] and say the final line of dialogue, but she died during pre-production at the age of 96.<ref name=Ray>{{cite book | author = Paul A. Woods | title = Peter Jackson: From Gore to Mordor | publisher = Plexus Books | year = 2005 | isbn = 978-0-85965-356-5 | pages = 176\u2013187 | chapter = Kong Cometh! | location = London}}</ref> ''King Kong'' proved to be Watts's most commercially successful film yet. Helmed by ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'' director [[Peter Jackson]], the film won high praise and [[revenue|grossed]] US$550&nbsp;million worldwide (equivalent to US${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|550|2005|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=kingkong05.htm|title=King Kong BoxOffice|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=naomiwatts.htm|title=Naomi Watts BoxOffice|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> The ''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]'' praised her performance: \"The third act becomes a star-crossed, \"Beauty and the Beast\" parable far more operatic and tragic than anything the original filmmakers could have imagined, exquisitely pantomimed by Watts with a poignancy and passion that rates Oscar consideration.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=A bigger, better 'Kong'|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/ae/movies/article/A-bigger-better-Kong-1189771.php|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|accessdate=7 August 2011|date=13 December 2005|first=William|last=Arnold}}</ref> Alongside the movie, she reprised her role as Darrow in the [[Peter Jackson's King Kong|video game adaptation]] of ''King Kong''.<ref>[https://www.gamespot.com/articles/king-kong-cast-bananas-for-game/1100-6140029/ King Kong cast bananas for game] Retrieved 17 May 2019]</ref> She was nominated for Best Performance by a Female at the [[Spike Video Game Awards#2005 Awards|2005 Spike Video Game Awards]] for her role as Darrow, as well as winning the Best Cast award with the rest of the game's voice cast.<ref>[https://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=6947/ Spike TV Announces Award Nominees, Presenters] Retrieved 15 May 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.awn.com/news/spike-tv-video-game-awards-2005-winners-announced/ Spike TV Video Game Awards 2005 Winners Announced] Retrieved 15 May 2019</ref> Her other 2005 film release was [[Marc Forster]]'s psychological thriller ''[[Stay (2005 film)|Stay]]'', alongside [[Ewan McGregor]], [[Ryan Gosling]] and [[Bob Hoskins]].<ref name=\"Talk Talk\"/> At this point in her career, Watts stated the following:\n\n{{cquote|You'd better know why you're here as an actor&nbsp;... I'm here to work out my shit, what my problems are and know who I am, so by cracking open these characters perhaps that shines a light on it a little bit better&nbsp;... I know myself. I mean, of course I know myself better but the journey and search continue because hopefully we're evolving and growing all the time.<ref name=Girl.com.au>{{cite web |url=http://www.girl.com.au/naomi-watts-king-kong-interview.htm |title=Naomi Watts \u2013 King Kong Interview |publisher=girl.com.au |last=Fischer|first=Paul |accessdate=July 2, 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nThe romantic drama ''[[The Painted Veil (2006 film)|The Painted Veil]]'' (2006), with [[Edward Norton]] and [[Liev Schreiber]], featured Watts as the daughter of a lawyer who marries a man for his reputation as a physician and [[bacteriology|bacteriologist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-painted-veil-v323785|title=The Painted Veil|work=AllRovie|publisher=Rovi Corpotation|accessdate=7 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118202342/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/the-painted-veil-v323785|archivedate=18 January 2012}}</ref> Comparing her portrayal with [[Greta Garbo]]'s in the original movie, the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' wrote \"Watts makes the role work on her own terms \u2013 her Kitty is more desperate, more foolish, more miserable and more driven . . . and her spiritual journey is greater.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/12/29/DDG4MN9CKF1.DTL&type=movies|title=Will you marry me? And live unhappily ever after in China?|first=Mick|last=LaSalle|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=29 December 2006|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref> Watts also provided the voice of a small role, Suzie Rabbit, in David Lynch's [[psychological thriller]] ''[[Inland Empire (film)|Inland Empire]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/inland-empire-v326849 |title=Inland Empire |work=AllRovie |accessdate=7 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110627113340/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/inland-empire-v326849 |archivedate=27 June 2011 |df= }}</ref> That year, she was announced as the new face of the jewellers [[David Yurman]] and completed a photoshoot which was featured in the 2007 [[Pirelli Calendar]].<ref name=people/>\n\nWatts portrayed a Russian-British midwife who delivers the baby of a drug-addicted 14-year old prostitute in [[David Cronenberg]]'s ''[[Eastern Promises]]'' (2007), with [[Viggo Mortensen]].<ref name=Eastern>{{cite web|url=http://www.viewlondon.co.uk/films/eastern-promises-film-review-20671.html|title=Eastern Promises|work=View London|first=Matthew|last=Turner|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> In its review, ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' magazine observed that she \"brings a wounded radiance to the overcurious midwife Anna. Though it's a bit of a one-note role, it's a note she's long specialised in, a kind of flustered moral aggrievement\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2007/09/eastern_promises.html|title=David Cronenberg's Eastern Promises reviewed.|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=13 September 2007}}</ref> ''Eastern Promises'' grossed US$56&nbsp;million worldwide, (equivalent to US${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|56|2005|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=easternpromises.htm|title=Eastern Promises|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Eastern-Promises|title=Eastern Promises|publisher=The-numbers.com|accessdate=27 October 2015}}</ref> She was one of the producers and starred as a mother who, along with her family, are held hostage by a pair of sociopathic teenagers in [[Michael Haneke]]'s ''[[Funny Games (2007 film)|Funny Games]]'' (also 2007), a remake of Haneke's 1997 film [[Funny Games (1997 film)|of the same name]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/827/827704p3.html|title=Top 10 Films at the London Film Festival|last=Tilly|first=Chris|date=17 October 2007|work=IGN UK|accessdate=25 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025040623/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/827/827704p3.html|archivedate=25 October 2007}}</ref> The director said that he agreed to make the film on condition that he be allowed to cast Watts, according to UK's ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/3672273/Film-review-Funny-Games.html|title=Film review: Funny Games|author=Sukhdev Sandhu|date=4 April 2008|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Film-Review/eastern-promises-naomi-watts-interview|title=Eastern Promises \u2013 Naomi Watts interview|publisher=IndieLondon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moviesonline.ca/movienews_14320.html|title=Naomi Watts Interview, Funny Games|publisher=MoviesOnline}}</ref> but it went largely unnoticed by critics and audiences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1175174-funny_games/|title=Funny Games|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|date=14 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=funnygames.htm|title=Funny Games (2008)|publisher=Box Office Mojo}}</ref> Nevertheless, ''[[Newsweek]]'' felt that Watts \"hurls herself into her physically demanding role with heroic conviction\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Ansen|first=David|url=http://www.newsweek.com/rottweiler-now-english-83715|title=A Rottweiler, Now in English|work=Newsweek|date=15 March 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Biographical and independent films (2009\u20132014)===\nAfter a short hiatus from acting following the birth of her two children, Watts returned to acting in 2009, starring alongside [[Clive Owen]] in the political thriller ''[[The International (2009 film)|The International]]'', in which she played a [[Manhattan]] assistant district attorney who partners with an [[Interpol]] agent to take down a [[merchant bank]].<ref name=\"naomifilm\">{{Cite news|first=Kit |last=Borys |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i47021a7b93e54966cb8af7e263c109c8 |title=Watts has passport for Col's 'Int'l' |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=13 July 2007 |accessdate=8 December 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715164550/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i47021a7b93e54966cb8af7e263c109c8 |archivedate=15 July 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The production was a moderate commercial success,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/international/|title=The International (2009)|work=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> grossing over US$60&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|60|2009|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}) worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=international.htm|title=The International|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> She next appeared in the drama ''[[Mother and Child (2009 film)|Mother and Child]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2009/film/markets-festivals/mother-and-child-2-1200476120/|title=Review: 'Mother and Child'|first=Todd|last=McCarthy|date=16 September 2009|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> portraying the role of a lawyer who never knew her biological mother.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mother and Child \u2013 Cast and Crew|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/mother-and-child-v499195|work=Allrovie|publisher=Rovie Corporation|accessdate=8 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111129035518/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/mother-and-child-v499195 |archivedate=29 November 2011}}</ref> ''ViewLondon'' found her to be \"terrific as [her character], delivering a powerful performance that [...] isn't afraid to be unsympathetic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viewlondon.co.uk/films/mother-and-child-film-review-44349.html|title=Mother and Child|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> She was nominated for the [[Australian Film Institute International Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] award at the [[Australian Film Institute Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.org.au/AFI_Award_Winners_and_Nominees/AM/ContentManagerNet/ContentDisplay.aspx?ContentID=11996&Section=AFI_Award_Winners_and_Nominees|title=2010 Samsung Mobile AFI Awards Nominees & Winners|work=AFI Awards|publisher=Australian Film Institute|accessdate=8 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613074712/http://www.afi.org.au/AFI_Award_Winners_and_Nominees/AM/ContentManagerNet/ContentDisplay.aspx?ContentID=11996&Section=AFI_Award_Winners_and_Nominees|archivedate=13 June 2011}}</ref> and for the [[Independent Spirit Award]] for [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Supporting Female|Best Supporting Female]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/mother-and-child-v499195|title=Mother and Child \u2013 Awards|work=Allrovie|publisher=Rovie Corporation|accessdate=8 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111129035518/http://www.allrovi.com/movies/movie/mother-and-child-v499195|archivedate=29 November 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Naomi Watts.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Watts at the [[Deauville American Film Festival]] in 2011]]\nHer next film, the [[Woody Allen]] [[dramedy]] ''[[You Will Meet a Tall Dark Stranger]]'', opened at the [[2010 Cannes Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/11019455/year/2010.html |title=Cannes Film Festival \u2013 Selection List |publisher=Le Festival International du Film de Cannes|accessdate=8 October 2010}}</ref> and saw her portray Sally, a woman who has a troubled marriage with author Roy (played by [[Josh Brolin]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/you-will-meet-a-tall-dark-stranger|title=You Will Meet a Tall Dark Stranger|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=8 October 2010}}</ref> It made over US$26&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|26|2010|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=talldarkstranger.htm|title=You Will Meet a Tall Dark Stranger|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> Her portrayal of [[Valerie Plame]] in the biographical thriller ''[[Fair Game (2010 film)|Fair Game]]'' followed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/11022739/year/2010.html|title=Fair Game|publisher=Le Festival International du Film de Cannes|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> and marked the third pairing of Watts with Sean Penn after ''21 Grams'' and ''The Assassination of Richard Nixon''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118000481.html?categoryid=1236&cs=1|first=Michael|last=Fleming |title=Sean Penn in talks for Plame 'Game' |work=Variety|date=23 February 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemagazine.com/reviews/theatrical/2010-05-fair-game?q=fair+game|title=A taut retelling of the scandal that exposed Valerie Plame|work=Box Office magazine|publisher=Box Office Media|date=22 May 2010|accessdate=8 August 2011|first=Pete|last=Hammond|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921025527/http://www.boxofficemagazine.com/reviews/theatrical/2010-05-fair-game?q=fair+game|archivedate=21 September 2011}}</ref> The film earned Watts a [[Satellite Award]] nomination for [[Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Best Actress]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://extratv.warnerbros.com/2010/11/winters_bone_tops_independent_spirit_award_nominations.php |title='Winter's Bone' Tops Indie Spirit Award Noms |work=Warner Bros.|accessdate=8 December 2010}}</ref> In 2011, she appeared with [[Daniel Craig]] and [[Rachel Weisz]] in [[Jim Sheridan]]'s psychological horror film ''[[Dream House (2011 film)|Dream House]]'', as the neighbour of a murdered family,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/dream-house-trailer-starring-daniel-craig-and-naomi-watts|title=Dream House Trailer Starring Daniel Craig and Naomi Watts|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=20 July 2011|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dream_house_2011/|title=Dream House|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> and with [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] in [[Clint Eastwood]]'s biographical drama ''[[J. Edgar]]'', playing secretary [[Helen Gandy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/03/idUS53343025320110803|title='J. Edgar' Slips into Theaters Nov. 9 With Limited Bow|date=3 August 2011|first=Joshua|last=Weinstein|work=The Wrap News, Inc|accessdate=8 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2011/11/box-office-j-edgar-immortals-jack-jill.html|title=Movie Projector: 'Immortals' poised to conquer box office|work=Los Angeles Times|date=10 November 2011}}</ref> While ''Dream House'' flopped,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3282&p=.htm|title=Weekend Report: 'Dolphin Tale' Leaps Into Lead \u2013 Box Office Mojo|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref>  ''J. Edgar'' had a more favorable reception.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=jedgar.htm|title=J. Edgar (2011)|publisher=Box Office Mojo}}</ref>\n\nWatts starred in ''[[The Impossible (2012 film)|The Impossible]]'' (2012), a [[disaster film|disaster]] [[drama film|drama]] based on the true story of [[Mar\u00eda Bel\u00f3n]] and her family's experience of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|2004 Indian Ocean tsunami]]; she played the lead role, with her name changed to Maria Bennett. The film was a critical darling, had the highest-grossing opening weekend for a film in Spain,<ref>https://www.boxofficemojo.com/intl/spain/?yr=2012&wk=43&p=new</ref> and made US$180.2 million (equivalent to ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|180|2012|r=1}}}} million in {{Currentyear}}) globally.<ref>{{cite news | title=The Impossible | url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20121219/REVIEWS/121219990/1023 | work=Chicago Sun-Times | date=19 December 2012}}</ref> Deborah Young of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' stated that \"Watts packs a huge charge of emotion as the battered, ever-weakening Maria whose tears of pain and fear never appear fake or idealised,\"<ref name=\"Young\">{{cite web |author=Young, Deborah |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/impossible-naomi-watts-ewan-mcgregor-369260 |title=The Impossible: Toronto Review |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=10 September 2012 |accessdate=15 October 2012}}</ref> while Justin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' magazine remarked that she \"has few equals at conveying physical and emotional extremis, something she again demonstrates in a mostly bedridden role.\"<ref name=\"Chang\">{{cite web \n|author=Chang, Justin |url=https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117948281?refcatid=31 |title=The Impossible |work=Variety |publisher=Reed Elsevier Properties Inc |date=10 September 2012 |accessdate=15 October 2012}}</ref> Damon Wise of ''[[The Guardian]]'' felt that \"Watts is both brave and vulnerable, and her scenes with the young Lucas&nbsp;[...] are among the film's best.\"<ref name=\"Wise\">{{cite news |author=Wise, Damon |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/sep/12/impossible-review |title=The Impossible |newspaper=The Guardian |date=12 September 2012 |accessdate=15 October 2012}}</ref> Watts went on to be nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Academy Award]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe]] and [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role|Screen Actors Guild Award]] for Best Actress.<ref name=allmovie>{{cite web |title=Naomi Watts|work=[[Allmovie]] |url=https://www.allmovie.com/artist/naomi-watts-p75056/awards |accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Adore (film)|Adore]]'' (2013), Watts starred with [[Robin Wright]] as two childhood friends who fall in love with each other's sons. On the film, critics concluded that Watts and Wright \"give it their all, but they can't quite make ''Adore'''s trashy, absurd plot believable\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/adore_2013/|title=Adore|date=6 September 2013}}</ref> She obtained the [[Film Critics Circle of Australia|FCCA Award]] for Best Actress in 2014 for her role. The anthology comedy ''[[Movie 43]]'' (2013) featured Watts as a devoted mother, alongside Liev Schreiber.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmofilia.com/movie-43-tv-spot-no3-130141/|title=MOVIE 43 TV Spot No3 \u2013 FilmoFilia|first=Aleksandar|last=Popovic|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> ''Movie 43'' was universally panned by critics, with [[Richard Roeper]] calling it \"the ''[[Citizen Kane]]'' of awful\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/movie-43-2013|title=Movie 43 Movie Review & Film Summary (2013) \u2013 Roger Ebert|first=Richard|last=Roeper|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Laurie Collyer]]'s independent drama ''[[Sunlight Jr.]]'' (2013), Watts starred with [[Matt Dillon]] as a struggling working-class couple.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/sunlight-jr-tribeca-review-443635|title=Sunlight Jr.: Tribeca Review|author=Frank Scheck|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribecafilm.com/stories/5-norman-reedus-performances-sunlight-jr-the-walking-dead|title=5 Norman Reedus Performances You Need to Seek Out \u2013 Tribeca|accessdate=27 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822011518/https://tribecafilm.com/stories/5-norman-reedus-performances-sunlight-jr-the-walking-dead|archive-date=22 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/urbanite-1.812039/movie-review-sunlight-jr-3-stars-1.6437713 |title=Movie review: 'Sunlight Jr.' \u2013 3 stars |last=Levin |first=Robert |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20141201234719/http://www.newsday.com/urbanite-1.812039/movie-review-sunlight-jr-3-stars-1.6437713 |archivedate=1 December 2014 |date=14 November 2013 |df= }}</ref> ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', praising Watts and Dillon, wrote in its review for the film that they are \"formidable actors at the top of their game here [...] exhibiting a remarkable chemistry\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Sunlight-Jr-review-Love-in-dismal-surroundings-4983883.php|title='Sunlight Jr.' review: Love in dismal surroundings|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=14 November 2013}}</ref> Watts portrayed the title role in [[Oliver Hirschbiegel]]'s ''[[Diana (film)|Diana]]'' (her last 2013 film),<ref name=allmovie/> a biographical drama about the last two years of the life of [[Diana, Princess of Wales]]. Released amid much controversy given its subject, the film was a critical and commercial flop.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-23985665|title=Diana film slammed by British press|work=BBC News|date=6 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/diana_2013/|title=Diana|date=1 November 2013|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes}}</ref> [[James Berardinelli]] found the film to be a \"dull, pointless\" production and remarked that while Watts did a \"decent job encapsulating the look and feel of Diana\", her portrayal was \"a two-dimensional recreation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/diana|title=Diana \u2013 Reelviews Movie Reviews|first=James|last=Berardinelli|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]]'s dark comedy ''[[Birdman (film)|Birdman or (The Unexpected Virtue of Ignorance)]]'' (2014) featured Watts as the actress of a play mounted by a faded Hollywood actor (played by [[Michael Keaton]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/naomi-watts-trades-oscarbait-for-a-lighter-career-20141030-11dzto.html.|title=Naomi Watts trades Oscar-bait for a lighter career|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=30 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/10/birdman-venice-film-festival-opening-night|title=Birdman to hatch on opening night of Venice film festival|first=Xan|last=Brooks|date=10 July 2014|accessdate=27 September 2016 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3926&p=.htm |title=Weekend Report: 'Fury' Topples 'Gone Girl,' 'Birdman' Soars in Limited Release \u2013 Box Office Mojo |accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/birdman_2014/?search=birdman|title=Birdman|date=17 October 2014|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes}}</ref> The film was the subject of widespread acclaim,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Birdman-review-Inarritu-s-fine-showbiz-5842625.php|title='Birdman' review: Inarritu's fine showbiz satire of ex-superhero|accessdate=27 September 2016|date=23 October 2014}}</ref> and won four awards at the [[87th Academy Awards]] including Best Picture;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/oscar-winners-2015-academy-award-winner-list-1201439020/|title=Oscar Winners 2015: Complete List|first=Variety|last=Staff|date=23 February 2015|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> Watts and the other cast members earned the [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Cast in a Motion Picture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-sag-awards-2015-birdman-wins-cast-motion-picture-story.html|title=SAG Awards 2015: 'Birdman' wins for cast in a motion picture|first=Los Angeles|last=Times|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref>  Her other two awaiting projects were screened at the [[2014 Toronto International Film Festival]]. The dramedy ''[[St. Vincent (film)|St. Vincent]]'' starred Watts as a Russian prostitute. She learnt the accent by spending time with Russian women in a [[West Village]] spa during a six-week period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/naomi-watts-on-preparing-for-st-vincent-with-bill-murray-and-melissa-mccarthy|title=Naomi Watts on how she conquered fear of working with Bill Murray|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref> ''Los Angeles Times'' reported a dividing reaction towards her performance, asserting that her part \"put off some critics with its outrageousness\", but \"earned plenty of plaudits too\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-naomi-watts-comedies-demolition-st-vincent-birdman-20141029-story.html#page=1|title=Naomi Watts chooses comedic roles to lighten up her career|date=29 October 2014|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> Watts nabbed a Screen Actors Guild Award nomination for [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role|Outstanding Supporting Actress]]. In ''[[While We're Young (film)|While We're Young]]'', Watts starred with [[Ben Stiller]] as a New York City-based married couple who begin hanging out with a couple in their 20s. That film was an [[arthouse]] success and Watts received praise for her on-screen chemistry with Stiller.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/were-young-toronto-review-730802|title='While We're Young': Toronto Review|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/festivals/toronto-film-festival-while-were-young-1201299916/|title=Toronto Film Review: 'While We're Young'|first=Peter|last=Debruge|date=7 September 2014|accessdate=27 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/27/movies/review-in-while-were-young-a-coupling-of-gen-x-and-y.html|title=Review: In 'While We're Young,' a Coupling of Gen X and Y|date=27 March 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=27 September 2016|last1=Scott|first1=A. O.}}</ref>\n\n===Film and television balance (2015\u2013present)===\n[[File:Naomi Watts Cannes 2015 2.jpg|thumb|upright|right| Watts at the [[2015 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\n\nWatts played rebel leader [[List of The Divergent trilogy characters#Evelyn Johnson-Eaton|Evelyn Johnson-Eaton]] in ''[[The Divergent Series: Insurgent|Insurgent]]'' (2015), the second film in ''[[The Divergent Series]]'', which is based on [[Veronica Roth]]'s best-selling [[Divergent (novel)|young adult novel of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Jessica Derschowitz|title=Naomi Watts joins cast of \"Divergent\" sequels \"Insurgent,\" \"Allegiant\"|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/naomi-watts-joins-cast-of-divergent-sequels-insurgent-allegiant/|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=30 June 2014|date=4 June 2014}}</ref> Despite mixed reviews, the film was a commercial success, grossing US$274.5&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref name=\"BOOM\">{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=insurgent.htm |title=The Divergent Series: Insurgent (2015) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teen.com/2015/03/18/movies/insurgent-movie-bad-reviews/|title=33 Horrible Insurgent Reviews That'll Piss Fans the Eff Off|accessdate=20 March 2015|date=18 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827003628/http://www.teen.com/2015/03/18/movies/insurgent-movie-bad-reviews/|archive-date=27 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Watts reprised her role in the series' third instalment, ''[[The Divergent Series: Allegiant|Allegiant]]'', released on 18 March 2016, to negative reviews and lackluster box office sales.<ref name=Variety>{{cite web|first1=Marc |last1=Graser |first2=Tatiana |last2=Siegel |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117974282.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|title=Naomi Watts set for 'Birds' remake|work=Variety|date=18 October 2007|accessdate=21 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://downriversundaytimes.com/2014/08/04/celebrity-extra-262/|title=Celebrity Extra|last=Elavsky|first=Cindy|publisher=[[King Features]]|date=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nWatts starred in [[Gus Van Sant]]'s mystery drama ''[[The Sea of Trees]]'', opposite [[Matthew McConaughey]], as the wife of an American man who attempts suicide in [[Mount Fuji]]'s \"[[Suicide Forest]]\". The film premiered at the [[2015 Cannes Film Festival]] where it competed for the [[Palme d'Or]], but was heavily panned by both critics and audiences, who reportedly booed and laughed during its screening.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gus Van Sant's 'Sea of Trees' Booed at Cannes Premiere|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/gus-van-sants-sea-of-trees-booed-at-cannes-premiere-1201497795/|accessdate=15 May 2015|work=Variety|date=15 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Reinstein|first1=Mara|title=Matthew McConaughey's Film The Sea of Trees Booed, Laughed at During Cannes Film Festival|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/matthew-mcconaugheys-the-sea-of-trees-booed-at-cannes-film-festival-2015165|work=Us Weekly|accessdate=15 May 2015|date=15 May 2015}}</ref> Critic Richard Mowe stated the audience reaction should \"give the film's creative team pause for reflection about exactly where they went so badly awry.\"<ref name=\"The Sea of Trees 2015 Review\">{{cite web|last1=Mowe|first1=Richard|title=The Sea of Trees (2015) Review|url=http://www.eyeforfilm.co.uk/review/the-sea-of-trees-2015-film-review-by-richard-mowe|publisher=eyeforefilm.co.uk|accessdate=15 May 2015|date=15 May 2015}}</ref> Justin Chang of ''Variety'' also criticised the film, but commended Watts's performance for being \"solidly moving and sometimes awesomely passive-aggressive.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chang|first1=Justin|title=Cannes Film Review: 'The Sea of Trees'|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/festivals/the-sea-of-trees-review-matthew-mcconaughey-cannes-1201495483/|work=Variety|accessdate=15 May 2015|date=15 May 2015}}</ref> ''The Sea of Trees'' did not find an audience in theaters.<ref>https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=theseaoftrees.htm</ref>\n\nLike ''St. Vincent'' and ''While We're Young'' the previous year, Watts had two starring vehicles \u2014''[[Demolition (2015 film)|Demolition]]'' and ''[[Three Generations]]''\u2014 screening at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]], in 2015. In ''Demolition'', directed by [[Jean-Marc Vall\u00e9e]] and opposite [[Jake Gyllenhaal]], Watts played a customer service representative and the interest of a grieving [[investment banker]] (Gyllenhaal).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/demolition_2016/|title=Demolition}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=demolition.htm|title=Demolition (2016) \u2013 Box Office Mojo}}</ref> ''The Wrap'' felt that she \"empathetically captures [her] harried single mom\" role as she played \"both the wit and the sadness with grace\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/demolition-review-jake-gyllenhaal/|title='Demolition' Review: Jake Gyllenhaal Grapples With Delayed Grief in Dark Dramedy|date=8 April 2016}}</ref> In ''Three Generations'', directed by [[Gaby Dellal]], she appeared with [[Susan Sarandon]] and [[Elle Fanning]] as the mother of a young [[transgender]] man (Fanning). Pulled from the schedule days before its intended initial release,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/09/about-ray-susan-sarandon-elle-fanning-transgender-film-release-date-change-1201528419/|title='About Ray' Pushed From This Weekend's Release Schedule By TWC|first=Anita Busch, Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=15 September 2015}}</ref> the film subsequently opened on selected theatres in May 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/weinstein-finally-puts-transgender-teen-drama-three-generations-back-schedule-973463|title=Weinstein Co. Finally Puts Transgender Teen Drama 'Three Generations' Back on Schedule (Exclusive)|last=Siegel|first=Tatiana|date=13 February 2017|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\nWatts played Linda, the second wife of heavyweight boxer [[Chuck Wepner]] (played by Liev Schreiber) in the biographical [[sport film|sport drama]] ''[[The Bleeder]]'' (2016), revolving around the life of Wepner and his 1975 fight with [[Muhammad Ali]]. ''Variety'' wrote in its review: \"Slightly out of place as the feisty bartender who gives Wepner a second chance at his downest and outest, a spirited Naomi Watts nonetheless gives proceedings her best [[Amy Adams]] in ''[[The Fighter]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/the-bleeder-review-liev-schreiber-1201850979/|title=Film Review: 'The Bleeder'|first=Guy|last=Lodge|date=2 September 2016}}</ref> She headlined the thriller ''[[Shut In (2016 film)|Shut In]]'' (also 2016), playing a psychologist insolated with her child in a rural house during a winter storm. The film received largely negative reviews and made US$8&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/shut_in|title=Shut In}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=shutin.htm|title=Shut In (2016) \u2013 Box Office Mojo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=shutin.htm|title=Shut In (2016) \u2013 International Box Office Results \u2013 Box Office Mojo}}</ref>\n\nWatts appeared in ''[[Twin Peaks (season 3)|Twin Peaks]]'', a limited event television series and a continuation of the [[Twin Peaks|1990 show of the same name]]. It was broadcast on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] in 2017, to critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/twin-peaks-naomi-watts-tom-sizemore-david-lynch-cast-showtime-1201694524/|title=Twin Peaks: Naomi Watts|publisher=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=1 February 2016|date=15 May 2015}}</ref> Watts starred as \"a therapist who begins to develop dangerous and intimate relationships with the people in her patients' lives\" in the [[Netflix]] drama series ''[[Gypsy (TV series)|Gypsy]]'' (also 2017), and served as one of its executive producers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/08/billy-crudup-cast-netflix-psychological-thriller-series-gypsy-1201804855/|title=Billy Crudup To Star in Netflix Drama Series 'Gypsy'|publisher=Deadline Hollywood|date=17 August 2016|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/naomi-watts-star-gypsy-netflix-series-1201739078/|title=Naomi Watts To Star in Netflix Psychological Thriller Series 'Gypsy'|publisher=Deadline Hollywood|date=18 April 2016|accessdate=18 April 2016}}</ref> While response was mixed, ''Gypsy'' was cancelled by Netflix after one season.<ref>{{cite web|title='Gypsy' Canceled By Netflix After 1 Season|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/gypsy-canceled-netflix-naomi-watts-one-season-1202146744/|publisher=Deadline Hollywood|date=11 August 2017}}</ref> In ''[[The Book of Henry]]'' (2017), Watts portrayed the mother of young genius who plans save the girl next door from abuse. The film polarized critics and audiences, but ''Rolling Stone'' described her as \"a plus in any movie\" and found her to be \"excellent\" in the role.<ref>https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/the-book-of-henry-review-boy-meets-girl-ends-up-in-wtf-tearjerker-thriller-199301/</ref> In her other 2017 film, ''[[The Glass Castle (film)|The Glass Castle]]'', an adaptation of [[Jeannette Walls]]' best selling memoir of the same name, Watts played the nonconformist mother of the author.<ref>https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=theglasscastle.htm</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Watts portrayed [[Gretchen Carlson]] in the Showtime miniseries ''[[The Loudest Voice]]'' based on the book ''[[The Loudest Voice in the Room]]'' about [[Roger Ailes]]'s sexual harassment of Carlson.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\">{{cite web |last1=Andreeva |first1=Nellie |title=Russell Crowe To Star As Roger Ailes In Limited Series Greenlighted By Showtime |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/russell-crowe-star-roger-ailes-showtime-limited-series-the-loudest-voice-in-the-room-1202416042/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=23 August 2018 |date=25 June 2018}}</ref> She was cast in the ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' spin-off ''Bloodmoon'' as \"a charismatic socialite hiding a dark secret\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/game-of-thrones-prequel-pilot-naomi-watts-hbo-1202977630/|title='Game of Thrones' Prequel Casts Naomi Watts in Lead Role|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|date=30 October 2018|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=31 October 2018|last2=Otterson|first2=Joe}}</ref> but development on the series was cancelled in October 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/game-thrones-naomi-watts-led-prequel-dead-at-hbo-1250795|title='Game of Thrones': Naomi Watts-Led Prequel Dead at HBO|last1=Wigler|first1=Josh|date=29 October 2019|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=29 October 2019|last2=Lesley|first2=Goldberg}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIn 2006, Watts became a goodwill ambassador for [[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS]], which helps raise awareness of issues related to the disease. She has used her high profile and celebrity to call attention to the needs of people living with this disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/media/unaids/contentassets/documents/aboutunaids/unaidsgoodwillambassadors/GWA_Watts_en.pdf|title=UNAIDS goodwill ambassador Naomi Watts|work=UNAIDS|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=28 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013042105/http://www.unaids.org/en/media/unaids/contentassets/documents/aboutunaids/unaidsgoodwillambassadors/GWA_Watts_en.pdf|archivedate=13 October 2011}}</ref> Watts has in campaigns for fundraising, events and activities, including the 21st Annual AIDS Walk.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.acqc.org/pdf/Voices5_sum_06.pdf|title=UNAIDS goodwill ambassador Naomi Watts|work=ACQC Voices|publisher=AIDS Center of Queens County|date=Summer 2006|accessdate=28 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706113953/http://acqc.org/pdf/Voices5_sum_06.pdf|archivedate=6 July 2011}}</ref> On 1 December 2009, Watts met with [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|United Nations Secretary-General]] [[Ban Ki-moon]] at a public event commemorating World AIDS Day 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.amfar.org/community/article.aspx?id=8226|title=Light for rights: World AIDS day 2009|work=The Foundation for AIDS Research|publisher=The Foundation for AIDS Research's Official Site|date=3 December 2009|accessdate=28 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Watts attended a charity polo match in New York City along with Australian actors [[Hugh Jackman]] and [[Isla Fisher]], which was intended to raise money to help victims of the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/hugh-jackman-isla-fisher-and-naomi-watts-attend-charity-polo-match-in-new-york/story-e6frewz0-1226070384290|first=Kate|last=McMahon|title=Hugh Jackman, Isla Fisher and Naomi Watts attend charity polo match in New York|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=6 June 2011|accessdate=28 July 2011}}</ref> In 2012, she became an  ambassador for [[Pantene]]'s [[Pantene Beautiful Lengths|Beautiful Lengths]], a program that donates real-hair wigs to women with cancer. She has visited the [[St Vincent's Hospital, Sydney|St Vincent's Hospital]] in [[Sydney]] to meet some of the women the program helps.<ref>https://www.bodyandsoul.com.au/health/celebrity-profiles/naomi-watts-on-health-fitness-and-motherhood/news-story/406d64e3a8dda46793f9e0ae77a2c143</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Watts collaborated with [[Sportscraft]] and children's charity [[Barnardos]] to produce a range of namesake coats, with a percentage of sales going to the charity,<ref>https://www.vogue.com.au/fashion/news/this-is-the-most-valuable-beauty-lesson-naomi-watts-learnt-from-her-mum/news-story/c5d7e416f98accc66fb81753164d7351</ref> and was one the public figures photographed by Italian photographer Fabrizio Ferri for [[Bulgari]]'s digital campaign \"Raise Your Hand\".<ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/declaneytan/2016/07/11/naomi-watts-meg-ryan-and-other-celebrities-raise-their-hand-for-charity/#cab12e258fa7</ref> In November 2018, she hosted the Worldwide Orphans 14th Annual Gala in NYC, and teamed up with [[McDonald's]], to serve as a McHappy Day ambassador, making a special appearance and stepping behind the counter in Haberfield, Sydney.<ref>https://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/actress-naomi-watts-heading-to-australia-as-mchapp/3553288/</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Naomi Watts, Liev Schreiber.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Watts with her then-boyfriend [[Liev Schreiber]] in 2012]] \n\nWatts is pictured in her mother's arms with her father, brother, the band and other crew members, in the hardback/softcover edition of Pink Floyd drummer [[Nick Mason]]'s autobiography of the band ''Inside Out''.<ref name=\"Mason\">{{Cite book| publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson Illustrated | isbn = 978-0-297-84387-0| pages = 360 p. : ill.; 29&nbsp;cm| last = Mason| first = Nick| title = Inside out a personal history of Pink Floyd| location = London| year = 2004 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, it was reported that she had agreed to become the honorary president of [[Glantraeth F.C.]], a small football club in [[Malltraeth]], [[Anglesey]], Wales, near her grandparents' farm, where she spent time as a child.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-35473354|title=A-lister Naomi Watts links up with Anglesey football club|work=BBC News|date=2 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Relationships===\nWatts had a relationship with Australian actor [[Heath Ledger]] from August 2002 to May 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/naomi-watts-opens-about-loss-ledger-wbna28920319 |title=Scoop: Watts opens up about loss of Ledger |publisher=Today.com |date=29 January 2009 |accessdate=22 February 2011}}</ref> In the spring of 2005, Watts began a relationship with American actor [[Liev Schreiber]]. The couple's first son, Alexander \"Sasha\" Pete, was born in July 2007 in Los Angeles, and their second son, Samuel \"Sammy\" Kai, in December 2008 in New York City.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20013570,00.html |title = Liev Schreiber: 'I'm going to be a dad'|accessdate =15 December 2008 |first=Stephen|last=Silverman|date=27 February 2007 |work=People}}</ref> On 26 September 2016, Watts and Schreiber announced their split after 11 years together.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nessif|first1=Bruno|title=Liev Schreiber and Naomi Watts Split After 11 Years Together|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/797780/liev-schreiber-and-naomi-watts-split-after-11-years-together|accessdate=26 September 2016|work=[[E! News]]|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|date=26 September 2016|location=United States}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nShe considered converting to [[Buddhism]] after having gained an interest in that religion during the shooting of ''The Painted Veil'' (2006). She said of her religious beliefs, \"I have some belief but I am not a strict Buddhist or anything yet\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/entertainment/watts-trying-out-buddhism/|title=Watts drawn to Buddhism}}</ref>\n\n===Politics ===\nIn July 2019, Naomi Watts donated to the Congressional Election Campaign of [[Valerie Plame]]  for [[New Mexico's 3rd congressional district]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/breaking-bad-star-and-holocaust-denier-donate-to-former-cia-officer-valerie-plame-campaign Breaking Bad star and Holocaust denier donate to former CIA officer Valerie Plame campaign] by Caitlin Yilek, 5 August 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.krwg.org/post/ex-cia-operative-plames-house-bid-gets-many-small-donors Ex-CIA operative Plame's House bid gets many small donors] NEWS EDITOR AND PARTNERS \u2022 17 July 2019</ref>\n\n==Filmography and awards==\n{{main|Naomi Watts filmography|List of awards and nominations received by Naomi Watts}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q132616|n=no|s=no|v=no|voy=no|b=no|wikt=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|c=category:Naomi Watts}}\n* {{IMDb name|0915208}}\n* {{people.com}}\n* [http://www.unaids.org/en/aboutunaids/unaidsambassadors/naomiwatts Naomi Watts at UNAIDS.org]\n* {{Instagram|naomiwatts|Naomi Watts}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Naomi Watts|Awards for Naomi Watts]]\n|list =\n{{London Film Critics Circle Award for Actress of the Year}}\n{{Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Actress 2001\u2013present}}\n{{National Board of Review Award for Breakthrough Performance}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Actress}}\n{{San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Actress}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Actress}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watts, Naomi}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Kent]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:English film producers]]\n[[Category:English people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS activists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at North Sydney Girls High School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ysgol Gyfun Llangefni]]\n[[Category:People from Shoreham, Kent]]\n[[Category:Transcendental Meditation practitioners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "BryanGaensler", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naomi_Watts"}
{"title_page": "Edward Te Whiu", "text_new": "'''Edward Thomas Te Whiu''' (1935&ndash;1955) was a notable New Zealand  criminal and murderer. Of [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] descent, he identified with the [[Nga Puhi]] [[iwi]]. He was born in [[Waipapakauri]], [[Northland Region|Northland]], [[New Zealand]] in 1935.<ref name=\"DNZB Te Whiu\">{{DNZB|title=Edward Thomas Te Whiu|first= Sherwood|last= Young|id=5t11|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> Te Whiu was hanged at Mount Eden Prison in August 1955, after he had killed an elderly widow in [[Ngararatunua]], near [[Kamo, New Zealand|Kamo]], when an attempted burglary went wrong.<ref name=\"DNZB Te Whiu\" />\n\nEvidence was given that he had calmly cooked himself a meal in the next room to the corpse of his aged victim. The ''completely non-adjusted a-social youth'' went happily to his death. He took a cigarette an hour before the hanging, smiled and said ''\"won't it be wonderful to be in heaven where cigarettes can come flying through the air.\"'' One of his last requests was to have his religious comics thrown into his grave with him.<ref>{{cite book |last= Department of Justice |first=  |title= Crime in New Zealand: A Survey of New Zealand Criminal Behaviour |accessdate=  |edition=   |origyear= 1968 |year= 1974 |publisher= A R Shearer Government Printer |location= Wellington |isbn=  |oclc= |page= |pages= 68,70}} </ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Te Whiu, Edward Thomas}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:People from the Northland Region]]\n[[Category:People executed by New Zealand by hanging]]\n[[Category:Ng\u0101puhi]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by New Zealand]]\n[[Category:People executed for murder]]\n[[Category:Executed New Zealand people]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1950s murders in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1955 crimes in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1955 murders in Oceania]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-crime-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Edward Thomas Te Whiu''' (1935&ndash;1955) was a notable New Zealand  criminal and murderer. Of [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] descent, he identified with the [[Nga Puhi]] [[iwi]]. He was born in [[Waipapakauri]], [[Northland Region|Northland]], [[New Zealand]] in 1935.<ref name=\"DNZB Te Whiu\">{{DNZB|title=Edward Thomas Te Whiu|first= Sherwood|last= Young|id=5t11|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> Te Whiu was hanged at Mount Eden Prison in August 1955, after he had killed an elderly widow in [[Ngararatunua]], near [[Kamo, New Zealand|Kamo]], when an attempted burglary went wrong.<ref name=\"DNZB Te Whiu\" />\n\nEvidence was given that he had calmly cooked himself a meal in the next room to the corpse of his aged victim. The ''completely non-adjusted a-social youth'' went happily to his death. He took a cigarette an hour before the hanging, smiled and said ''\"won't it be wonderful to be in heaven where cigarettes can come flying through the air.\"'' One of his last requests was to have his religious comics thrown into his grave with him.<ref>{{cite book |last= Department of Justice |first=  |title= Crime in New Zealand: A Survey of New Zealand Criminal Behaviour |accessdate=  |edition=   |origyear= 1968 |year= 1974 |publisher= A R Shearer Government Printer |location= Wellington |isbn=  |oclc= |page= |pages= 68,70}} </ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Te Whiu, Edward Thomas}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:People from the Northland Region]]\n[[Category:People executed by New Zealand by hanging]]\n[[Category:Ng\u0101puhi]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by New Zealand]]\n[[Category:People executed for murder]]\n[[Category:Executed New Zealand people]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1950s murders in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1955 crimes in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1955 murders in Oceania]]\n\n{{NewZealand-crime-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Brycehughes", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Te_Whiu"}
{"title_page": "Dolly (Faur\u00e9)", "text_new": "[[File:Faure-middle-years.jpg|thumb|300px|<center>Faur\u00e9 in the 1890s</center>]]\n\nThe '''''Dolly Suite''''', [[opus number|Op.]] 56, is a collection of pieces for [[piano duet]] by [[Gabriel Faur\u00e9]]. It consists of six short pieces written or revised between 1893 and 1896, to mark the birthdays and other events in the life of the daughter of the composer's mistress, [[Emma Bardac]].\n\nAn orchestral version of the suite was scored in 1906 by [[Henri Rabaud]], and has, like the original piano duet version, been the subject of many recordings. The best-known section of the suite, the ''[[Berceuse]]'', has been arranged for several combinations of instruments. In the [[United Kingdom]] it became famous as the play-out tune to the BBC radio programme ''[[Listen with Mother]]''.\n\nThe suite, consisting of six short pieces, each with its own title: ''Berceuse'', ''Mi-a-ou'', ''Le jardin de Dolly'', ''Kitty-[[waltz (music)|valse]]'', ''Tendresse'', and ''Le pas espagnol''. The complete suite takes about fifteen minutes to perform.\n\n==Analysis==\n{{Listen|filename=Berceuse by Gabriel Faur\u00e9 op56 no1.ogg|title=Berceuse from Dolly|description=The [[Berceuse]] from Dolly by [[Gabriel Faur\u00e9]].|pos=right}}\n\nFaur\u00e9 wrote or revised the pieces between 1893 and 1896,<ref name=n61>Nectoux, p. 61</ref> for R\u00e9gina-H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Bardac (1892\u20131985), known to her family as Dolly (she was later to become Madame Gaston de Tinan),the young daughter of the singer [[Emma Bardac]], with whom Faur\u00e9 had a long-running affair.<ref name=n36>Nectoux, p. 36</ref> He was in the practice of sending pieces of music, in manuscript, to mark Dolly's birthdays and other family occasions.<ref name=a1/>\n\nIn a marked departure from his customary practice, Faur\u00e9 gave each of the six movements a descriptive, sometimes whimsical, title. Ordinarily he disliked fanciful titles for musical pieces, and maintained that he would not use even such generic titles as \"barcarolle\" unless his publishers insisted upon them. His son Philippe recalled, \"he would far rather have given his Nocturnes, Impromptus, and even his Barcarolles the simple title Piano Piece no. so-and-so\".<ref>Nectoux, p. 48</ref>\n\n;Berceuse\n''Allegretto moderato''. The ''Berceuse'', marking Dolly's first birthday, was a very early piece, composed in 1864 for Suzanne Garnier, the daughter of a family friend. In 1893 Faur\u00e9 made some small amendments and changed its title from \"La Chanson dans le jardin\" to \"Berceuse\" \u2013 that is, a cradle song.<ref name=n62>Nectoux, p. 62</ref>\n\n;Mi-a-ou\n''Allegro vivo.'' \"Mi-a-ou\" was written for Dolly's second birthday in June 1894.<ref name=n62/> The title does not refer to a pet cat, as has often been supposed,<ref name=n62/>  but to Dolly's attempts to pronounce the name of her elder brother Raoul, who later became one of Faur\u00e9's favourite pupils.<ref name=n36/> The young Dolly called her brother ''Messieu Aoul'', which Faur\u00e9 took as the original title for the piece.<ref name=n62/> In his finished manuscript the title is shortened to \"Miaou\" (without hyphens).<ref name=p82/> The Faur\u00e9 scholar [[Robert Orledge]] writes that the title \"Mi-a-ou\", like that of the \"Kitty-valse\" later in the suite, is the responsibility of Faur\u00e9's publisher, [[Julien Hamelle]].<ref>Orledge, {{p.|95}}</ref>\n\n;Le jardin de Dolly\n''Andantino''. The third section of the suite, \"Le jardin de Dolly\", was composed as a present for New Year's Day 1895. It contains a quotation from Faur\u00e9's First Violin Sonata, composed 20 years earlier.<ref name=m13>Morrison, p. 13</ref> The Faur\u00e9 scholar Jean-Michel Nectoux considers this \"perhaps the jewel of the suite, with its lovely tune, moving harmonies and limpid, subtle counterpoint.\"<ref name=n62/>\n\n;Kitty-valse\n''Tempo di valse''. The fourth piece is no more feline in its reference than \"Mi-a-ou\". The Bardacs' pet dog was called Ketty, and in Faur\u00e9's manuscript the piece is called \"Ketty-Valse\".<ref name=p82>Phillips, p. 82</ref> Nectoux calls this piece \"a kind of whirling portrait\" of the animal.<ref name=n62/>\n\n;Tendresse\n''Andante''. \"Tendresse\", written in 1896, was originally dedicated to [[Adela Maddison]], wife of a music publisher.<ref name=a1>Anderson, p. 4</ref> Like \"Le Jardin de Dolly\", this piece is lyrical, but is in a more modern style, making use of [[chromaticism]] of the kind Faur\u00e9 later deployed in his Nocturnes.<ref name=n62/>\n\n;Le pas espagnol\n''Allegro.'' The suite ends with a Spanish dance, a lively and picturesque piece of scene-painting, in the style of ''[[Espa\u00f1a (Chabrier)|Espa\u00f1a]]'' by Faur\u00e9's friend [[Emmanuel Chabrier]].<ref name=n62/>\n\n==Premiere and later versions==\n[[File:Gabriel Faur\u00e9 jouant \u00e0 quatre mains avec Melle Lombard.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Faur\u00e9 and Mlle Lombard in 1913]]\nThe first public performance of the suite was given by [[Alfred Cortot]] and [[\u00c9douard Risler]] in 1898.<ref name=n62/> Faur\u00e9 himself enjoyed taking part in performances of the work, not only in public but ''en famille'' with the young children of his friends. The photograph opposite shows the composer playing the ''secondo'' part to the ''primo'' of the young Mlle Lombard, daughter of his host and hostess at Trevano, Lake Lugano, in 1913.<ref name=n62/>\n\nCortot arranged the work for solo piano in 1899, and in 1906 [[Henri Rabaud]] orchestrated the work for full symphony orchestra. This version received its first public performance conducted by [[L\u00e9on Jehin]] in Monte Carlo in December 1906,<ref name=n62/> and this was later used to accompany \"an ingenious ballet\" with a story by [[Louis Laloy]] at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre H\u00e9bertot|Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Arts]] in Paris.<ref>Koechlin, Charles. ''Gabriel Faur\u00e9 (1845-1924).'' Translated by Leslie Orry. Dennis Dobson Ltd, London, 1946, p34 note 3.</ref>\n\nThe harpist Carlos Salzedo arranged Dolly for his Trio de Lut\u00e8ce, which consisted of flute, 'cello and harp. His arrangement was transcribed to performing parts by the members of Trio Lyra of Canada. The 'cello part was transcribed for viola, and this new arrangement was premiered in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania on June 16, 1993. A commercial recording of the work was released on the Opening Day Recordings label in 1997.\n\nThe Berceuse was the closing [[signature theme|theme]] for the long-running [[BBC Light Programme]] (and later [[BBC Home Service|Home Service]]) radio programme for small children ''[[Listen with Mother]]'' (1950\u20131982).<ref>Greenfield, Edward. [http://www.gramophone.net/Issue/Page/June%201961/38/734380/ \"Sir Thomas Beecham\"], ''[[Gramophone (magazine)|The Gramophone]]'' June 1961, p. 38</ref> It is performed in the film ''[[Bicentennial Man (film)|Bicentennial Man]]'' by Andrew and Little Miss.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0182789/soundtrack \"Soundtracks for Bicentennial Man\"], Internet Movie Database, accessed 5 November 2011</ref> Although it was written as a piano duet, there have been numerous arrangements of the Berceuse for other instruments and ensembles. Examples include versions for piano and [[glockenspiel]] by [[Evelyn Glennie]] and for two guitars recorded by [[Julian Bream]] and  [[John Williams (guitarist)|John Williams]].<ref>Bream, Julian and John Williams \"Together\", RCA Victor Gold Seal, 1993, OCLC 28391923</ref>\n\nThe Berceuse was also covered in the IDM group [[Boards of Canada]] on the second volume in their unreleased [[Old Tunes]] Saga, which was said to date back to 1995.\n\n==Recordings==\nRecordings of the suite in its original form for piano duet include those by [[Genevi\u00e8ve Joy]] and [[Jacqueline Robin|Jacqueline Bonneau]] (1955),<ref>33t Path\u00e9 DT 1026</ref>\n[[Robert Casadesus|Robert]] and [[Gaby Casadesus]] (1962),<ref>CBS LP SBRG 72050</ref>\n[[Kathryn Stott]] and [[Martin Roscoe]] (1995),<ref>Morrison, p. 5</ref>\nPierre-Alain Volondat and Patrick Hooge (2000),<ref>Anderson, p. 2</ref> as well as\n[[Pascal Rog\u00e9|Pascal]] and Ami Rog\u00e9.<ref>ONYX, Pascal and Ami Rog\u00e9, Music for piano duo, ''Wedding Cake''</ref>\n\nAmong recordings of the orchestral version are those by the [[Orchestre National de France|Orchestre national de l'ORTF]] conducted by [[Thomas Beecham|Sir Thomas Beecham]] (1959),<ref>EMI CD CDM 7-63379-2</ref> the [[Boston Symphony Orchestra]] conducted by [[Seiji Ozawa]] (1988),<ref>DG CD 423 089-2GH</ref> and the [[BBC Philharmonic]] conducted by [[Yan Pascal Tortelier]] (1995).<ref>Chandos CD CHAN 9416</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Anderson |first=Keith |year=2000|title=''Notes to'' Faur\u00e9 \u2013 Four-hand Piano Music|location=Hong Kong |publisher=Naxos Records |oclc=163133009 }}\n* {{cite book|last=Morrison |first=Bryce |year=1995 |title=''Notes to'' The Complete Piano Music of Gabriel Faur\u00e9 |location=London |publisher= Hyperion Records|oclc=224489565 }}\n* {{cite book|last= Nectoux |first= Jean-Michel |authorlink=Jean-Michel Nectoux |others=Roger Nichols (trans)|year= 1991|title= Gabriel Faur\u00e9 \u2013 A Musical Life |location= Cambridge |publisher= Cambridge University Press |isbn= 0-521-23524-3}}\n* {{cite book|last= Orledge |first= Robert |authorlink=Robert Orledge |year= 1979|title=Gabriel Faur\u00e9 |url= https://archive.org/details/gabrielfaur0000orle |url-access= registration |location= London |publisher= Eulenburg Books |isbn= 0-903873-40-0}}\n* {{cite book|last= Phillips |first=G. M. |year= 1999|title= Gabriel Faur\u00e9 \u2013 A guide to research |location= Connecticut |publisher= Garland Publishing |isbn= 0-8240-7073-9}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMSLP2|cname=Dolly|work=Dolly_Suite,_Op.56_(Faur%C3%A9,_Gabriel)}}\n\n{{Gabriel Faur\u00e9}}\n{{italic title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dolly (Faure)}}\n[[Category:Compositions by Gabriel Faur\u00e9]]\n[[Category:Compositions for piano four-hands]]\n[[Category:Suites (music)]]\n[[Category:1897 compositions]]\n[[Category:Orchestral suites]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Faure-middle-years.jpg|thumb|300px|<center>Faur\u00e9 in the 1890s</center>]]\n\nThe '''''Dolly Suite''''', [[opus number|Op.]] 56, is a collection of pieces for [[piano duet]] by [[Gabriel Faur\u00e9]]. It consists of six short pieces written or revised between 1893 and 1896, to mark the birthdays and other events in the life of the daughter of the composer's mistress, [[Emma Bardac]].\n\nAn orchestral version of the suite was scored in 1906 by [[Henri Rabaud]], and has, like the original piano duet version, been the subject of many recordings. The best-known section of the suite, the ''[[Berceuse]]'', has been arranged for several combinations of instruments. In the [[United Kingdom]] it became famous as the play-out tune to the BBC radio programme ''[[Listen with Mother]]''.\n\nThe suite, consisting of six short pieces, each with its own title: ''Berceuse'', ''Mi-a-ou'', ''Le jardin de Dolly'', ''Kitty-[[waltz (music)|valse]]'', ''Tendresse'', and ''Le pas espagnol''. The complete suite takes about fifteen minutes to perform.\n\n==Analysis==\n{{Listen|filename=Berceuse by Gabriel Faur\u00e9 op56 no1.ogg|title=Berceuse from Dolly|description=The [[Berceuse]] from Dolly by [[Gabriel Faur\u00e9]].|pos=right}}\n\nFaur\u00e9 wrote or revised the pieces between 1893 and 1896,<ref name=n61>Nectoux, p. 61</ref> for R\u00e9gina-H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Bardac (1892\u20131985), known to her family as Dolly (she was later to become Madame Gaston de Tinan),the young daughter of the singer [[Emma Bardac]], with whom Faur\u00e9 had a long-running affair.<ref name=n36>Nectoux, p. 36</ref> He was in the practice of sending pieces of music, in manuscript, to mark Dolly's birthdays and other family occasions.<ref name=a1/>\n\nIn a marked departure from his customary practice, Faur\u00e9 gave each of the six movements a descriptive, sometimes whimsical, title. Ordinarily he disliked fanciful titles for musical pieces, and maintained that he would not use even such generic titles as \"barcarolle\" unless his publishers insisted upon them. His son Philippe recalled, \"he would far rather have given his Nocturnes, Impromptus, and even his Barcarolles the simple title Piano Piece no. so-and-so\".<ref>Nectoux, p. 48</ref>\n\n;Berceuse\n''Allegretto moderato''. The ''Berceuse'', marking Dolly's first birthday, was a very early piece, composed in 1864 for Suzanne Garnier, the daughter of a family friend. In 1893 Faur\u00e9 made some small amendments and changed its title from \"La Chanson dans le jardin\" to \"Berceuse\" \u2013 that is, a cradle song.<ref name=n62>Nectoux, p. 62</ref>\n\n;Mi-a-ou\n''Allegro vivo.'' \"Mi-a-ou\" was written for Dolly's second birthday in June 1894.<ref name=n62/> The title does not refer to a pet cat, as has often been supposed,<ref name=n62/>  but to Dolly's attempts to pronounce the name of her elder brother Raoul, who later became one of Faur\u00e9's favourite pupils.<ref name=n36/> The young Dolly called her brother ''Messieu Aoul'', which Faur\u00e9 took as the original title for the piece.<ref name=n62/> In his finished manuscript the title is shortened to \"Miaou\" (without hyphens).<ref name=p82/> The Faur\u00e9 scholar [[Robert Orledge]] writes that the title \"Mi-a-ou\", like that of the \"Kitty-valse\" later in the suite, is the responsibility of Faur\u00e9's publisher, [[Julien Hamelle]].<ref>Orledge, {{p.|95}}</ref>\n\n;Le jardin de Dolly\n''Andantino''. The third section of the suite, \"Le jardin de Dolly\", was composed as a present for New Year's Day 1895. It contains a quotation from Faur\u00e9's First Violin Sonata, composed 20 years earlier.<ref name=m13>Morrison, p. 13</ref> The Faur\u00e9 scholar Jean-Michel Nectoux considers this \"perhaps the jewel of the suite, with its lovely tune, moving harmonies and limpid, subtle counterpoint.\"<ref name=n62/>\n\n;Kitty-valse\n''Tempo di valse''. The fourth piece is no more feline in its reference than \"Mi-a-ou\". The Bardacs' pet dog was called Ketty, and in Faur\u00e9's manuscript the piece is called \"Ketty-Valse\".<ref name=p82>Phillips, p. 82</ref> Nectoux calls this piece \"a kind of whirling portrait\" of the animal.<ref name=n62/>\n\n;Tendresse\n''Andante''. \"Tendresse\", written in 1896, was originally dedicated to [[Adela Maddison]], wife of a music publisher.<ref name=a1>Anderson, p. 4</ref> Like \"Le Jardin de Dolly\", this piece is lyrical, but is in a more modern style, making use of [[chromaticism]] of the kind Faur\u00e9 later deployed in his Nocturnes.<ref name=n62/>\n\n;Le pas espagnol\n''Allegro.'' The suite ends with a Spanish dance, a lively and picturesque piece of scene-painting, in the style of ''[[Espa\u00f1a (Chabrier)|Espa\u00f1a]]'' by Faur\u00e9's friend [[Emmanuel Chabrier]].<ref name=n62/>\n\n==Premiere and later versions==\n[[File:Gabriel Faur\u00e9 jouant \u00e0 quatre mains avec Melle Lombard.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Faur\u00e9 and Mlle Lombard in 1913]]\nThe first public performance of the suite was given by [[Alfred Cortot]] and [[\u00c9douard Risler]] in 1898.<ref name=n62/> Faur\u00e9 himself enjoyed taking part in performances of the work, not only in public but ''en famille'' with the young children of his friends. The photograph opposite shows the composer playing the ''secondo'' part to the ''primo'' of the young Mlle Lombard, daughter of his host and hostess at Trevano, Lake Lugano, in 1913.<ref name=n62/>\n\nCortot arranged the work for solo piano in 1899, and in 1906 [[Henri Rabaud]] orchestrated the work for full symphony orchestra. This version received its first public performance conducted by [[L\u00e9on Jehin]] in Monte Carlo in December 1906,<ref name=n62/> and this was later used to accompany \"an ingenious ballet\" with a story by [[Louis Laloy]] at the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre H\u00e9bertot|Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Arts]] in Paris.<ref>Koechlin, Charles. ''Gabriel Faur\u00e9 (1845-1924).'' Translated by Leslie Orry. Dennis Dobson Ltd, London, 1946, p34 note 3.</ref>\n\nThe Berceuse was the closing [[signature theme|theme]] for the long-running [[BBC Light Programme]] (and later [[BBC Home Service|Home Service]]) radio programme for small children ''[[Listen with Mother]]'' (1950\u20131982).<ref>Greenfield, Edward. [http://www.gramophone.net/Issue/Page/June%201961/38/734380/ \"Sir Thomas Beecham\"], ''[[Gramophone (magazine)|The Gramophone]]'' June 1961, p. 38</ref> It is performed in the film ''[[Bicentennial Man (film)|Bicentennial Man]]'' by Andrew and Little Miss.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0182789/soundtrack \"Soundtracks for Bicentennial Man\"], Internet Movie Database, accessed 5 November 2011</ref> Although it was written as a piano duet, there have been numerous arrangements of the Berceuse for other instruments and ensembles. Examples include versions for piano and [[glockenspiel]] by [[Evelyn Glennie]] and for two guitars recorded by [[Julian Bream]] and  [[John Williams (guitarist)|John Williams]].<ref>Bream, Julian and John Williams \"Together\", RCA Victor Gold Seal, 1993, OCLC 28391923</ref>\n\nThe Berceuse was also covered in the IDM group [[Boards of Canada]] on the second volume in their unreleased [[Old Tunes]] Saga, which was said to date back to 1995.\n\n==Recordings==\nRecordings of the suite in its original form for piano duet include those by [[Genevi\u00e8ve Joy]] and [[Jacqueline Robin|Jacqueline Bonneau]] (1955),<ref>33t Path\u00e9 DT 1026</ref>\n[[Robert Casadesus|Robert]] and [[Gaby Casadesus]] (1962),<ref>CBS LP SBRG 72050</ref>\n[[Kathryn Stott]] and [[Martin Roscoe]] (1995),<ref>Morrison, p. 5</ref>\nPierre-Alain Volondat and Patrick Hooge (2000),<ref>Anderson, p. 2</ref> as well as\n[[Pascal Rog\u00e9|Pascal]] and Ami Rog\u00e9.<ref>ONYX, Pascal and Ami Rog\u00e9, Music for piano duo, ''Wedding Cake''</ref>\n\nAmong recordings of the orchestral version are those by the [[Orchestre National de France|Orchestre national de l'ORTF]] conducted by [[Thomas Beecham|Sir Thomas Beecham]] (1959),<ref>EMI CD CDM 7-63379-2</ref> the [[Boston Symphony Orchestra]] conducted by [[Seiji Ozawa]] (1988),<ref>DG CD 423 089-2GH</ref> and the [[BBC Philharmonic]] conducted by [[Yan Pascal Tortelier]] (1995).<ref>Chandos CD CHAN 9416</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Anderson |first=Keith |year=2000|title=''Notes to'' Faur\u00e9 \u2013 Four-hand Piano Music|location=Hong Kong |publisher=Naxos Records |oclc=163133009 }}\n* {{cite book|last=Morrison |first=Bryce |year=1995 |title=''Notes to'' The Complete Piano Music of Gabriel Faur\u00e9 |location=London |publisher= Hyperion Records|oclc=224489565 }}\n* {{cite book|last= Nectoux |first= Jean-Michel |authorlink=Jean-Michel Nectoux |others=Roger Nichols (trans)|year= 1991|title= Gabriel Faur\u00e9 \u2013 A Musical Life |location= Cambridge |publisher= Cambridge University Press |isbn= 0-521-23524-3}}\n* {{cite book|last= Orledge |first= Robert |authorlink=Robert Orledge |year= 1979|title=Gabriel Faur\u00e9 |url= https://archive.org/details/gabrielfaur0000orle |url-access= registration |location= London |publisher= Eulenburg Books |isbn= 0-903873-40-0}}\n* {{cite book|last= Phillips |first=G. M. |year= 1999|title= Gabriel Faur\u00e9 \u2013 A guide to research |location= Connecticut |publisher= Garland Publishing |isbn= 0-8240-7073-9}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMSLP2|cname=Dolly|work=Dolly_Suite,_Op.56_(Faur%C3%A9,_Gabriel)}}\n\n{{Gabriel Faur\u00e9}}\n{{italic title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dolly (Faure)}}\n[[Category:Compositions by Gabriel Faur\u00e9]]\n[[Category:Compositions for piano four-hands]]\n[[Category:Suites (music)]]\n[[Category:1897 compositions]]\n[[Category:Orchestral suites]]\n", "name_user": "Michilds1944", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePremiere and later versions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dolly_(Faur%C3%A9)"}
{"title_page": "CBS This Morning", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = CBS This Morning\n| image                    = CBS This Morning.svg\n| caption                  = \n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = [[News program]]\n| creator                  = \n| director                 = \n| presenter                = {{Plainlist |<!-- Per [[Template:Infobox television]], it states: \"The show's presenter or presenters. Separate multiple entries using {{Plainlist}} or {{Unbulleted list}}. Presenters are listed in original credit order followed by order in which new presenters joined the show. Years or seasons should not be included.\" -->\n* '''Weekday'''\n* [[Gayle King]]\n* [[Anthony Mason (journalist)|Anthony Mason]]\n* [[Tony Dokoupil]]\n* {{small|(for past weekday anchors, [[#Former on-air staff|see section]])}}\n* '''Saturday'''\n* [[Dana Jacobson]]\n* [[Michelle Miller]]\n* [[Jeff Glor]]\n* {{small|(for past Saturday anchors, [[#Saturday edition|see section]])}}\n| theme_music_composer     = {{Plainlist |\n* Paul Evans and Red Nienkirchen (1989\u201390)<ref>Closing Credits, \"CBS This Morning,\" [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5249gWAln2M October 6, 1989].</ref>\n* [[Carly Simon]] and Peter Fish (1996\u201399)\n* Joel Beckerman (2012\u2013)\n}}\n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = {{Plainlist |\n* 12 (1987\u201399)\n* 6 (2012\u2013)}}\n}}\n| num_episodes             = {{Plainlist |\n* 3,110 (1987\u201399)\n* 1,667<!--Update ONLY at the end of the work week on Friday--> (2012\u2013)\n* (as of May 20, 2018)\n}}\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = \n| producer                 = \n| location                 = {{Plainlist |\n* Studio 57\n* [[CBS Broadcast Center]]\n* [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n}}\n| camera                   = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 120 minutes (including commercials)\n| company                  = [[CBS News|CBS News Productions]]\n| distributor              = \n| network                  = [[CBS]]\n| picture_format           = {{Plainlist |\n* [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]]; 1987\u201399)\n* [[1080i]] ([[high-definition television|HDTV]]; 2012\u2013)\n* (downconverted to [[letterboxing (filming)|letterboxed]] 480i for SDTV sets)\n}}\n| first_aired              = '''Original series:'''<br>{{Start date|1987|11|30}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|1999|10|29}}<br>'''Revival series:'''<br>{{Start date|2012|1|09}} \u2013 {{End date|present}}\n| preceded_by              = ''[[The Early Show]]'' (1999\u20132012)\n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = ''[[CBS Evening News]]''<br>''[[CBS Morning News]]''<br>''[[CBS Overnight News]]''\n| website                  = http://www.cbsnews.com/cbsthismorning\n| production_website       = \n| image_alt                = \n| channel                  = \n| first_run                = \n| released                 = \n}}\n\n'''''CBS This Morning''''' is an American [[Breakfast television|morning television program]] that is broadcast on [[CBS]]. The program, which shares its title with a more traditionally formatted morning program that aired on the network from 1987 to 1999, airs Monday through Saturday. It airs live from 7:00 to 9:00&nbsp;a.m. in the [[Eastern Time Zone]].  On weekdays, it airs on [[broadcast delay|tape-delay]] in the [[Central Time Zone|Central]] and [[Mountain Time Zone]]s; stations in the [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific]], [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska]] and [[Hawaii-Aleutian Time Zone|Hawaii Time Zone]]s (as well as Arizona from mid-March to early November) receive an updated feed with a specialized opening and updated live reports. Stations outside the Eastern Time Zone carry the Saturday broadcast at varied times. It is the tenth distinct morning news-features program format that CBS has aired since 1954, having replaced ''[[The Early Show]]'' on January 9, 2012.\n\nThe program emphasizes general national and international news stories and in-depth reports throughout each edition, although it also includes live in-studio and pre-taped interviews. The format was chosen as an alternative to the [[soft news]] and lifestyle-driven formats of competitors ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'' and ''[[Good Morning America]]'' following the first hour or half-hour of those broadcasts, in an attempt to give the program a competitive edge with its [[hard news]] format. (With the exception of CBS News Sunday Morning, CBS has historically placed a distant third in the [[Nielsen ratings|ratings]] among the network morning shows.)\n\n==History==\n\n===''CBS This Morning'' (first incarnation) and ''The Early Show''===\nThe original incarnation of ''CBS This Morning'' made its debut on November 30, 1987, with hosts [[Harry Smith (US journalist)|Harry Smith]], former ''[[Good Morning America]]'' news anchor [[Kathleen Sullivan (journalist)|Kathleen Sullivan]], and [[Mark McEwen]], a holdover from the show's infotainment-intensive predecessor ''[[The Early Show#The Morning Program|The Morning Program]]'' as weather caster and announcer. Sullivan was replaced by [[Paula Zahn]] on February 26, 1990. Beginning on October 26, 1992, in an effort to stop [[network affiliate|affiliates]] from dropping the program, CBS increased the amount of time available during the broadcast for local stations, most of which air their own early morning newscasts before the national news program. Despite a far more successful team in Smith, Zahn and McEwen, ''CBS This Morning'' continued to languish in third place. It was, however, far more competitive than any of its predecessors. A new set and live format introduced in October 1995 had little effect on the ratings.{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n\nSmith and Zahn left the program on June 14, 1996, with [[CBS News]] correspondents [[Harold Dow]] and [[Erin Moriarty]] anchoring ''CBS This Morning'' for seven weeks until a new format was in place. In August 1996, the program was revamped again, as simply ''This Morning'', with McEwen and [[Jane Robelot]] as co-hosts, news anchor [[Jose Diaz-Balart]] (succeeded by Cynthia Bowers, then [[Thalia Assuras]], and finally [[Julie Chen]]) and [[Craig Allen (meteorologist)|Craig Allen]] (of [[WCBS-TV]] and [[WCBS (AM)|WCBS-AM]] in [[New York City]]) serving as weather anchor.\n\nA new format was created where local stations could opt to air their own newscast from 7 to 8 a.m. local time, interspersed with inserts from the national broadcast; the second hour of the national broadcast would then air uninterrupted from 8 to 9 a.m. Ratings went up slightly, and at one point in 1998 the program even moved ahead of ''Good Morning America''. But its ratings success was also brief, and CBS announced its decision to cancel the program in early 1999. Robelot left ''This Morning'' in June 1999 after it was revealed that the program would be replaced. Assuras served as co-anchor and Chen as newsreader for the show's remaining five months. McEwen left the show at the end of September 1999 to prepare for the launch of ''The Early Show'' and was replaced by [[Russ Mitchell]], who formerly conducted sports segments.\n\n''This Morning'' ended on October 29, 1999 after twelve years. It was replaced by ''[[The Early Show]]'', which debuted the following Monday, November 1. Though it had occasional peaks in the [[The Early Show#Ratings|ratings]], ''The Early Show'' was a perennial third-place finisher behind [[NBC]]'s ''Today'' and [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''Good Morning America''. In its last year, ''The Early Show'' shied away from the news, features, light stories and \"[[infotainment]]\" approach used by the program since its debut, that it based off the formats of its two main competitors.\n\n===Development and revival===\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Participates in an Interview With Gayle King of CBS (48584861642).jpg|thumb|[[Gayle King]] interviews Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] in 2019]]\nOn November 15, 2011, CBS News announced that ''The Early Show'' would be cancelled, and that the news division would overhaul its morning news program effective January 9, 2012. The news division's chairman [[Jeff Fager]] and president David Rhodes revealed at the official announcement that day that the revamped and retitled program would \"redefine the morning television landscape\" \u2013 meaning that rather than replicate the relaxed lifestyle-driven styles of ''Today'' and ''Good Morning America'', the new format would feature a mix of \"[[hard news]]\" (a CBS News hallmark), analysis and discussion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Revamped CBS Morning Show With Charlie Rose & Gayle King To Premiere January 9|url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/11/cbs-confirms-plan-for-new-morning-show-with-charlie-rose-gayle-king|author=The Deadline|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref> On December 1, 2011, the title of the new show was revealed as ''CBS This Morning'',<ref>{{cite news|title=The New CBS News Morning Show Gets a Name: \u2018CBS This Morning\u2019 |url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/the-new-cbs-morning-show-gets-a-name-cbs-this-morning_b100534|work=[[AdWeek|TVNewser]]|publisher=[[Mediabistro.com]] |date=December 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=CBS' New Morning Show to Be Called \u2018This Morning' |url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/programming/cbs-new-morning-show-be-called-%E2%80%98-morning/38792|magazine=[[Broadcasting & Cable]] |accessdate=June 2, 2017}}</ref> marking a return of the name to the morning newscast since 1999.\n\nThe founding [[executive producer]] of ''CBS This Morning'' was [[Chris Licht]], who was hired by CBS in the spring of 2011 after serving as executive producer of [[MSNBC]]'s morning news-discussion program ''[[Morning Joe]]''. Licht's move to CBS led to speculation that ''Morning Joe'' hosts [[Joe Scarborough]] and [[Mika Brzezinski]] would follow Licht to CBS, as their contracts with MSNBC were set to expire;<ref>{{cite news|title=CBS Attempts To Recruit Morning Joe And Mika For Morning Show|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/cbs-attempts-to-recruit-morning-joe-and-mika-for-morning-show |work=[[Mediaite]]|date=May 3, 2011}}</ref> though Scarborough and Brzezinski confirmed contemplating offers from CBS and other networks, they signed a new contract with MSNBC out of a belief that their interview-intensive approach could not be duplicated on broadcast television.<ref>{{cite news|title=TCA: MSNBC's Joe Scarborough, Mika Brzezinski Admit CBS News Attempted to Poach Them|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/joe-scarborough-mika-brzezinski-msnbc-tca-279379|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nCBS instead tapped a trio of noted television veterans for the weekday edition of ''CBS This Morning'': ''Early Show'' holdover [[Erica Hill]], [[Gayle King]] and [[Charlie Rose]]. Licht describes Rose, who previously hosted CBS's former overnight news program ''[[CBS News Nightwatch]]'' (which was replaced by ''[[Up to the Minute]]'' and later ''[[CBS Overnight News]]'') in the 1980s, and has also served as a part-time correspondent for occasional segments since 2008 on the long-running newsmagazine ''[[60 Minutes]]'', as \"an incredible interviewer.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Charlie Rose, Gayle King to Headline New CBS Morning News |url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/charlie-rose-gayle-king-to-headline-new-cbs-morning-news_b93969#more-93969|author=Chris Ariens |work=TVNewser |publisher=Mediabistro.com |date=November 10, 2011|accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref><ref name= TVGuideOnCBSThisMorning>{{cite news|title=CBS' Morning Glory?|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Biz-CBS-Morning-1041249.aspx|work=The Biz column|publisher=[[TV Guide]]|date=January 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nLicht promised an \"outside the box\" approach to ''CBS This Morning'', insisting that the show would not include forced anchor banter, cooking segments, \"comedic weather forecasters, [or] cheering fans on an outdoor plaza.\"<ref name=\"TVGuideOnCBSThisMorning\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.boston.com/2012-01-02/ae/30582004_1_robin-roberts-james-goldston-erica-hill|title=Something new coming to morning television|date=January 2, 2012|work=[[Boston Globe]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|access-date=March 23, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516122827/http://articles.boston.com/2012-01-02/ae/30582004_1_robin-roberts-james-goldston-erica-hill|archive-date=May 16, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"TVNewserKickoff\">{{cite news|url=https://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/cbs-kicks-off-cbs-this-morning_b105740|title=CBS Kicks Off 'CBS This Morning'|date=January 9, 2012|work=[[AdWeek|TVNewser]]|publisher=[[Mediabistro.com]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Since revival ===\nOn July 26, 2012, CBS announced that its Chief [[The White House|White House]] Correspondent [[Norah O'Donnell]] would replace Hill starting in September 2012. Hill was pulled from the program immediately after the announcement (an absence which was not explained on the broadcast),<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Top of the Morning (book)|Top of the Morning: Inside the Cutthroat World of Morning TV]]|author=[[Brian Stelter]]|publisher=[[Grand Central Publishing]]|date=April 23, 2013}}</ref> and was eventually released from her CBS contract (Hill joined NBC in November 2012, becoming a co-host of [[Weekend Today|weekend editions]] of ''Today'').\n\nOn November 20, 2017, Rose was fired by CBS following a report in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' in which eight women accused him of sexual harassment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/eight-women-say-charlie-rose-sexually-harassed-them--with-nudity-groping-and-lewd-calls/2017/11/20/9b168de8-caec-11e7-8321-481fd63f174d_story.html|title=Eight women say Charlie Rose sexually harassed them \u2014 with nudity, groping and lewd calls|last=Carmon|first=Irin|date=November 20, 2017|work=Washington Post|accessdate=December 1, 2017|last2=Brittain|first2=Amy|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> King and O'Donnell addressed the issue on the show.<ref>{{Citation|last=Washington Free Beacon|title=CBS hosts address suspension of Charlie Rose over sexual harassment|date=2017-11-21|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p6GbHFB3da0|accessdate=2017-12-01}}</ref> In January 2018, it was announced that [[John Dickerson (journalist)|John Dickerson]] (moderator of ''[[Face the Nation]]'') would join the program as the third co-anchor.<ref name=\"CBS 1\">{{cite news|title=John Dickerson named new ''CBS This Morning'' co-host|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/john-dickerson-cbs-this-morning-new-co-host-announced-today/|accessdate=January 9, 2018|work=[[CBS News]]|publisher=[[CBS Corporation]]|date=January 9, 2018|location=United States|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn May 6, 2019, it was announced that Dickerson and O'Donnell would leave ''CBS This Morning'', with Dickerson moving to ''60 Minutes'' and O'Donnell to ''[[CBS Evening News]]''. [[Anthony Mason (journalist)|Anthony Mason]] and Tony Dokoupil were named as successors, and made their debuts on May 20, 2019, alongside King.<ref name=\"TVLine 1\">{{cite web |last=Iannucci |first=Rebecca |title=''CBS This Morning'' Confirms New Anchor Lineup, Norah O'Donnell to Take Over ''Evening News'' This Summer \u2014 Watch |url=https://tvline.com/2019/05/06/norah-odonnell-cbs-evening-news-anchor-gayle-king-john-dickerson/ |website=[[TVLine]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=May 6, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506135354/https://tvline.com/2019/05/06/norah-odonnell-cbs-evening-news-anchor-gayle-king-john-dickerson/ |archivedate=May 6, 2019 |location=United States |date=May 6, 2019}}</ref> O'Donnell's last day on the show was May 16, 2019 followed by John Dickerson on May 17, 2019.\n\n==Format==\nBoth hours begin with the \"EyeOpener,\" a fast-paced 90-second video montage of the day's top stories, ending with overnight sports highlights clips and quips from late-night talk shows. The first hour of the show is more news-intensive, with more original journalism and analysis than the second hour.<ref name=TVGuideOnCBSThisMorning/> The 8:00 hour begins with the \"EyeOpener @ 8,\" recaps the first hour's news, leads into a brief summary of the morning's news headlines, and then shifts its focus to interviews and discussion (\u00e0 la ''Morning Joe'') and lighter fare.\n\n===Weather reports===\n\nTrue to Licht's \"no comedic weather\" promise, the show does not include any standalone national weather segments<ref>{{cite magazine|title=CBS: We're going hard news in the am|url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com/artman2/publish/Dayparts_update_51/CBS-We-re-going-hard-news-in-the-a-m-.asp|author=Bill Cromwell|magazine=Media Life Magazine|date=November 16, 2011|accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref> \u2013 this makes ''CBS This Morning'' the only national morning news program on any of the [[Big Three television networks|\"Big Three\" networks]] not to include such a segment, although time is allotted for CBS affiliates to insert their own local weather forecasts (with national maps and forecasts or a text-only list of forecasts for individual cities nationwide provided for affiliates that do not insert their own weather updates, particularly those that do not have a news department).\n\nHowever, the program will use local [[meteorologists]] from CBS stations to provide the forecast during major [[severe weather]] events (such as hurricanes, wildfires, and blizzards). Most frequently, meteorologists from one of CBS's [[owned-and-operated station]]s - such as Danielle Niles of [[Boston]] O&O [[WBZ-TV]], [[Megan Glaros]] of [[Chicago]] O&O [[WBBM-TV]] and [[Lonnie Quinn]] (former meteorologist for the program's Saturday edition) of [[flagship (broadcasting)|flagship]] New York City O&O [[WCBS-TV]] - appear weekdays (as needed), and Ed Curran of [[Chicago]] O&O [[WBBM-TV]] works the Saturday edition (when necessary).\n\n===Local news cutaways===\n\nFor stations that do not make use of the local news cutaways at :26 and :56 past the hour (including CBS affiliates that do not have a news department), the program uses a taped story introduced by that day's ''[[CBS Morning News]]'' anchor during that time; previously it contained a [[happy talk]] segment between the anchors and panelists.  This was similar to what was done during the 1981-87 run of the CBS Morning News.\n\n===West coast===\n\nFor the [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific]], [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska]] and [[Hawaii\u2013Aleutian Time Zone]]s (along with most of [[Arizona]] during [[daylight saving time]]), an updated version of the broadcast incorporates an additional greeting to those viewers (\"Good morning to our viewers in the West! and \"As you are waking up in the West...\"), along with updated reports previously denoted by the reporter specifically acknowledging the viewers in that part of the country (e.g., \"Good morning and Good morning to our viewers watching us in the West\").\n\n===Studio===\n{{Quote_box|width=26%|align=right|quote=\"With a wall this big, something important better be happening on the inside.<br>There is.<br>Sorry for the mess. We\u2019re busy building you a better morning.\"|source=\u2014A message adorning the [[CBS Broadcast Center]], as featured in a December 2011 promo for ''CBS This Morning''<ref>{{cite news|title=What's Going on Behind This Wall?|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/whats-going-on-behind-this-wall_b95706|work=TVNewser|publisher=Mediabistro.com|date=November 1, 2011}}</ref>}}\n''CBS This Morning'' operates out of a set in Studio 57 at the [[CBS Broadcast Center]] (numbered for the street address in [[Manhattan]], West 57th Street). The new set was originally planned for use by ''The Early Show'' before its cancellation; that program was based out of the windowed [[General Motors Building (New York)|General Motors Building]] during its entire run, which was shared with the network's [[NFL on CBS|NFL]] [[pre-game show]] ''[[The NFL Today]]'' at times, though during the final year of ''The Early Show'' the windows were covered at all times due to the change to a hard-news focus.<ref>{{cite news|title=''The Early Show'' Leaving GM Building For CBS Broadcast Center, New Studio To Have Different Look |url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/the-early-show-leaving-gm-building-for-cbs-broadcast-center-new-studio-to-have-different-look_b85286 |work=TVNewser |publisher=Mediabistro.com |date=September 16, 2011}}</ref> A section of the studio's exterior, covered in white walls and adorned with the [[CBS Eye]] logo (and also bearing the message shown at right), was featured in promos for the show that began airing in early December 2011.<ref name=CBSThisMorningPreviewed/> [[CBS Evening News]] has shared Studio 57 with ''CBS This Morning'' since December 2016, when the former program moved from its longtime home at Studio 47.<ref>{{cite web|title=A look back at \u2018CBS Evening News\u2019 in Studio 47 |url=https://www.newscaststudio.com/2016/12/07/cbs-evening-news-studio-47/ |work=Newscast Studio |date=December 7, 2016 |accessdate=September 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBits and pieces of the ''CBS This Morning'' set were revealed in promos and web videos released prior to the program's debut,<ref name=CBSThisMorningPreviewed>{{cite news|title='CBS This Morning' debuts Monday, January 9|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/8301-500202_162-57352425/cbs-this-morning-debuts-monday-jan-9/?tag=cbsnewsTwoColLowerPromoArea |work=CBSNews.com|date=January 4, 2012|accessdate=January 7, 2012}}</ref> with the full set unveiled during the January 2012 premiere. Some of the set's features include:<ref name=TVNewserKickoff/>\n* Real exposed brick walls and dark hardwood flooring\n* An in-the-round anchor desk, topped in clear [[lucite]] and etched with the famous \"Eyemark\", as well as additional \"prong\" sections which can be removed if necessary\n* Moveable monitors, allowing guests who appear via satellite to \"sit\" alongside their interviewers at the anchor desk\n* Various items representing CBS News's legacy (most prominently a [[Goode homolosine projection|world map]] from the venerated [[Walter Cronkite]] tenure of the ''[[CBS Evening News]]'')\n* An adjoining newsroom (which was not ready in time for the premiere), complete with large windows facing the street (allowing passers-by to look in)\n* A visible [[green room]] (complete with the only couch on the set), allowing viewers to catch a glimpse of behind-the-scenes action\n\nAlso included on the set, as reported by ''[[TV Guide]]'' reporter Stephen Battaglio, is an [[Oakland Athletics]] baseball cap; executive producer Chris Licht included it to remind his staff of the sports film ''[[Moneyball (film)|Moneyball]]'', whose central character (team executive [[Billy Beane]], played in the film by [[Brad Pitt]]) took an \"outside-the-box\" approach that Licht hopes ''CBS This Morning'' replicates (Licht has called the show \"The ''Moneyball'' of TV\" \u2013 a take-off on the methodology featured in the 2011 film \u2013 and screened the film prior to the premiere for ''CBS This Morning'' staff as a motivational tool).<ref name=TVGuideOnCBSThisMorning/>\n\nIn the wake of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] and the associated closure of the CBS Broadcast Center on March 11, 2020 for disinfection, ''CBS This Morning'' was briefly re-located to the Washington, D.C. studio of the ''[[CBS Evening News]]'' for two editions. After the facility was closed once more on March 18, the program began broadcasting from the [[Ed Sullivan Theater]] on the stage of ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'' (where Licht now serves as producer).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cbs-news-film-morning-show-late-shows-ed-sullivan-theater-1285179|title=CBS News to Film Morning Show From 'Late Show's' Ed Sullivan Theater|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/cbs-broadcast-center-closed-cbs-news-handling-ongoing-crisis-1202887415/|title=CBS Broadcast Center Closed Again; How CBS News Is Handling Ongoing Crisis|last=Fleming.Jr|first=Mike|date=2020-03-19|website=Deadline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/cbs-this-morning-coronavirus-colbert-studio-move-1203541449/|title=How \u2018CBS This Morning\u2019 Rolled With Three Studio Moves in One Week Amid Coronavirus Crisis|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|date=2020-03-21|website=Variety|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/cbs-owned-stations-pitch-in-with-national-newscasts|title=CBS\u2019 Owned Stations Pitch In With National Newscasts|last=Malone|first=Michael|website=Broadcasting & Cable|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==Notable on-air staff==\n\nThe program was originally hosted by Charlie Rose, Erica Hill and Gayle King.<ref>{{cite news|title=Welcome to ''CBS This Morning''|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/welcome-to-cbs-this-morning/|accessdate=November 27, 2017|work=[[CBS News]]|date=January 17, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127231744/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/welcome-to-cbs-this-morning/|archivedate=November 27, 2017|location=United States|language=en}}</ref>  Hill left the show about six months following its debut, and was replaced by Norah O'Donnell.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=Shakeup At ''CBS This Morning'': Norah O\u2019Donnell To Replace Erica Hill As Co-Host|url=https://deadline.com/2012/07/shakeup-at-cbs-this-morning-norah-odonnell-to-replace-erica-hill-as-co-host-307427/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|accessdate=November 27, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127232128/http://deadline.com/2012/07/shakeup-at-cbs-this-morning-norah-odonnell-to-replace-erica-hill-as-co-host-307427/|archivedate=November 27, 2017|location=United States|date=July 26, 2012}}</ref> In November 2017, Rose was suspended and subsequently fired following [[sexual harassment]] accusations made against him becoming public knowledge.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ausiello|first1=Michael|title=Charlie Rose Officially Fired at CBS, Network Cites 'Intolerable Behavior'|url=http://tvline.com/2017/11/21/charlie-rose-officially-fired-at-cbs-this-morning-host/|website=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|accessdate=November 27, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121210135/http://tvline.com/2017/11/21/charlie-rose-officially-fired-at-cbs-this-morning-host/|archivedate=November 21, 2017|location=United States|date=November 21, 2017}}</ref>  Upon Rose's firing, various anchors have filled the third spot on a rotating basis. On January 9, 2018, CBS News president [[David Rhodes (CBS News President)|David Rhodes]] announced that former ''[[Face the Nation]]'' host John Dickerson would join Gayle King and Norah O'Donnell as the third co-anchor of ''CBS This Morning''.<ref name=\"CBS 1\" /> It was announced on October 3, 2018, that correspondent [[Bianna Golodryga]] would be joining the show as the fourth co-host.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bianna-golodryga-cbs-this-morning-co-host/|title=Bianna Golodryga named co-host of \"CBS This Morning\"|access-date=2018-10-03|language=en}}</ref> However, six months later, in April 2019, Golodryga chose to leave CBS News. On May 6, 2019, it was announced that Dickerson and O'Donnell would leave ''CBS This Morning'', with Anthony Mason and Tony Dokoupil named as successors.<ref name=\"TVLine 1\" /> O'Donnell's last day on the show was May 16, 2019 followed by John Dickerson on May 17, 2019.\n\n===Correspondents===\n* [[Don Dahler]] \u2013 special correspondent\n\n===Former on-air staff===\n* [[Harry Smith (American journalist)|Harry Smith]] \u2013 anchor (1987\u20131996) (now at [[NBC News]])\n* [[Kathleen Sullivan (journalist)|Kathleen Sullivan]] \u2013 anchor (1987\u20131990) (later at [[E!]])\n* [[Paula Zahn]] \u2013 anchor (1990\u20131996) (later at [[Fox News|Fox News Channel]] and [[CNN]]; now at [[Investigation Discovery]])\n* [[Harold Dow]] \u2013 interim anchor (1996) (deceased)\n* [[Erin Moriarty]] \u2013 interim anchor (1996)\n* [[Mark McEwen]] \u2013 anchor (1996\u20131999; previous worked as weather and entertainment reporter from 1987\u20131996)\n* [[Jane Robelot]] \u2013 anchor (1996\u20131999) (later at [[WGCL-TV]]; now at [[WYFF-TV]])\n* [[Thalia Assuras]] \u2013 anchor (1999; previously worked as newsreader from 1996\u20131999)\n* [[Russ Mitchell]] \u2013 anchor (1999; previously worked as sports reporter) (now at [[WKYC]])\n* [[Erica Hill]] \u2013 co-host (January\u2013July 2012; now at CNN)\n* [[John Miller (journalist)|John Miller]] \u2013 senior correspondent (resigned from CBS in 2014 to take a position with the [[New York Police Department]])\n* [[Charlie Rose]] \u2013 co-host (2012\u20132017; fired by CBS after sexual misconduct allegations revealed by ''[[The Washington Post]]'')\n* [[Norah O'Donnell]] \u2013 co host (2012\u20132019) (currently on ''[[CBS Evening News]]'')\n* [[Bianna Golodryga]] \u2013 co-host (2018\u20132019) (now a contributor on CNN)\n* [[John Dickerson (journalist)|John Dickerson]] \u2013 co-host (2018\u20132019) (currently on ''[[60 Minutes]]'')\n\n==Saturday edition==\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = CBS This Morning Saturday\n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| show_name_2          = \n| genre                = [[News program]]\n| creator              = \n| director             = \n| presenter            = '''Saturday edition''':<br>[[Michelle Miller]]<br>[[Dana Jacobson]]<br>[[Jeff Glor]]\n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = \n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = \n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 6\n| num_episodes         = \n| list_episodes        = \n| executive_producer   = Brian Applegate\n| producer             = \n| location             = \n| camera               = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime              = 84 minutes\n| company              = [[CBS News|CBS News Productions]]\n| distributor          = \n| network              = [[CBS]]\n| picture_format       = [[1080i]] ([[high-definition television|HDTV]])<br>{{small|(downconverted to [[letterboxing (filming)|letterboxed]] [[480i]] for [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]] sets)}}\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2012|01|14}}\n| last_aired           = present\n| preceded_by          = ''[[The Saturday Early Show]]'' {{small|(1999\u20132012)}}\n| followed_by          = \n| related              = \n| website              = http://www.cbsnews.com/cbsthismorning\n| production_website   = \n}}\n\n''CBS This Morning Saturday'' is the Saturday edition of the program, which premiered on January 14, 2012 and is currently anchored by [[Michelle Miller]], [[Dana Jacobson]] and [[Jeff Glor]], who joined them in late June 2019. It airs live from 7:00 to 9:00&nbsp;a.m. Eastern Time, although local air times for the Saturday broadcast vary significantly from station to station, even within the same time zone; in some markets, the local CBS affiliate may opt to pre-empt ''CBS This Morning Saturday'' \u2013 usually to carry extended weekend morning local newscasts \u2013 and may instead air it on a [[digital subchannel]], a [[sister station]] (such as the case with [[MyNetworkTV]] affiliate [[WNDY-TV]] in [[Indianapolis]], which aired it in lieu of co-owned [[WISH-TV]] until that station lost its CBS affiliation in January 2015; [[WWL-TV]] in [[New Orleans]] does the same, moving it to sister station [[WUPL]] to carry their strong local morning newscast) or refuses to air it (such as with [[KENS-TV]] in [[San Antonio, Texas]] and [[WREG-TV]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]]).\n\nMost CBS affiliates in the Central Time Zone carry the Saturday edition live from 6:00 to 8:00&nbsp;a.m. Central Time, unlike its morning counterparts, which air their Saturday editions on a [[broadcast delay|tape delay]]; it is the only morning program that airs live in both the Eastern and Central time zones, whereas the Saturday edition is aired on tape delay in the remaining time zones.\n\nWhen it debuted, the Saturday edition was originally anchored by [[Rebecca Jarvis]] and Jeff Glor, with [[Betty Nguyen]] serving as the program's news anchor and [[Lonnie Quinn]] as weather anchor. After Glor was named anchor of the Sunday edition of the ''[[CBS Evening News]]'', the program started using various male correspondents, including [[Anthony Mason (journalist)|Anthony Mason]], [[Chip Reid]], [[Jim Axelrod]], [[Maurice DuBois]], [[James Brown (sportscaster)|James Brown]], [[Byron Pitts]], [[Ben Tracy]], [[Lee Cowan]], [[Seth Doane]] and [[John Miller (journalist)|John Miller]], rotating every other Saturday. Following a divisional restructuring in May 2019 that resulted in his departure from the ''CBS Evening News'', Glor rejoined ''CBS This Morning Saturday'' on June 22, 2019.\n\nLike the weekend editions of other network morning shows, the program has a greater focus on human-interest pieces than on weekdays, though it still concentrates primarily on the news of the day during the first half-hour. It also retains some of the common features of the morning show genre which were removed from the weekday show, such as musical performances and food segments, and a couch moved temporarily onto the main set where the hosts introduce certain segments; it also did not include some features of the weekday program including the \"EyeOpener\" (which was added at the top of the first hour of the broadcast on June 14, 2014). Formal national weather segments continued to be included until March 2013; [[Lonnie Quinn]] served as the Saturday weather anchor until his unannounced departure in late 2012, with CBS owned-and-operated station meteorologists substituting until formal weather segments were dropped in accordance with the weekday edition of the program.\n\nAn exception to the usual Saturday format occurred on February 2, 2013 (the day before [[Super Bowl XLVII]]), when the weekday anchor team hosted from [[New Orleans]] (where the game was held at the [[Mercedes-Benz Superdome]]), an edition that was branded as simply ''CBS This Morning'' (instead of ''CBS This Morning Saturday'') and was formatted similarly to the weekday program, including \"EyeOpener\" segments at the top of both hours.\n\n''CBS This Morning'' does not produce a Sunday edition as a result of the long-running ''[[CBS News Sunday Morning]]'', a newsmagazine that debuted in 1979 (and is a remnant of a [[The Early Show#The Morning era|short-lived reformatting]] of the original ''CBS Morning News'' broadcast that lasted until 1982). In contrast to ''CBS This Morning'', ''CBS News Sunday Morning'' has long led the ratings among the Sunday morning shows.\n\n===Anchors===\n* [[Michelle Miller]] (2018\u2013present)\n* [[Dana Jacobson]] (2018\u2013present)\n* [[Jeff Glor]] (2012; 2019\u2014present)\n\n===Former on-air staff===\n* [[Rebecca Jarvis]] \u2013 anchor (2012\u20132013) (now at [[ABC News]])\n* [[Betty Nguyen]] \u2013 news anchor (2012) (now at [[WPIX]] in New York City)\n* [[Lonnie Quinn]] \u2013 weather anchor (2012) (now at [[WCBS-TV]] in New York City)\n* [[Anthony Mason (journalist)|Anthony Mason]] (2012\u20132019)<ref>https://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/cbs-face-the-nation-to-go-one-hour-permanently-mason-joins-jarvis-on-cbs-this-morning/140557/</ref>\n* [[Vinita Nair]] (2013\u20132016)\n* [[Alex Wagner]] (2016\u20132018) (now co-host of [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s ''[[The Circus: Inside the Greatest Political Show on Earth|The Circus]]'')\n\n==Broadcast==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2019}}\nIn the [[Southern Hemisphere]], in the  [[Australia|Commonwealth of Australia]], a trimmed version (for 70 minutes excluding commercials) of the ''CBS This Morning'' weekday edition currently airs on CBS's sister network (since November 2017) [[Network 10]], along with regional affiliate [[WIN Television]], on Tuesday - Friday mornings from 6:30 am until 8:00 am [[AEST]] . A national weather map of Australia is inserted during local affiliate station's [[Cutaway (filmmaking)|cutaways]] for weather reports and forecasts.  Commercial advertising is inserted instead of the usual [[Cutaway (filmmaking)|cutaway]] to the local news programming , however, near-simultaneously with the other US's major [[Big Three television networks|\"Big Three\" television networks]]' breakfast / morning television programs, along with [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC-TV's]] longtime ''[[Good Morning America]]'' (broadcasting in U.S.A. since 1976)  on the [[Nine Network]] from 3:30&nbsp;a.m. and the [[Today (U.S. TV program)|NBC's ''Today'']] longtime morning news/features  show (since 1952, of [[NBC]]) airing on the [[Seven Network]] from 4:00 a.m. It is subject to preemption in regional areas for paid and religious programming. Until recent March 2020, the program was broadcast weekday mornings from 4:30 - 6:00 am, with the Friday edition usually held over to the following Monday. As a result of Network 10's plans to give local mid morning program ''[[Studio 10]]'' a natural lead in for watching by Australian viewers, the program will now air four days a week, in direct competition to rivals of Network Seven's ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' and Nine's ''[[Today (Australian TV program) |Today]]'' (Australian version), with encores of CBS daytime soap opera dramas ''[[The Bold & The Beautiful]]'' to air for two hours on Monday mornings from 6am. Unlike the [[Nine Network]] and [[Seven Network]], the weekend edition is not shown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/04/bumped-cbs-this-morning.html |title=Bumped: CBS This Morning|date=3 April 2020|publisher=TV Tonight|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe format of ''CBS This Morning'' was praised by [[Associated Press]] critic [[Frazier Moore]], noting the network was differentiating itself from its competitors with its focus on hard news: \"''CBS This Morning'' has, in effect, vowed to keep the silliness to a minimum, and its first week is promising.\" He noted the absence of [[tabloid journalism|tabloid]] news items, saying \"[what] ''CBS This Morning'' didn't have \u2013 that, too, provides a good argument for watching.\"<ref>{{cite news|title='CBS This Morning': A Worthy Wakeup TV Alternative|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/01/13/cbs-this-morning-a-worthy_n_1204998.html?ref=media|author=Frazier Moore|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 13, 2012|accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> [[Gail Shister]] of ''[[AdWeek|TVNewser]]'' gave Charlie Rose \"an A for effort\" for stretching past his usual slate of hard news into [[popular culture|pop-culture]] stories. Shister concluded, \"CBS is not reinventing morning TV. But at least they're trying, and that, in itself, is good news.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=CBS This Morning\u2019 Review: Mold Broken, Comfort Zones Stretched, \u2018An A for Effort\u2019 |url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/cbs-this-morning-review-mold-broken-comfort-zones-stretched-an-a-for-effort_b105744|author=Gail Shister |work=TVNewser|publisher=Mediabistro.com|date=January 9, 2012|accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n''CBS This Morning'' won a [[Peabody Awards|Peabody Award]] in 2014 for \"its timely, meaningful look into the face and mind of a tyrant\" in the feature story \"One-on-One with Assad\".<ref>{{cite web|title=73rd Annual Peabody Awards|url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/one-on-one-with-assad-cbs|work=Peabody Awards|date=May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\nUpon the show's launch, CBS executives said that they expected it would take years for a ratings turnaround in the morning time period.<ref name=\"firstrating\">{{cite news|title=First Ratings for \u2018CBS This Morning\u2019 Highlight Steep Challenges Ahead|url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/20/first-ratings-for-cbs-this-morning-highlight-steep-challenges-ahead/?src=tp|author=Brian Stelter|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 20, 2012|accessdate=January 20, 2012}}</ref> The program debuted to an average of 2.72 million viewers (1.11 million in the key demographic of adults 25 to 54 years old) in its first week; its total viewership was 10% lower than ''The Early Show''{{'}}s during the same week in the previous year.<ref name=\"firstrating\"/> As of August 2015, ''CBS This Morning'' continued to show the most growth, up to 12 percent in viewers and up to 14 percent in the A25-54 demo vs. the same week in 2014, with 3.196 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Morning Show Ratings: Week of April 15|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/morning-show-ratings-week-of-august-3/269531|work=TVNewser|publisher=Mediabistro.com|date=August 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, \"CBS This Morning\" came within striking distance of ''Today'' and scored the best November sweeps month for a CBS morning show in 23 years, averaging 2.8 million viewers - only 800,000 viewers behind \"Today.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=CBS Delivers its Most-Watched November Sweeps in the Morning Since 1993|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/cbs-this-morning-delivers-its-most-watched-november-sweeps-in-over-two-decades/312423|date=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.cbsnews.com/cbsthismorning}}\n*{{IMDb title|0355070|CBS This Morning (1987 version)}}\n*{{IMDb title|2163227|CBS This Morning (2012 version)}}\n\n{{US morning news shows}}\n{{CBS News Personalities}}\n{{CBSNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n\n[[Category:1987 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1999 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s American television news programs]]\n[[Category:1990s American television news programs]]\n[[Category:2012 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s American television news programs]]\n[[Category:2020s American television news programs]]\n[[Category:CBS News]]\n[[Category:CBS original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by CBS Television Studios]]\n[[Category:American television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Breakfast television in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = CBS This Morning\n| image                    = CBS This Morning.svg\n| caption                  = \n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = [[News program]]\n| creator                  = \n| director                 = \n| presenter                = {{Plainlist |<!-- Per [[Template:Infobox television]], it states: \"The show's presenter or presenters. Separate multiple entries using {{Plainlist}} or {{Unbulleted list}}. Presenters are listed in original credit order followed by order in which new presenters joined the show. Years or seasons should not be included.\" -->\n* '''Weekday'''\n* [[Gayle King]]\n* [[Anthony Mason (journalist)|Anthony Mason]]\n* [[Tony Dokoupil]]\n* {{small|(for past weekday anchors, [[#Former on-air staff|see section]])}}\n* '''Saturday'''\n* [[Dana Jacobson]]\n* [[Michelle Miller]]\n* [[Jeff Glor]]\n* {{small|(for past Saturday anchors, [[#Saturday edition|see section]])}}\n| theme_music_composer     = {{Plainlist |\n* Paul Evans and Red Nienkirchen (1989\u201390)<ref>Closing Credits, \"CBS This Morning,\" [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5249gWAln2M October 6, 1989].</ref>\n* [[Carly Simon]] and Peter Fish (1996\u201399)\n* Joel Beckerman (2012\u2013)\n}}\n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = {{Plainlist |\n* 12 (1987\u201399)\n* 6 (2012\u2013)}}\n}}\n| num_episodes             = {{Plainlist |\n* 3,110 (1987\u201399)\n* 1,667<!--Update ONLY at the end of the work week on Friday--> (2012\u2013)\n* (as of May 20, 2018)\n}}\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = \n| producer                 = \n| location                 = {{Plainlist |\n* Studio 57\n* [[CBS Broadcast Center]]\n* [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n}}\n| camera                   = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 120 minutes (including commercials)\n| company                  = [[CBS News|CBS News Productions]]\n| distributor              = \n| network                  = [[CBS]]\n| picture_format           = {{Plainlist |\n* [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]]; 1987\u201399)\n* [[1080i]] ([[high-definition television|HDTV]]; 2012\u2013)\n* (downconverted to [[letterboxing (filming)|letterboxed]] 480i for SDTV sets)\n}}\n| first_aired              = '''Original series:'''<br>{{Start date|1987|11|30}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|1999|10|29}}<br>'''Revival series:'''<br>{{Start date|2012|1|09}} \u2013 {{End date|present}}\n| preceded_by              = ''[[The Early Show]]'' (1999\u20132012)\n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = ''[[CBS Evening News]]''<br>''[[CBS Morning News]]''<br>''[[CBS Overnight News]]''\n| website                  = http://www.cbsnews.com/cbsthismorning\n| production_website       = \n| image_alt                = \n| channel                  = \n| first_run                = \n| released                 = \n}}\n\n'''''CBS This Morning''''' is an American [[Breakfast television|morning television program]] that is broadcast on [[CBS]]. The program, which shares its title with a more traditionally formatted morning program that aired on the network from 1987 to 1999, airs Monday through Saturday. It airs live from 7:00 to 9:00&nbsp;a.m. in the [[Eastern Time Zone]].  On weekdays, it airs on [[broadcast delay|tape-delay]] in the [[Central Time Zone|Central]] and [[Mountain Time Zone]]s; stations in the [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific]], [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska]] and [[Hawaii-Aleutian Time Zone|Hawaii Time Zone]]s (as well as Arizona from mid-March to early November) receive an updated feed with a specialized opening and updated live reports. Stations outside the Eastern Time Zone carry the Saturday broadcast at varied times. It is the tenth distinct morning news-features program format that CBS has aired since 1954, having replaced ''[[The Early Show]]'' on January 9, 2012.\n\nThe program emphasizes general national and international news stories and in-depth reports throughout each edition, although it also includes live in-studio and pre-taped interviews. The format was chosen as an alternative to the [[soft news]] and lifestyle-driven formats of competitors ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'' and ''[[Good Morning America]]'' following the first hour or half-hour of those broadcasts, in an attempt to give the program a competitive edge with its [[hard news]] format. (With the exception of CBS News Sunday Morning, CBS has historically placed a distant third in the [[Nielsen ratings|ratings]] among the network morning shows.)\n\n==History==\n\n===''CBS This Morning'' (first incarnation) and ''The Early Show''===\nThe original incarnation of ''CBS This Morning'' made its debut on November 30, 1987, with hosts [[Harry Smith (US journalist)|Harry Smith]], former ''[[Good Morning America]]'' news anchor [[Kathleen Sullivan (journalist)|Kathleen Sullivan]], and [[Mark McEwen]], a holdover from the show's infotainment-intensive predecessor ''[[The Early Show#The Morning Program|The Morning Program]]'' as weather caster and announcer. Sullivan was replaced by [[Paula Zahn]] on February 26, 1990. Beginning on October 26, 1992, in an effort to stop [[network affiliate|affiliates]] from dropping the program, CBS increased the amount of time available during the broadcast for local stations, most of which air their own early morning newscasts before the national news program. Despite a far more successful team in Smith, Zahn and McEwen, ''CBS This Morning'' continued to languish in third place. It was, however, far more competitive than any of its predecessors. A new set and live format introduced in October 1995 had little effect on the ratings.{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n\nSmith and Zahn left the program on June 14, 1996, with [[CBS News]] correspondents [[Harold Dow]] and [[Erin Moriarty]] anchoring ''CBS This Morning'' for seven weeks until a new format was in place. In August 1996, the program was revamped again, as simply ''This Morning'', with McEwen and [[Jane Robelot]] as co-hosts, news anchor [[Jose Diaz-Balart]] (succeeded by Cynthia Bowers, then [[Thalia Assuras]], and finally [[Julie Chen]]) and [[Craig Allen (meteorologist)|Craig Allen]] (of [[WCBS-TV]] and [[WCBS (AM)|WCBS-AM]] in [[New York City]]) serving as weather anchor.\n\nA new format was created where local stations could opt to air their own newscast from 7 to 8 a.m. local time, interspersed with inserts from the national broadcast; the second hour of the national broadcast would then air uninterrupted from 8 to 9 a.m. Ratings went up slightly, and at one point in 1998 the program even moved ahead of ''Good Morning America''. But its ratings success was also brief, and CBS announced its decision to cancel the program in early 1999. Robelot left ''This Morning'' in June 1999 after it was revealed that the program would be replaced. Assuras served as co-anchor and Chen as newsreader for the show's remaining five months. McEwen left the show at the end of September 1999 to prepare for the launch of ''The Early Show'' and was replaced by [[Russ Mitchell]], who formerly conducted sports segments.\n\n''This Morning'' ended on October 29, 1999 after twelve years. It was replaced by ''[[The Early Show]]'', which debuted the following Monday, November 1. Though it had occasional peaks in the [[The Early Show#Ratings|ratings]], ''The Early Show'' was a perennial third-place finisher behind [[NBC]]'s ''Today'' and [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''Good Morning America''. In its last year, ''The Early Show'' shied away from the news, features, light stories and \"[[infotainment]]\" approach used by the program since its debut, that it based off the formats of its two main competitors.\n\n===Development and revival===\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Participates in an Interview With Gayle King of CBS (48584861642).jpg|thumb|[[Gayle King]] interviews Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] in 2019]]\nOn November 15, 2011, CBS News announced that ''The Early Show'' would be cancelled, and that the news division would overhaul its morning news program effective January 9, 2012. The news division's chairman [[Jeff Fager]] and president David Rhodes revealed at the official announcement that day that the revamped and retitled program would \"redefine the morning television landscape\" \u2013 meaning that rather than replicate the relaxed lifestyle-driven styles of ''Today'' and ''Good Morning America'', the new format would feature a mix of \"[[hard news]]\" (a CBS News hallmark), analysis and discussion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Revamped CBS Morning Show With Charlie Rose & Gayle King To Premiere January 9|url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/11/cbs-confirms-plan-for-new-morning-show-with-charlie-rose-gayle-king|author=The Deadline|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref> On December 1, 2011, the title of the new show was revealed as ''CBS This Morning'',<ref>{{cite news|title=The New CBS News Morning Show Gets a Name: \u2018CBS This Morning\u2019 |url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/the-new-cbs-morning-show-gets-a-name-cbs-this-morning_b100534|work=[[AdWeek|TVNewser]]|publisher=[[Mediabistro.com]] |date=December 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=CBS' New Morning Show to Be Called \u2018This Morning' |url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/programming/cbs-new-morning-show-be-called-%E2%80%98-morning/38792|magazine=[[Broadcasting & Cable]] |accessdate=June 2, 2017}}</ref> marking a return of the name to the morning newscast since 1999.\n\nThe founding [[executive producer]] of ''CBS This Morning'' was [[Chris Licht]], who was hired by CBS in the spring of 2011 after serving as executive producer of [[MSNBC]]'s morning news-discussion program ''[[Morning Joe]]''. Licht's move to CBS led to speculation that ''Morning Joe'' hosts [[Joe Scarborough]] and [[Mika Brzezinski]] would follow Licht to CBS, as their contracts with MSNBC were set to expire;<ref>{{cite news|title=CBS Attempts To Recruit Morning Joe And Mika For Morning Show|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/cbs-attempts-to-recruit-morning-joe-and-mika-for-morning-show |work=[[Mediaite]]|date=May 3, 2011}}</ref> though Scarborough and Brzezinski confirmed contemplating offers from CBS and other networks, they signed a new contract with MSNBC out of a belief that their interview-intensive approach could not be duplicated on broadcast television.<ref>{{cite news|title=TCA: MSNBC's Joe Scarborough, Mika Brzezinski Admit CBS News Attempted to Poach Them|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/joe-scarborough-mika-brzezinski-msnbc-tca-279379|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nCBS instead tapped a trio of noted television veterans for the weekday edition of ''CBS This Morning'': ''Early Show'' holdover [[Erica Hill]], [[Gayle King]] and [[Charlie Rose]]. Licht describes Rose, who previously hosted CBS's former overnight news program ''[[CBS News Nightwatch]]'' (which was replaced by ''[[Up to the Minute]]'' and later ''[[CBS Overnight News]]'') in the 1980s, and has also served as a part-time correspondent for occasional segments since 2008 on the long-running newsmagazine ''[[60 Minutes]]'', as \"an incredible interviewer.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Charlie Rose, Gayle King to Headline New CBS Morning News |url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/charlie-rose-gayle-king-to-headline-new-cbs-morning-news_b93969#more-93969|author=Chris Ariens |work=TVNewser |publisher=Mediabistro.com |date=November 10, 2011|accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref><ref name= TVGuideOnCBSThisMorning>{{cite news|title=CBS' Morning Glory?|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Biz-CBS-Morning-1041249.aspx|work=The Biz column|publisher=[[TV Guide]]|date=January 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nLicht promised an \"outside the box\" approach to ''CBS This Morning'', insisting that the show would not include forced anchor banter, cooking segments, \"comedic weather forecasters, [or] cheering fans on an outdoor plaza.\"<ref name=\"TVGuideOnCBSThisMorning\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.boston.com/2012-01-02/ae/30582004_1_robin-roberts-james-goldston-erica-hill|title=Something new coming to morning television|date=January 2, 2012|work=[[Boston Globe]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|access-date=March 23, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516122827/http://articles.boston.com/2012-01-02/ae/30582004_1_robin-roberts-james-goldston-erica-hill|archive-date=May 16, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"TVNewserKickoff\">{{cite news|url=https://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/cbs-kicks-off-cbs-this-morning_b105740|title=CBS Kicks Off 'CBS This Morning'|date=January 9, 2012|work=[[AdWeek|TVNewser]]|publisher=[[Mediabistro.com]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Since revival ===\nOn July 26, 2012, CBS announced that its Chief [[The White House|White House]] Correspondent [[Norah O'Donnell]] would replace Hill starting in September 2012. Hill was pulled from the program immediately after the announcement (an absence which was not explained on the broadcast),<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Top of the Morning (book)|Top of the Morning: Inside the Cutthroat World of Morning TV]]|author=[[Brian Stelter]]|publisher=[[Grand Central Publishing]]|date=April 23, 2013}}</ref> and was eventually released from her CBS contract (Hill joined NBC in November 2012, becoming a co-host of [[Weekend Today|weekend editions]] of ''Today'').\n\nOn November 20, 2017, Rose was fired by CBS following a report in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' in which eight women accused him of sexual harassment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/eight-women-say-charlie-rose-sexually-harassed-them--with-nudity-groping-and-lewd-calls/2017/11/20/9b168de8-caec-11e7-8321-481fd63f174d_story.html|title=Eight women say Charlie Rose sexually harassed them \u2014 with nudity, groping and lewd calls|last=Carmon|first=Irin|date=November 20, 2017|work=Washington Post|accessdate=December 1, 2017|last2=Brittain|first2=Amy|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> King and O'Donnell addressed the issue on the show.<ref>{{Citation|last=Washington Free Beacon|title=CBS hosts address suspension of Charlie Rose over sexual harassment|date=2017-11-21|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p6GbHFB3da0|accessdate=2017-12-01}}</ref> In January 2018, it was announced that [[John Dickerson (journalist)|John Dickerson]] (moderator of ''[[Face the Nation]]'') would join the program as the third co-anchor.<ref name=\"CBS 1\">{{cite news|title=John Dickerson named new ''CBS This Morning'' co-host|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/john-dickerson-cbs-this-morning-new-co-host-announced-today/|accessdate=January 9, 2018|work=[[CBS News]]|publisher=[[CBS Corporation]]|date=January 9, 2018|location=United States|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn May 6, 2019, it was announced that Dickerson and O'Donnell would leave ''CBS This Morning'', with Dickerson moving to ''60 Minutes'' and O'Donnell to ''[[CBS Evening News]]''. [[Anthony Mason (journalist)|Anthony Mason]] and Tony Dokoupil were named as successors, and made their debuts on May 20, 2019, alongside King.<ref name=\"TVLine 1\">{{cite web |last=Iannucci |first=Rebecca |title=''CBS This Morning'' Confirms New Anchor Lineup, Norah O'Donnell to Take Over ''Evening News'' This Summer \u2014 Watch |url=https://tvline.com/2019/05/06/norah-odonnell-cbs-evening-news-anchor-gayle-king-john-dickerson/ |website=[[TVLine]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |accessdate=May 6, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506135354/https://tvline.com/2019/05/06/norah-odonnell-cbs-evening-news-anchor-gayle-king-john-dickerson/ |archivedate=May 6, 2019 |location=United States |date=May 6, 2019}}</ref> O'Donnell's last day on the show was May 16, 2019 followed by John Dickerson on May 17, 2019.\n\n==Format==\nBoth hours begin with the \"EyeOpener,\" a fast-paced 90-second video montage of the day's top stories, ending with overnight sports highlights clips and quips from late-night talk shows. The first hour of the show is more news-intensive, with more original journalism and analysis than the second hour.<ref name=TVGuideOnCBSThisMorning/> The 8:00 hour begins with the \"EyeOpener @ 8,\" recaps the first hour's news, leads into a brief summary of the morning's news headlines, and then shifts its focus to interviews and discussion (\u00e0 la ''Morning Joe'') and lighter fare.\n\n===Weather reports===\n\nTrue to Licht's \"no comedic weather\" promise, the show does not include any standalone national weather segments<ref>{{cite magazine|title=CBS: We're going hard news in the am|url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com/artman2/publish/Dayparts_update_51/CBS-We-re-going-hard-news-in-the-a-m-.asp|author=Bill Cromwell|magazine=Media Life Magazine|date=November 16, 2011|accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref> \u2013 this makes ''CBS This Morning'' the only national morning news program on any of the [[Big Three television networks|\"Big Three\" networks]] not to include such a segment, although time is allotted for CBS affiliates to insert their own local weather forecasts (with national maps and forecasts or a text-only list of forecasts for individual cities nationwide provided for affiliates that do not insert their own weather updates, particularly those that do not have a news department).\n\nHowever, the program will use local [[meteorologists]] from CBS stations to provide the forecast during major [[severe weather]] events (such as hurricanes, wildfires, and blizzards). Most frequently, meteorologists from one of CBS's [[owned-and-operated station]]s - such as Danielle Niles of [[Boston]] O&O [[WBZ-TV]], [[Megan Glaros]] of [[Chicago]] O&O [[WBBM-TV]] and [[Lonnie Quinn]] (former meteorologist for the program's Saturday edition) of [[flagship (broadcasting)|flagship]] New York City O&O [[WCBS-TV]] - appear weekdays (as needed), and Ed Curran of [[Chicago]] O&O [[WBBM-TV]] works the Saturday edition (when necessary).\n\n===Local news cutaways===\n\nFor stations that do not make use of the local news cutaways at :26 and :56 past the hour (including CBS affiliates that do not have a news department), the program uses a taped story introduced by that day's ''[[CBS Morning News]]'' anchor during that time; previously it contained a [[happy talk]] segment between the anchors and panelists.  This was similar to what was done during the 1981-87 run of the CBS Morning News.\n\n===West coast===\n\nFor the [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific]], [[Alaska Time Zone|Alaska]] and [[Hawaii\u2013Aleutian Time Zone]]s (along with most of [[Arizona]] during [[daylight saving time]]), an updated version of the broadcast incorporates an additional greeting to those viewers (\"Good morning to our viewers in the West! and \"As you are waking up in the West...\"), along with updated reports previously denoted by the reporter specifically acknowledging the viewers in that part of the country (e.g., \"Good morning and Good morning to our viewers watching us in the West\").\n\n===Studio===\n{{Quote_box|width=26%|align=right|quote=\"With a wall this big, something important better be happening on the inside.<br>There is.<br>Sorry for the mess. We\u2019re busy building you a better morning.\"|source=\u2014A message adorning the [[CBS Broadcast Center]], as featured in a December 2011 promo for ''CBS This Morning''<ref>{{cite news|title=What's Going on Behind This Wall?|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/whats-going-on-behind-this-wall_b95706|work=TVNewser|publisher=Mediabistro.com|date=November 1, 2011}}</ref>}}\n''CBS This Morning'' operates out of a set in Studio 57 at the [[CBS Broadcast Center]] (numbered for the street address in [[Manhattan]], West 57th Street). The new set was originally planned for use by ''The Early Show'' before its cancellation; that program was based out of the windowed [[General Motors Building (New York)|General Motors Building]] during its entire run, which was shared with the network's [[NFL on CBS|NFL]] [[pre-game show]] ''[[The NFL Today]]'' at times, though during the final year of ''The Early Show'' the windows were covered at all times due to the change to a hard-news focus.<ref>{{cite news|title=''The Early Show'' Leaving GM Building For CBS Broadcast Center, New Studio To Have Different Look |url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/the-early-show-leaving-gm-building-for-cbs-broadcast-center-new-studio-to-have-different-look_b85286 |work=TVNewser |publisher=Mediabistro.com |date=September 16, 2011}}</ref> A section of the studio's exterior, covered in white walls and adorned with the [[CBS Eye]] logo (and also bearing the message shown at right), was featured in promos for the show that began airing in early December 2011.<ref name=CBSThisMorningPreviewed/> [[CBS Evening News]] has shared Studio 57 with ''CBS This Morning'' since December 2016, when the former program moved from its longtime home at Studio 47.<ref>{{cite web|title=A look back at \u2018CBS Evening News\u2019 in Studio 47 |url=https://www.newscaststudio.com/2016/12/07/cbs-evening-news-studio-47/ |work=Newscast Studio |date=December 7, 2016 |accessdate=September 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBits and pieces of the ''CBS This Morning'' set were revealed in promos and web videos released prior to the program's debut,<ref name=CBSThisMorningPreviewed>{{cite news|title='CBS This Morning' debuts Monday, January 9|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/8301-500202_162-57352425/cbs-this-morning-debuts-monday-jan-9/?tag=cbsnewsTwoColLowerPromoArea |work=CBSNews.com|date=January 4, 2012|accessdate=January 7, 2012}}</ref> with the full set unveiled during the January 2012 premiere. Some of the set's features include:<ref name=TVNewserKickoff/>\n* Real exposed brick walls and dark hardwood flooring\n* An in-the-round anchor desk, topped in clear [[lucite]] and etched with the famous \"Eyemark\", as well as additional \"prong\" sections which can be removed if necessary\n* Moveable monitors, allowing guests who appear via satellite to \"sit\" alongside their interviewers at the anchor desk\n* Various items representing CBS News's legacy (most prominently a [[Goode homolosine projection|world map]] from the venerated [[Walter Cronkite]] tenure of the ''[[CBS Evening News]]'')\n* An adjoining newsroom (which was not ready in time for the premiere), complete with large windows facing the street (allowing passers-by to look in)\n* A visible [[green room]] (complete with the only couch on the set), allowing viewers to catch a glimpse of behind-the-scenes action\n\nAlso included on the set, as reported by ''[[TV Guide]]'' reporter Stephen Battaglio, is an [[Oakland Athletics]] baseball cap; executive producer Chris Licht included it to remind his staff of the sports film ''[[Moneyball (film)|Moneyball]]'', whose central character (team executive [[Billy Beane]], played in the film by [[Brad Pitt]]) took an \"outside-the-box\" approach that Licht hopes ''CBS This Morning'' replicates (Licht has called the show \"The ''Moneyball'' of TV\" \u2013 a take-off on the methodology featured in the 2011 film \u2013 and screened the film prior to the premiere for ''CBS This Morning'' staff as a motivational tool).<ref name=TVGuideOnCBSThisMorning/>\n\nIn the wake of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] and the associated closure of the CBS Broadcast Center on March 11, 2020 for disinfection, ''CBS This Morning'' was briefly re-located to the Washington, D.C. studio of the ''[[CBS Evening News]]'' for two editions. After the facility was closed once more on March 18, the program began broadcasting from the [[Ed Sullivan Theater]] on the stage of ''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]'' (where Licht now serves as producer).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cbs-news-film-morning-show-late-shows-ed-sullivan-theater-1285179|title=CBS News to Film Morning Show From 'Late Show's' Ed Sullivan Theater|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/cbs-broadcast-center-closed-cbs-news-handling-ongoing-crisis-1202887415/|title=CBS Broadcast Center Closed Again; How CBS News Is Handling Ongoing Crisis|last=Fleming.Jr|first=Mike|date=2020-03-19|website=Deadline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/cbs-this-morning-coronavirus-colbert-studio-move-1203541449/|title=How \u2018CBS This Morning\u2019 Rolled With Three Studio Moves in One Week Amid Coronavirus Crisis|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|date=2020-03-21|website=Variety|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/cbs-owned-stations-pitch-in-with-national-newscasts|title=CBS\u2019 Owned Stations Pitch In With National Newscasts|last=Malone|first=Michael|website=Broadcasting & Cable|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==Notable on-air staff==\n\nThe program was originally hosted by Charlie Rose, Erica Hill and Gayle King.<ref>{{cite news|title=Welcome to ''CBS This Morning''|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/welcome-to-cbs-this-morning/|accessdate=November 27, 2017|work=[[CBS News]]|date=January 17, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127231744/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/welcome-to-cbs-this-morning/|archivedate=November 27, 2017|location=United States|language=en}}</ref>  Hill left the show about six months following its debut, and was replaced by Norah O'Donnell.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=Shakeup At ''CBS This Morning'': Norah O\u2019Donnell To Replace Erica Hill As Co-Host|url=https://deadline.com/2012/07/shakeup-at-cbs-this-morning-norah-odonnell-to-replace-erica-hill-as-co-host-307427/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|accessdate=November 27, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127232128/http://deadline.com/2012/07/shakeup-at-cbs-this-morning-norah-odonnell-to-replace-erica-hill-as-co-host-307427/|archivedate=November 27, 2017|location=United States|date=July 26, 2012}}</ref> In November 2017, Rose was suspended and subsequently fired following [[sexual harassment]] accusations made against him becoming public knowledge.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ausiello|first1=Michael|title=Charlie Rose Officially Fired at CBS, Network Cites 'Intolerable Behavior'|url=http://tvline.com/2017/11/21/charlie-rose-officially-fired-at-cbs-this-morning-host/|website=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|accessdate=November 27, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121210135/http://tvline.com/2017/11/21/charlie-rose-officially-fired-at-cbs-this-morning-host/|archivedate=November 21, 2017|location=United States|date=November 21, 2017}}</ref>  Upon Rose's firing, various anchors have filled the third spot on a rotating basis. On January 9, 2018, CBS News president [[David Rhodes (CBS News President)|David Rhodes]] announced that former ''[[Face the Nation]]'' host John Dickerson would join Gayle King and Norah O'Donnell as the third co-anchor of ''CBS This Morning''.<ref name=\"CBS 1\" /> It was announced on October 3, 2018, that correspondent [[Bianna Golodryga]] would be joining the show as the fourth co-host.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bianna-golodryga-cbs-this-morning-co-host/|title=Bianna Golodryga named co-host of \"CBS This Morning\"|access-date=2018-10-03|language=en}}</ref> However, six months later, in April 2019, Golodryga chose to leave CBS News. On May 6, 2019, it was announced that Dickerson and O'Donnell would leave ''CBS This Morning'', with Anthony Mason and Tony Dokoupil named as successors.<ref name=\"TVLine 1\" /> O'Donnell's last day on the show was May 16, 2019 followed by John Dickerson on May 17, 2019.\n\n===Correspondents===\n* [[Don Dahler]] \u2013 special correspondent\n\n===Former on-air staff===\n* [[Harry Smith (American journalist)|Harry Smith]] \u2013 anchor (1987\u20131996) (now at [[NBC News]])\n* [[Kathleen Sullivan (journalist)|Kathleen Sullivan]] \u2013 anchor (1987\u20131990) (later at [[E!]])\n* [[Paula Zahn]] \u2013 anchor (1990\u20131996) (later at [[Fox News|Fox News Channel]] and [[CNN]]; now at [[Investigation Discovery]])\n* [[Harold Dow]] \u2013 interim anchor (1996) (deceased)\n* [[Erin Moriarty]] \u2013 interim anchor (1996)\n* [[Mark McEwen]] \u2013 anchor (1996\u20131999; previous worked as weather and entertainment reporter from 1987\u20131996)\n* [[Jane Robelot]] \u2013 anchor (1996\u20131999) (later at [[WGCL-TV]]; now at [[WYFF-TV]])\n* [[Thalia Assuras]] \u2013 anchor (1999; previously worked as newsreader from 1996\u20131999)\n* [[Russ Mitchell]] \u2013 anchor (1999; previously worked as sports reporter) (now at [[WKYC]])\n* [[Erica Hill]] \u2013 co-host (January\u2013July 2012; now at CNN)\n* [[John Miller (journalist)|John Miller]] \u2013 senior correspondent (resigned from CBS in 2014 to take a position with the [[New York Police Department]])\n* [[Charlie Rose]] \u2013 co-host (2012\u20132017; fired by CBS after sexual misconduct allegations revealed by ''[[The Washington Post]]'')\n* [[Norah O'Donnell]] \u2013 co host (2012\u20132019) (currently on ''[[CBS Evening News]]'')\n* [[Bianna Golodryga]] \u2013 co-host (2018\u20132019) (now a contributor on CNN)\n* [[John Dickerson (journalist)|John Dickerson]] \u2013 co-host (2018\u20132019) (currently on ''[[60 Minutes]]'')\n\n==Saturday edition==\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = CBS This Morning Saturday\n| image                = \n| caption              = \n| show_name_2          = \n| genre                = [[News program]]\n| creator              = \n| director             = \n| presenter            = '''Saturday edition''':<br>[[Michelle Miller]]<br>[[Dana Jacobson]]<br>[[Jeff Glor]]<br>\n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = \n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = \n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 6\n| num_episodes         = \n| list_episodes        = \n| executive_producer   = Brian Applegate\n| producer             = \n| location             = \n| camera               = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime              = 84 minutes\n| company              = [[CBS News|CBS News Productions]]\n| distributor          = \n| network              = [[CBS]]\n| picture_format       = [[1080i]] ([[high-definition television|HDTV]])<br>{{small|(downconverted to [[letterboxing (filming)|letterboxed]] [[480i]] for [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]] sets)}}\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2012|01|14}}\n| last_aired           = present\n| preceded_by          = ''[[The Saturday Early Show]]'' {{small|(1999\u20132012)}}\n| followed_by          = \n| related              = \n| website              = http://www.cbsnews.com/cbsthismorning\n| production_website   = \n}}\n\n''CBS This Morning Saturday'' is the Saturday edition of the program, which premiered on January 14, 2012 and is currently anchored by [[Michelle Miller]], [[Dana Jacobson]] and [[Jeff Glor]], who joined them in late June 2019. It airs live from 7:00 to 9:00&nbsp;a.m. Eastern Time, although local air times for the Saturday broadcast vary significantly from station to station, even within the same time zone; in some markets, the local CBS affiliate may opt to pre-empt ''CBS This Morning Saturday'' \u2013 usually to carry extended weekend morning local newscasts \u2013 and may instead air it on a [[digital subchannel]], a [[sister station]] (such as the case with [[MyNetworkTV]] affiliate [[WNDY-TV]] in [[Indianapolis]], which aired it in lieu of co-owned [[WISH-TV]] until that station lost its CBS affiliation in January 2015; [[WWL-TV]] in [[New Orleans]] does the same, moving it to sister station [[WUPL]] to carry their strong local morning newscast) or refuses to air it (such as with [[KENS-TV]] in [[San Antonio, Texas]] and [[WREG-TV]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee]]).\n\nMost CBS affiliates in the Central Time Zone carry the Saturday edition live from 6:00 to 8:00&nbsp;a.m. Central Time, unlike its morning counterparts, which air their Saturday editions on a [[broadcast delay|tape delay]]; it is the only morning program that airs live in both the Eastern and Central time zones, whereas the Saturday edition is aired on tape delay in the remaining time zones.\n\nWhen it debuted, the Saturday edition was originally anchored by [[Rebecca Jarvis]] and Jeff Glor, with [[Betty Nguyen]] serving as the program's news anchor and [[Lonnie Quinn]] as weather anchor. After Glor was named anchor of the Sunday edition of the ''[[CBS Evening News]]'', the program started using various male correspondents, including [[Anthony Mason (journalist)|Anthony Mason]], [[Chip Reid]], [[Jim Axelrod]], [[Maurice DuBois]], [[James Brown (sportscaster)|James Brown]], [[Byron Pitts]], [[Ben Tracy]], [[Lee Cowan]], [[Seth Doane]] and [[John Miller (journalist)|John Miller]], rotating every other Saturday. Following a divisional restructuring in May 2019 that resulted in his departure from the ''CBS Evening News'', Glor rejoined ''CBS This Morning Saturday'' on June 22, 2019.\n\nLike the weekend editions of other network morning shows, the program has a greater focus on human-interest pieces than on weekdays, though it still concentrates primarily on the news of the day during the first half-hour. It also retains some of the common features of the morning show genre which were removed from the weekday show, such as musical performances and food segments, and a couch moved temporarily onto the main set where the hosts introduce certain segments; it also did not include some features of the weekday program including the \"EyeOpener\" (which was added at the top of the first hour of the broadcast on June 14, 2014). Formal national weather segments continued to be included until March 2013; [[Lonnie Quinn]] served as the Saturday weather anchor until his unannounced departure in late 2012, with CBS owned-and-operated station meteorologists substituting until formal weather segments were dropped in accordance with the weekday edition of the program.\n\nAn exception to the usual Saturday format occurred on February 2, 2013 (the day before [[Super Bowl XLVII]]), when the weekday anchor team hosted from [[New Orleans]] (where the game was held at the [[Mercedes-Benz Superdome]]), an edition that was branded as simply ''CBS This Morning'' (instead of ''CBS This Morning Saturday'') and was formatted similarly to the weekday program, including \"EyeOpener\" segments at the top of both hours.\n\n''CBS This Morning'' does not produce a Sunday edition as a result of the long-running ''[[CBS News Sunday Morning]]'', a newsmagazine that debuted in 1979 (and is a remnant of a [[The Early Show#The Morning era|short-lived reformatting]] of the original ''CBS Morning News'' broadcast that lasted until 1982). In contrast to ''CBS This Morning'', ''CBS News Sunday Morning'' has long led the ratings among the Sunday morning shows.\n\n===Anchors===\n* [[Michelle Miller]] (2018\u2013present)\n* [[Dana Jacobson]] (2018\u2013present)\n* [[Jeff Glor]] (2012; 2019\u2014present)\n\n===Former on-air staff===\n* [[Rebecca Jarvis]] \u2013 anchor (2012\u20132013) (now at [[ABC News]])\n* [[Betty Nguyen]] \u2013 news anchor (2012) (now at [[WPIX]] in New York City)\n* [[Lonnie Quinn]] \u2013 weather anchor (2012) (now at [[WCBS-TV]] in New York City)\n* [[Anthony Mason (journalist)|Anthony Mason]] (2012\u20132019)<ref>https://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/cbs-face-the-nation-to-go-one-hour-permanently-mason-joins-jarvis-on-cbs-this-morning/140557/</ref>\n* [[Vinita Nair]] (2013\u20132016)\n* [[Alex Wagner]] (2016\u20132018) (now co-host of [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s ''[[The Circus: Inside the Greatest Political Show on Earth|The Circus]]'')\n\n==Broadcast==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2019}}\nIn the [[Southern Hemisphere]], in the  [[Australia|Commonwealth of Australia]], a trimmed version (for 70 minutes excluding commercials) of the ''CBS This Morning'' weekday edition currently airs on CBS's sister network (since November 2017) [[Network 10]], along with regional affiliate [[WIN Television]], on Tuesday - Friday mornings from 6:30 am until 8:00 am [[AEST]] . A national weather map of Australia is inserted during local affiliate station's [[Cutaway (filmmaking)|cutaways]] for weather reports and forecasts.  Commercial advertising is inserted instead of the usual [[Cutaway (filmmaking)|cutaway]] to the local news programming , however, near-simultaneously with the other U.S.A.'s major [[Big Three television networks|\"Big Three\" television networks]]' breakfast / morning television programs, along with [[ABC|ABC-TV's]] \nlongtime ''[[Good Morning America]]'' (broadcasting in U.S.A. since 1976)  on the [[Nine Network]] from 3:30&nbsp;a.m. and the [[Today (U.S. TV program)|NBC's ''Today'']] longtime morning news/features  show (since 1952, of [[NBC]]) airing on the [[Seven Network]] from 4:00 a.m. It is subject to preemption in regional areas for paid and religious programming. Until recent March 2020, the program was broadcast weekday mornings from 4:30 - 6:00 am, with the Friday edition usually held over to the following Monday. As a result of Network 10's plans to give local mid morning program ''[[Studio 10]]'' a natural lead in for watching by Australian viewers, the program will now air four days a week, in direct competition to rivals of Network Seven's ''[[Sunrise (TV program) |Sunrise ]]'' and Nine's ''[[Today (Australian TV program) |Today ]]'' (Australian version), with encores of CBS daytime soap opera dramas ''[[The Bold & The Beautiful |The Bold & The Beautiful]]'' to air for two hours on Monday mornings from 6am. Unlike the [[Nine Network]] and [[Seven Network]], the weekend edition is not shown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/04/bumped-cbs-this-morning.html |title=Bumped: CBS This Morning|date=3 April 2020|publisher=TV Tonight|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe format of ''CBS This Morning'' was praised by [[Associated Press]] critic [[Frazier Moore]], noting the network was differentiating itself from its competitors with its focus on hard news: \"''CBS This Morning'' has, in effect, vowed to keep the silliness to a minimum, and its first week is promising.\" He noted the absence of [[tabloid journalism|tabloid]] news items, saying \"[what] ''CBS This Morning'' didn't have \u2013 that, too, provides a good argument for watching.\"<ref>{{cite news|title='CBS This Morning': A Worthy Wakeup TV Alternative|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/01/13/cbs-this-morning-a-worthy_n_1204998.html?ref=media|author=Frazier Moore|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 13, 2012|accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> [[Gail Shister]] of ''[[AdWeek|TVNewser]]'' gave Charlie Rose \"an A for effort\" for stretching past his usual slate of hard news into [[popular culture|pop-culture]] stories. Shister concluded, \"CBS is not reinventing morning TV. But at least they\u2019re trying, and that, in itself, is good news.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=CBS This Morning\u2019 Review: Mold Broken, Comfort Zones Stretched, \u2018An A for Effort\u2019 |url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/cbs-this-morning-review-mold-broken-comfort-zones-stretched-an-a-for-effort_b105744|author=Gail Shister |work=TVNewser|publisher=Mediabistro.com|date=January 9, 2012|accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n''CBS This Morning'' won a [[Peabody Awards|Peabody Award]] in 2014 for \"its timely, meaningful look into the face and mind of a tyrant\" in the feature story \"One-on-One with Assad\".<ref>{{cite web|title=73rd Annual Peabody Awards|url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/one-on-one-with-assad-cbs|work=Peabody Awards|date=May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\nUpon the show's launch, CBS executives said that they expected it would take years for a ratings turnaround in the morning time period.<ref name=\"firstrating\">{{cite news|title=First Ratings for \u2018CBS This Morning\u2019 Highlight Steep Challenges Ahead|url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/20/first-ratings-for-cbs-this-morning-highlight-steep-challenges-ahead/?src=tp|author=Brian Stelter|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 20, 2012|accessdate=January 20, 2012}}</ref> The program debuted to an average of 2.72 million viewers (1.11 million in the key demographic of adults 25 to 54 years old) in its first week; its total viewership was 10% lower than ''The Early Show''{{'}}s during the same week in the previous year.<ref name=\"firstrating\"/> As of August 2015, ''CBS This Morning'' continued to show the most growth, up to 12 percent in viewers and up to 14 percent in the A25-54 demo vs. the same week in 2014, with 3.196 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Morning Show Ratings: Week of April 15|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/morning-show-ratings-week-of-august-3/269531|work=TVNewser|publisher=Mediabistro.com|date=August 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, \"CBS This Morning\" came within striking distance of ''Today'' and scored the best November sweeps month for a CBS morning show in 23 years, averaging 2.8 million viewers - only 800,000 viewers behind \"Today.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=CBS Delivers its Most-Watched November Sweeps in the Morning Since 1993|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/cbs-this-morning-delivers-its-most-watched-november-sweeps-in-over-two-decades/312423|date=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.cbsnews.com/cbsthismorning}}\n*{{IMDb title|0355070|CBS This Morning (1987 version)}}\n*{{IMDb title|2163227|CBS This Morning (2012 version)}}\n\n{{US morning news shows}}\n{{CBS News Personalities}}\n{{CBSNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n\n[[Category:1987 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1999 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s American television news programs]]\n[[Category:1990s American television news programs]]\n[[Category:2012 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s American television news programs]]\n[[Category:2020s American television news programs]]\n[[Category:CBS News]]\n[[Category:CBS original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by CBS Television Studios]]\n[[Category:American television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Breakfast television i