u00e8ne du Sud\n[[Pa\u00efta]], [[New Caledonia]]\n|-\n|align=center|[[Pacific Games]]\n|align=center|{{vb-big|ASA}}\n|align=center|{{vb-big|TAH}}\n|align=center|{{vb-big|NCL}}<br><small>(Not AVC member)\n|rowspan=2 align=center| [[Women's Volleyball at the 2015 Pacific Games|2015]]\n|Papua New Guinea\n|-\n|align=center|[[Pacific Games]]<br><small>(AVC member only)\n|align=center|{{vb-big|ASA}}\n|align=center|{{vb-big|TAH}}\n|align=center|{{vb-big|FJI}}\n|Papua New Guinea\n|-\n|}\n\n===Beach volleyball===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Competition!!Winners!!Runner-up!!Third place!!Current event\n|-\n!colspan=5|Men tournament\n|-\n|[[Pacific Games]]||{{flag|Papua New Guinea}}  ||{{flag|Fiji}} ||{{flag|American Samoa}} ||align=center| [[Beach volleyball at the 2015 Pacific Games|2015]]\n|-\n!colspan=5|Women tournament\n|-\n|[[Pacific Games]]||{{flag|American Samoa}} ||{{flag|Vanuatu}} ||{{flag|French Polynesia}} ||align=center| [[Beach volleyball at the 2015 Pacific Games|2015]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://asianvolleyball.net/|name=AVC official website}} {{in lang|en}}\n*[http://www.oceaniavolleyball.org/ Oceania Volleyball official website] {{en icon}}\n\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 1993]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Asia]]\n[[Category:Volleyball in Asia]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Volleyball in Oceania]]\n", "name_user": "Kenwick", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oceania_Zonal_Volleyball_Association"}
{"title_page": "Charles Lewis Anderson", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist/sandbox\n| name = Charles Lewis Anderson\n| image = Charles Lewis Anderson.jpg\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1827|09|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Roanoke County, Virginia]], U.S,\n| death_date = {{death date and age |1910|12|22|1827|09|22}}\n| death_place = [[Santa Cruz, California]], U.S.\n| residence = \n| fields = Botany and other areas of natural history\n| known_for = Early Nevada and California botanist\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| spouse = Merial Howe Anderson\n| signature = C. L. Anderson signature.jpg\n}}\nDr. '''Charles Lewis Anderson''' was an American medical doctor who, in addition to the practice of medicine, made important contributions to fields of [[natural history]], especially botany. Educated in Indiana, he spent most of his professional life in the upper Midwest and West (Hennepin Co., Minnesota; Carson City, NV; and Santa Cruz, CA). Many plants collected by him were subsequently named in his honor.  He wrote about local natural history, and actively engaged in public service in places where he resided.\n\n==Biographical==\nHe was born in [[Roanoke County, Virginia]] September 27, 1827.<ref name=\"harr\">{{cite book |last1=Harrison |first1=E. S. |title=History of Santa Cruz County, California |date=1892 |publisher=Pacific Press Publishing Co. |location=San Francisco, Cal. |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofsantacr00harr/page/n8/mode/2up |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Jeps\"/><ref name=\"reif\"/> His family relocated to [[Morgan County, Indiana]], when he was 10, and his further education took place in that state. He attended  [[Franklin College (Indiana)|Franklin College]] and [[DePauw University]] (known, then, as Indiana Asbury University), and obtained his medical credentials from the latter in 1852.<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite news|title=Dr. L. C. Anderson dies at the age of 83 years |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=SCS19101223.1.1&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN--------1 |newspaper=Santa Cruz Sentinel |date=Dec 23, 1910 |page=1,5 |accessdate=Mar 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Jeps\"/><ref name=\"reif\">{{cite book |last1=Reifschneider |first1=Olga |title=Biographies of Nevada Botanists 1844-1963 |date=1964 |publisher=Univ. of Nevada Press |location=Reno, NV |pages=34\u201337}}</ref> He then spent 10 years engaged in medical practice in [[Hennepin County, Minnesota]].<ref name=\"reif\"/> In 1862 he relocated to [[Carson City, Nevada]] (to be joined a year later by his wife and two daughters). He resided in Carson City for four years,<ref name=\"harr\"/> then moved with his family to [[Santa Cruz, California]], where he lived until his death in 1910.<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n\nDuring his college years he developed a strong interest in natural history, especially botany.<ref name=\"Jeps\"/><ref name=\"reif\"/>  His lifetime income was derived principally from medical practice, but he devoted much effort to the study of botany and other aspects of natural history.\n\n===Hennepin County, Minnesota===\nIn 1852 he was one of the earliest physicians to set up medical practice in the region that later became [[Minneapolis]].<ref name=\"stev\">{{cite book |last1=Stevens |first1=John H. |last2=Robinson |first2=Marshall |title=Personal Recollections of Minnesota and its People, and early history of Minneapolis |date=1890 |publisher=Tribune Job Ptg. Co. |location=Minneapolis, Minnesota |url=https://archive.org/details/personalrecollec00stev/page/n3/mode/2up |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"shutter\">{{cite book |last1=Shutter |first1=Marion Daniel |title=History of Minneapolis |date=1923 |publisher=S. J. Clarke Publishing Co. |location=Minneapolis |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PCgUAAAAYAAJ&ppis=_c&d |accessdate=Apr 8, 2020}}</ref> The [https://www.metrodoctors.com/mission St. Anthony and Minneapolis Union Medical Society] was organized in 1855 with Dr. C. L. Anderson as vice-president.<ref name=\"shutter\" />   \nHe was active in geological and geographical exploration to the west of the Minneapolis area, locating the [[Kandiyohi County, Minnesota|Kandiyohi Lakes region]], and going as far as the present states of Montana and Idaho.<ref name=\"stev\"/> He was sometimes referred to as a geologist, and co-authored a report to the Minnesota state government suggesting a geological survey for the state,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Anderson |first1=C. L. |last2=Clark |first2=Thomas |title=Report on Geology and Plan for a Geological Survey of the State of Minnesota |date=1861 |publisher=Wm. R. Marshall |location=St Paul |url=https://conservancy.umn.edu/bitstream/handle/11299/59459/MGS_surveyplan.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |accessdate=Apr 11, 2020}}</ref> but the governor was reluctant to do so at that time.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Clements |first1=J. Morgan |title=The Vermilion iron-bearing district of Minnesota, with an atlas |date=1903 |publisher=Govt. Print. Office |location=Washington, DC |page=66 |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=ucw.ark:/13960/t6446837c&view=1up&seq=78 |accessdate=Apr 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe helped build a public school and served as the first school superintendent of Hennepin County.<ref name=\"harr\" />\n\n[[Henry David Thoreau]], in 1861 (the last year of his life), seeking a more healthful climate, [http://collections.mnhs.org/MNHistoryMagazine/articles/16/v16i01p035-046.pdf visited the Minneapolis area] for about two weeks.  He wished to study the flora and fauna of the region, and was accompanied most of that time by Dr. Anderson, whom Thoreau had sought out when learning of his extensive knowledge of the area's natural history.<ref name=\"shutter\" /><ref name=\"strak\">{{cite journal |last1=Straker |first1=Robert L. |title=Thoreau's Journey to Minnesota |journal=The New England Quarterly |date=1941 |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=549\u2013555 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/360492?seq=4#metadata_info_tab_contents |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March, 1862, Anderson left Minnesota.  As related by Shutter<ref name=\"shutter\" /> (p.&nbsp;359):  \"He had many friends, and his departure was deeply regretted.\"\n\n===Carson City, Nevada===\nAfter settling his wife and two daughters in Beloit, Wisconsin, he commenced the arduous trek to Carson City.  While travelling, and after arriving and establishing a practice there, he wrote frequently to his wife.<ref name=\"reif\" /><ref name=\"who\" />  In one letter he wrote:\n\n<blockquote>The height of my ambition is to have a pleasant quiet cottage of 5 or 6 rooms, one for a library where we could read and converse evening or enjoy other amusements, a small garden of vines and fruits with a few choice flowers. A business that would yield a comfortable living and a few select friends to come and see us. Out of debt so that what I earned I could call my own, my motto then could be to \"owe no man anything.\" In the study of Nature, and Nature's God, we would be enabled to live nearer to Him, and with greater happiness to ourselves.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Reifschneider |first1=Olga |title=Dr. Anderson in Wild & Wooly Carson City. Nevada |journal=Nevada Highways and Parks |date=1966 |volume=26 |issue=3 |page=16}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\nHis wife and daughters, braving the rigors of a wagon train journey, joined him in August, 1863.<ref name=\"reif\" />\n\nHis four years in Nevada saw him travelling widely around Carson City, discovering and collecting many plant species new or only poorly known to science.<ref name=\"Jeps\"/><ref name=\"who\">{{cite web |last1=Blakely |first1=Larry |title=Anderson's Buttercup . . . |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~larryblakely/whoname/who_andr.htm |website=Who's in a Name? |accessdate=Mar 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPublic service included being superintendent of schools in Ormsby Co., and surgeon-general under Nevada's governor.<ref name=\"reif\" /><ref name=\"harr\" />\n\n===Santa Cruz, California===\nDr. Anderson spent 10 years in Minneapolis, 4 years in Carson City, then 43 years, the rest of his life, in Santa Cruz.  In each case he joined a community in its infancy, and was a significant contributor to its maturation.  \n\nIn Santa Cruz he served local schools, and helped found the Santa Cruz City Public Library in 1868, serving as president of its first board of trustees.<ref name=\"libr\">{{cite news|title=First Librarian |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=SCS19380821-02.1.30&srpos=16&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22santa+cruz+sentinel%22+AND+%22Dr.+C.+L.+Anderson%22-------1 |newspaper=Santa Cruz Sentinel |date=Aug 21, 1938 |page=30 |accessdate=Apr 11, 2020}}</ref>  Subsequently, he oversaw the funding of a [[Carnegie library]] building.<ref>{{cite news|title=Carnegie |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=ES19020102.1.3&e=------190-en--20-ES-1--txt-txIN-evening+sentinel++january+2+1902+page+3-PAGE---1902---1 |newspaper=Santa Cruz Evening Sentinel |date=Jan 2, 1902 |page=3 |accessdate=Apr 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Death====\n\nHe was\n<blockquote> \"one of the most respected of Santa Cruz County's old pioneers . . . for many years enjoyed an enviable medical practice in this community, was a man of scholarly attainments . . . was a man of exemplary character, of an even disposltion, quiet in his ways, unpretending, self-sacrificing, of a very kindly nature. Santa Cruz was made much richer by his presence amongst us, for he lived a life of service, caring little for pecuniary emoluments.<ref name=\"obit\"/></blockquote>\n\n==Collecting, and eponymous scientific names==\n====Flowering plants====\nDuring the period 1862 - 1867, when Anderson lived in Nevada, he collected many specimens of [[flowering plant]]s, which he sent to [[Asa Gray]]'s [[Harvard University Herbaria|herbarium]] for analysis.  According to Tiehm,<ref name=\"tiehm\">{{cite book |last1=Tiehm |first1=Arnold |title=Nevada Vascular Plant Types and Their Collectors |date=1996 |publisher=New York Botanical Garden |location=Bronx, New York |isbn=0-89327-401-1}}</ref> 34 of the plants collected in Nevada became [[Type (biology)|type specimens]] (as did at least one, collected later, when he lived in Santa Cruz, CA;<ref name=\"thom\">{{cite web |last1=Thomas |first1=John H. |title=The History of Botanical Collecting in the Santa Cruz Mountains of Central California |url=https://trees.stanford.edu/PDF/Thomas_1961.pdf |website=trees.stanford.edu |publisher=Stanford University |accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref> namely, ''Arctostaphylos andersonii'' A.Gray).\n\n[[File:Anderson's buttercup 1950m elevation,.jpg|thumb|''Ranunculus andersonii'', Eastern Sierra Nevada]]\n[[File:Prunus andersonii May 21, 2001, Sierra Nevada foothills east of Bishop, CA at 2480 m elevation.jpg|thumb|''Prunus andersonii'', Eastern Sierra Nevada]]\n\nMany [[Binomial nomenclature|binomial scientific names]] honor an Anderson; the ones below honor Charles Lewis Anderson, and are currently (2020) accepted (see references and ITIS<ref name=\"ITIS\">{{cite web |last1=ITIS |url=https://www.itis.gov/index.html |title=ITIS|website=ITIS |accessdate=Mar 16, 2020}}</ref>).  Each name is followed by the (plant family name), a common name, and the region where Anderson collected the type specimen.\n\nPhotographs of each flowering plant may be found at CalPhotos,<ref name=\"Mar 8, 2020\">{{cite web |url=https://calphotos.berkeley.edu/flora/ |title=CalPhotos|website=CalPhotos}}</ref> and further information is available at CalFlora.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.calflora.org/ |title=CalFlora|website=CalFlora |accessdate=Mar 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*''[[Arctostaphylos andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |title=Miscellaneous Botanical Contributions |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1876 |volume=11 |page=83 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/8862039#page/91/mode/1up |accessdate=Mar 6, 2020}}</ref>  ([[Ericaceae]]), Santa Cruz manzanita, near Santa Cruz, CA\n*''[[Astragalus andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |title=Characters of Some New Plants of California and Nevada . . . |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1864-1865 |volume=6 |page=524 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3097299 |accessdate=Mar 6, 2020}}</ref> ([[Fabaceae]]), Anderson's milkvetch, near Carson City, NV\n*''[[Cirsium andersonii]]'' (A. Gray) Petr<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Petrak |first1=F. |title=Beitr\u00e4ge zur Kenntnis der mexikanischen und zentral-amerikanischen Cirsien |journal=Bot. Tidsskr. |date=1911 |volume=31 |page=68 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/44695912 |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref> ([[Asteraceae]]), Anderson's thistle, [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] [Original name:  ''Cnicus andersonii'' (A. Gray)<ref name=\"Mar 7, 2020\">{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |title=Contributions to the Botany of North America |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1874 |volume=10 |page=44 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3076941#page/52/mode/1up}}</ref>]\n*''[[Delphinium andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |title=Delphinium, an attempt to distinguish the North American Species |journal=Bot. Gaz. 12: 50, 53 |date=1887 |volume=12 |issue=3 |page=53 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/28545819 |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref>   ([[Ranunculaceae]]), Anderson's larkspur, eastern [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]]\n*''[[Lupinus andersonii]]'' S.Watson<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=Sereno |title=United States Exploration of the Fortieth Parallel.  Vol. V.  Botanyi |date=1871 |publisher=Govt. Printing Office |location=Washington, DC |url=https://pubs.usgs.gov/unnumbered/70039231/report.pdf |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref>  ([[Fabaceae]]),  Anderson's lupine, near Carson City, NV\n*''[[Lycium andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |title=Characters of New Plants of California and Elsewhere . . |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1868 |volume=7 |page=388 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3068569}}</ref>   ([[Solanaceae]]), Anderson thornbush, S.E. NV\n*''Oreostemma alpigenum'' var. ''andersonii'' (A. Gray) G.L. Nesom<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nesom |first1=G. L. |title=Oreostemma alpigenum (Torr. & A. Gray) Greene var. andersonii (A. Gray) |url=https://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/eflora/eflora_display.php?tid=80348 |website=Jepson eFlora |publisher=UC Berkeley |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref>  ([[Asteraceae]]), Anderson's aster, near Carson City, NV  (Original name: ''Aster andersonii'' (A.Gray) A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=A. |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1868  |title=Characters of New Plants of California and Elsewhere . . . |volume=7 |page=352 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3068911 |accessdate=Mar 3, 2020}}</ref>\n*''[[Prunus andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1868 |title=Characters of New Plants of California and Elsewhere . . .|volume=7 |page=337 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3068561 |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref>  ([[Rosaceae]]), desert peach,  eastern [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]]\n*''[[Ranunculus andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1868 |title=Characters of New Plants of California and Elsewhere . . .|volume=7 |page=327 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3068899 |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref> ([[Ranunculaceae]]),  Anderson's buttercup, eastern [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]]\n*''[[Trifolium andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |title=Characters of some New Plants of California and Nevada . . . |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1865 |volume=6 |page=522 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3097524 |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref>    ([[Fabaceae]]), Anderson's clover, near Carson City, NV\n\n====Marine algae====\nAfter settling in Santa Cruz, Anderson collected many specimens of marine algae.  He sent them to [[William Gilson Farlow|W. G. Farlow]], a prominent [[phycology|phycologist]], who wrote of \"the many interesting species discovered by Dr. Anderson\",<ref name=\"Farl\">{{cite journal |last1=Farlow |first1=W.G. |title=On Some New or Imperfectly Known Algae of the United States |journal=Bulletin of THE TORREY BOTANICAL CLUB |date=1889 |volume=XVI |issue=I |page=1 |url=https://archive.org/stream/mobot31753002261508/mobot31753002261508_djvu.txt |accessdate=Mar 15, 2020}}</ref> and named some in Anderson's honor.<ref name=\"Jeps\">{{cite journal |last1=Jepson |first1=Willis Linn |title=The Botanical Explorers of California-V.  Charles Lewis Anderson |journal=Madro\u00f1o |date=1929 |volume=1 |pages=214\u2013216 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/47993035#page/166/mode/1up |accessdate=Mar 15, 2020}}</ref> The following is currently (2020) an accepted name:<ref>{{cite web |last1=ITIS |title=Haplogloia andersonii |url=https://www.itis.gov/servlet/SingleRpt/SingleRpt?search_topic=TSN&search_value=10995#null |accessdate=Mar 15, 2020}}</ref>\n*''Haplogloia andersonii'' (Farlow) Levring<ref>{{cite web |last1=UC Jepson Berkeley |title=Haplogloia andersonii (Farlow) Levring |url=https://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/guide/brown42.html |website=DECEW'S GUIDE |accessdate=Mar 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=hairy brown seaweed |url=https://wildflowersearch.org/search?oldstate=name%3AHaplogloia%3B&buttonName=none&hab=&Elev=&PlantName=&S__Haplogloia_andersonii.x=131&S__Haplogloia_andersonii.y=89 |website=Wildflower Search |accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref> (Chordariaceae), hairy brown seaweed, Santa Cruz, CA\n\n==Publications==\n*Anderson, C. L. 1861. Report on Geology and Plan for a Geological Survey of the State of Minnesota. State of Minnesota. Retrieved from the University of Minnesota Digital Conservancy, http://hdl.handle.net/11299/59459\n*Anderson, C. L. 1871. A Catalog of Nevada Flora.  Third Biennial Report of the State Mineralogist. p.&nbsp;116-128.<ref>{{cite web |title=Third Biennial Report |url=http://www.nsladigitalcollections.org/browse/stateofnevadamineralogistreports18671879#/item/000000083098935/view |website=Nevada State Library, Digital Collections}}</ref>\n*Anderson, C. L.(Ed). 1890. Catalog of Flowering Plants and Ferns of Santa Cruz County, California.  Santa Cruz Surf Print.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |title=Catalog |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015061230168&view=1up&seq=1 |website=Hathitrust |accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref>\n*Anderson, C. L. 1892.  Chapter VI:<ref name=\"harr\"/>  Geology or the Ancient History of Santa Cruz, pp 90\u201397\n*Anderson, C. L. 1892.  Chapter VII:<ref name=\"harr\"/>  The Gardens of the Seashore, pp 98\u2013110\n*Anderson, C. L. 1892.  Chapter VIII:<ref name=\"harr\"/>  The Fishes of Monterey Bay, pp 111\u2013117\n*Anderson, C. L. 1892.  Chapter IX:<ref name=\"harr\"/>  Catalogue of Flowering Plants and Ferns of Santa Cruz County, California, pp 118\u2013128\n*Anderson, C. L. 1892.  Chapter X:<ref name=\"harr\"/>  Lists and Notes of Native and other Grasses Found Growing Wild in Santa Cruz County, pp 129\u2013135\n*Anderson, C. L. 1892.  Chapter XII:<ref name=\"harr\"/>  Our Feathered Songsters, pp 144\u2013150\n*Anderson, C. L. 1894. Some New and Some Old Algae but Recently Recognized on the California Coast . . .   . Zoe 4(4):358<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=C. L.|title=Some New and Some Old Algae ... |url=https://search.proquest.com/openview/55def9da354b864bf349f5892c87f23b/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=54267}}</ref>\n\n{{botanist|C.L.Anderson}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Charles Lewis}}\n[[Category:1827 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Roanoke County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Botanists active in California]]\n[[Category:Botanists active in North America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist/sandbox\n| name = Charles Lewis Anderson\n| image = Charles Lewis Anderson.jpg\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1827|09|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Roanoke County, Virginia]], U.S,\n| death_date = {{death date and age |1910|12|22|1827|09|22}}\n| death_place = [[Santa Cruz, California]], U.S.\n| residence = \n| fields = Botany and other areas of natural history\n| known_for = Early Nevada and California botanist\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| spouse = Merial Howe Anderson\n| signature = C. L. Anderson signature.jpg\n}}\nDr. '''Charles Lewis Anderson''' was an American medical doctor who, in addition to the practice of medicine, made important contributions to fields of [[natural history]], especially botany. Educated in Indiana, he spent most of his professional life in the upper Midwest and West (Hennepin Co., Minnesota; Carson City, NV; and Santa Cruz, CA). Many plants collected by him were subsequently named in his honor.  He wrote about local natural history, and actively engaged in public service in places where he resided.\n\n==Biographical==\nHe was born in [[Roanoke County, Virginia]] September 27, 1827.<ref name=\"harr\">{{cite book |last1=Harrison |first1=E. S. |title=History of Santa Cruz County, California |date=1892 |publisher=Pacific Press Publishing Co. |location=San Francisco, Cal. |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofsantacr00harr/page/n8/mode/2up |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Jeps\"/><ref name=\"reif\"/> His family relocated to [[Morgan County, Indiana]], when he was 10, and his further education took place in that state. He attended  [[Franklin College (Indiana)|Franklin College]] and [[DePauw University]] (known, then, as Indiana Asbury University), and obtained his medical credentials from the latter in 1852.<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite news|title=Dr. L. C. Anderson dies at the age of 83 years |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=SCS19101223.1.1&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN--------1 |newspaper=Santa Cruz Sentinel |date=Dec 23, 1910 |page=1,5 |accessdate=Mar 28, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Jeps\"/><ref name=\"reif\">{{cite book |last1=Reifschneider |first1=Olga |title=Biographies of Nevada Botanists 1844-1963 |date=1964 |publisher=Univ. of Nevada Press |location=Reno, NV |pages=34\u201337}}</ref> He then spent 10 years engaged in medical practice in [[Hennepin County, Minnesota]].<ref name=\"reif\"/> In 1862 he relocated to [[Carson City, Nevada]] (to be joined a year later by his wife and two daughters). He resided in Carson City for four years,<ref name=\"harr\"/> then moved with his family to [[Santa Cruz, California]], where he lived until his death in 1910.<ref name=\"obit\"/>\n\nDuring his college years he developed a strong interest in natural history, especially botany.<ref name=\"Jeps\"/><ref name=\"reif\"/>  His lifetime income was derived principally from medical practice, but he devoted much effort to the study of botany and other aspects of natural history.\n\n===Hennepin County, Minnesota===\nIn 1852 he was one of the earliest physicians to set up medical practice in the region that later became [[Minneapolis]].<ref name=\"stev\">{{cite book |last1=Stevens |first1=John H. |last2=Robinson |first2=Marshall |title=Personal Recollections of Minnesota and its People, and early history of Minneapolis |date=1890 |publisher=Tribune Job Ptg. Co. |location=Minneapolis, Minnesota |url=https://archive.org/details/personalrecollec00stev/page/n3/mode/2up |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"shutter\">{{cite book |last1=Shutter |first1=Marion Daniel |title=History of Minneapolis |date=1923 |publisher=S. J. Clarke Publishing Co. |location=Minneapolis |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PCgUAAAAYAAJ&ppis=_c&d |accessdate=Apr 8, 2020}}</ref> The [https://www.metrodoctors.com/mission St. Anthony and Minneapolis Union Medical Society] was organized in 1855 with Dr. C. L. Anderson as vice-president.<ref name=\"shutter\" />   \nHe was active in geological and geographical exploration to the west of the Minneapolis area, locating the [[Kandiyohi County, Minnesota|Kandiyohi Lakes region]], and going as far as the present states of Montana and Idaho.<ref name=\"stev\"/> He was sometimes referred to as a geologist, and co-authored a report to the Minnesota state government suggesting a geological survey for the state,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Anderson |first1=C. L. |last2=Clark |first2=Thomas |title=Report on Geology and Plan for a Geological Survey of the State of Minnesota |date=1861 |publisher=Wm. R. Marshall |location=St Paul |url=https://conservancy.umn.edu/bitstream/handle/11299/59459/MGS_surveyplan.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |accessdate=Apr 11, 2020}}</ref> but the governor was reluctant to do so at that time.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Clements |first1=J. Morgan |title=The Vermilion iron-bearing district of Minnesota, with an atlas |date=1903 |publisher=Govt. Print. Office |location=Washington, DC |page=66 |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=ucw.ark:/13960/t6446837c&view=1up&seq=78 |accessdate=Apr 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe helped build a public school and served as the first school superintendent of Hennepin County.<ref name=\"harr\" />\n\n[[Henry David Thoreau]], in 1861 (the last year of his life), seeking a more healthful climate, [http://collections.mnhs.org/MNHistoryMagazine/articles/16/v16i01p035-046.pdf visited the Minneapolis area] for about two weeks.  He wished to study the flora and fauna of the region, and was accompanied most of that time by Dr. Anderson, whom Thoreau had sought out when learning of his extensive knowledge of the area's natural history.<ref name=\"shutter\" /><ref name=\"strak\">{{cite journal |last1=Straker |first1=Robert L. |title=Thoreau's Journey to Minnesota |journal=The New England Quarterly |date=1941 |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=549\u2013555 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/360492?seq=4#metadata_info_tab_contents |accessdate=Apr 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March, 1862, Anderson left Minnesota.  As related by Shutter<ref name=\"shutter\" /> (p.&nbsp;359):  \"He had many friends, and his departure was deeply regretted.\"\n\n===Carson City, Nevada===\nAfter settling his wife and two daughters in Beloit, Wisconsin, he commenced the arduous trek to Carson City.  While travelling, and after arriving and establishing a practice there, he wrote frequently to his wife.<ref name=\"reif\" /><ref name=\"who\" />  In one letter he wrote:\n\n<blockquote>The height of my ambition is to have a pleasant quiet cottage of 5 or 6 rooms, one for a library where we could read and converse evening or enjoy other amusements, a small garden of vines and fruits with a few choice flowers. A business that would yield a comfortable living and a few select friends to come and see us. Out of debt so that what I earned I could call my own, my motto then could be to \"owe no man anything.\" In the study of Nature, and Nature's God, we would be enabled to live nearer to Him, and with greater happiness to ourselves.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Reifschneider |first1=Olga |title=Dr. Anderson in Wild & Wooly Carson City. Nevada |journal=Nevada Highways and Parks |date=1966 |volume=26 |issue=3 |page=16}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\nHis wife and daughters, braving the rigors of a wagon train journey, joined him in August, 1863.<ref name=\"reif\" />\n\nHis four years in Nevada saw him travelling widely around Carson City, discovering and collecting many plant species new or only poorly known to science.<ref name=\"Jeps\"/><ref name=\"who\">{{cite web |last1=Blakely |first1=Larry |title=Anderson's Buttercup . . . |url=https://www.cpp.edu/~larryblakely/whoname/who_andr.htm |website=Who's in a Name? |accessdate=Mar 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPublic service included being superintendent of schools in Ormsby Co., and surgeon-general under Nevada's governor.<ref name=\"reif\" /><ref name=\"harr\" />\n\n===Santa Cruz, California===\nDr. Anderson spent 10 years in Minneapolis, 4 years in Carson City, then 43 years, the rest of his life, in Santa Cruz.  In each case he joined a community in its infancy, and was a significant contributor to its maturation.  He served local schools, and he helped found the Santa Cruz City Public Library in 1868, serving as president of its first board of trustees.<ref name=\"libr\">{{cite news|title=First Librarian |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=SCS19380821-02.1.30&srpos=16&e=-------en--20--1--txt-txIN-%22santa+cruz+sentinel%22+AND+%22Dr.+C.+L.+Anderson%22-------1 |newspaper=Santa Cruz Sentinel |date=Aug 21, 1938 |page=30 |accessdate=Apr 11, 2020}}</ref>  Subsequently, he oversaw the funding of a [[Carnegie library]] building.<ref>{{cite news|title=Carnegie |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/?a=d&d=ES19020102.1.3&e=------190-en--20-ES-1--txt-txIN-evening+sentinel++january+2+1902+page+3-PAGE---1902---1 |newspaper=Santa Cruz Evening Sentinel |date=Jan 2, 1902 |page=3 |accessdate=Apr 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Death====\n\nHe was\n<blockquote> \"one of the most respected of Santa Cruz County's old pioneers . . . for many years enjoyed an enviable medical practice in this community, was a man of scholarly attainments . . . was a man of exemplary character, of an even disposltion, quiet in his ways, unpretending, self-sacrificing, of a very kindly nature. Santa Cruz was made much richer by his presence amongst us, for he lived a life of service, caring little for pecuniary emoluments.<ref name=\"obit\"/></blockquote>\n\n==Collecting, and eponymous scientific names==\n====Flowering plants====\nDuring the period 1862 - 1867, when Anderson lived in Nevada, he collected many specimens of [[flowering plant]]s, which he sent to [[Asa Gray]]'s [[Harvard University Herbaria|herbarium]] for analysis.  According to Tiehm,<ref name=\"tiehm\">{{cite book |last1=Tiehm |first1=Arnold |title=Nevada Vascular Plant Types and Their Collectors |date=1996 |publisher=New York Botanical Garden |location=Bronx, New York |isbn=0-89327-401-1}}</ref> 34 of the plants collected in Nevada became [[Type (biology)|type specimens]] (as did at least one, collected later, when he lived in Santa Cruz, CA;<ref name=\"thom\">{{cite web |last1=Thomas |first1=John H. |title=The History of Botanical Collecting in the Santa Cruz Mountains of Central California |url=https://trees.stanford.edu/PDF/Thomas_1961.pdf |website=trees.stanford.edu |publisher=Stanford University |accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref> namely, ''Arctostaphylos andersonii'' A.Gray).\n\n[[File:Anderson's buttercup 1950m elevation,.jpg|thumb|''Ranunculus andersonii'', Eastern Sierra Nevada]]\n[[File:Prunus andersonii May 21, 2001, Sierra Nevada foothills east of Bishop, CA at 2480 m elevation.jpg|thumb|''Prunus andersonii'', Eastern Sierra Nevada]]\n\nMany [[Binomial nomenclature|binomial scientific names]] honor an Anderson; the ones below honor Charles Lewis Anderson, and are currently (2020) accepted (see references and ITIS<ref name=\"ITIS\">{{cite web |last1=ITIS |url=https://www.itis.gov/index.html |title=ITIS|website=ITIS |accessdate=Mar 16, 2020}}</ref>).  Each name is followed by the (plant family name), a common name, and the region where Anderson collected the type specimen.\n\nPhotographs of each flowering plant may be found at CalPhotos,<ref name=\"Mar 8, 2020\">{{cite web |url=https://calphotos.berkeley.edu/flora/ |title=CalPhotos|website=CalPhotos}}</ref> and further information is available at CalFlora.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.calflora.org/ |title=CalFlora|website=CalFlora |accessdate=Mar 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*''[[Arctostaphylos andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |title=Miscellaneous Botanical Contributions |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1876 |volume=11 |page=83 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/8862039#page/91/mode/1up |accessdate=Mar 6, 2020}}</ref>  ([[Ericaceae]]), Santa Cruz manzanita, near Santa Cruz, CA\n*''[[Astragalus andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |title=Characters of Some New Plants of California and Nevada . . . |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1864-1865 |volume=6 |page=524 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3097299 |accessdate=Mar 6, 2020}}</ref> ([[Fabaceae]]), Anderson's milkvetch, near Carson City, NV\n*''[[Cirsium andersonii]]'' (A. Gray) Petr<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Petrak |first1=F. |title=Beitr\u00e4ge zur Kenntnis der mexikanischen und zentral-amerikanischen Cirsien |journal=Bot. Tidsskr. |date=1911 |volume=31 |page=68 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/44695912 |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref> ([[Asteraceae]]), Anderson's thistle, [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] [Original name:  ''Cnicus andersonii'' (A. Gray)<ref name=\"Mar 7, 2020\">{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |title=Contributions to the Botany of North America |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1874 |volume=10 |page=44 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3076941#page/52/mode/1up}}</ref>]\n*''[[Delphinium andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |title=Delphinium, an attempt to distinguish the North American Species |journal=Bot. Gaz. 12: 50, 53 |date=1887 |volume=12 |issue=3 |page=53 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/28545819 |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref>   ([[Ranunculaceae]]), Anderson's larkspur, eastern [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]]\n*''[[Lupinus andersonii]]'' S.Watson<ref>{{cite book |last1=Watson |first1=Sereno |title=United States Exploration of the Fortieth Parallel.  Vol. V.  Botanyi |date=1871 |publisher=Govt. Printing Office |location=Washington, DC |url=https://pubs.usgs.gov/unnumbered/70039231/report.pdf |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref>  ([[Fabaceae]]),  Anderson's lupine, near Carson City, NV\n*''[[Lycium andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |title=Characters of New Plants of California and Elsewhere . . |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1868 |volume=7 |page=388 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3068569}}</ref>   ([[Solanaceae]]), Anderson thornbush, S.E. NV\n*''Oreostemma alpigenum'' var. ''andersonii'' (A. Gray) G.L. Nesom<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nesom |first1=G. L. |title=Oreostemma alpigenum (Torr. & A. Gray) Greene var. andersonii (A. Gray) |url=https://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/eflora/eflora_display.php?tid=80348 |website=Jepson eFlora |publisher=UC Berkeley |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref>  ([[Asteraceae]]), Anderson's aster, near Carson City, NV  (Original name: ''Aster andersonii'' (A.Gray) A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=A. |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1868  |title=Characters of New Plants of California and Elsewhere . . . |volume=7 |page=352 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3068911 |accessdate=Mar 3, 2020}}</ref>\n*''[[Prunus andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1868 |title=Characters of New Plants of California and Elsewhere . . .|volume=7 |page=337 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3068561 |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref>  ([[Rosaceae]]), desert peach,  eastern [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]]\n*''[[Ranunculus andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1868 |title=Characters of New Plants of California and Elsewhere . . .|volume=7 |page=327 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3068899 |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref> ([[Ranunculaceae]]),  Anderson's buttercup, eastern [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]]\n*''[[Trifolium andersonii]]'' A.Gray<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gray |first1=Asa |title=Characters of some New Plants of California and Nevada . . . |journal=Proc. Amer. Acad. Arts |date=1865 |volume=6 |page=522 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3097524 |accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref>    ([[Fabaceae]]), Anderson's clover, near Carson City, NV\n\n====Marine algae====\nAfter settling in Santa Cruz, Anderson collected many specimens of marine algae.  He sent them to [[William Gilson Farlow|W. G. Farlow]], a prominent [[phycology|phycologist]], who wrote of \"the many interesting species discovered by Dr. Anderson\",<ref name=\"Farl\">{{cite journal |last1=Farlow |first1=W.G. |title=On Some New or Imperfectly Known Algae of the United States |journal=Bulletin of THE TORREY BOTANICAL CLUB |date=1889 |volume=XVI |issue=I |page=1 |url=https://archive.org/stream/mobot31753002261508/mobot31753002261508_djvu.txt |accessdate=Mar 15, 2020}}</ref> and named some in Anderson's honor.<ref name=\"Jeps\">{{cite journal |last1=Jepson |first1=Willis Linn |title=The Botanical Explorers of California-V.  Charles Lewis Anderson |journal=Madro\u00f1o |date=1929 |volume=1 |pages=214\u2013216 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/47993035#page/166/mode/1up |accessdate=Mar 15, 2020}}</ref> The following is currently (2020) an accepted name:<ref>{{cite web |last1=ITIS |title=Haplogloia andersonii |url=https://www.itis.gov/servlet/SingleRpt/SingleRpt?search_topic=TSN&search_value=10995#null |accessdate=Mar 15, 2020}}</ref>\n*''Haplogloia andersonii'' (Farlow) Levring<ref>{{cite web |last1=UC Jepson Berkeley |title=Haplogloia andersonii (Farlow) Levring |url=https://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/guide/brown42.html |website=DECEW'S GUIDE |accessdate=Mar 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=hairy brown seaweed |url=https://wildflowersearch.org/search?oldstate=name%3AHaplogloia%3B&buttonName=none&hab=&Elev=&PlantName=&S__Haplogloia_andersonii.x=131&S__Haplogloia_andersonii.y=89 |website=Wildflower Search |accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref> (Chordariaceae), hairy brown seaweed, Santa Cruz, CA\n\n==Publications==\n*Anderson, C. L. 1861. Report on Geology and Plan for a Geological Survey of the State of Minnesota. State of Minnesota. Retrieved from the University of Minnesota Digital Conservancy, http://hdl.handle.net/11299/59459\n*Anderson, C. L. 1871. A Catalog of Nevada Flora.  Third Biennial Report of the State Mineralogist. p.&nbsp;116-128.<ref>{{cite web |title=Third Biennial Report |url=http://www.nsladigitalcollections.org/browse/stateofnevadamineralogistreports18671879#/item/000000083098935/view |website=Nevada State Library, Digital Collections}}</ref>\n*Anderson, C. L.(Ed). 1890. Catalog of Flowering Plants and Ferns of Santa Cruz County, California.  Santa Cruz Surf Print.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |title=Catalog |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015061230168&view=1up&seq=1 |website=Hathitrust |accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref>\n*Anderson, C. L. 1892.  Chapter VI:<ref name=\"harr\"/>  Geology or the Ancient History of Santa Cruz, pp 90\u201397\n*Anderson, C. L. 1892.  Chapter VII:<ref name=\"harr\"/>  The Gardens of the Seashore, pp 98\u2013110\n*Anderson, C. L. 1892.  Chapter VIII:<ref name=\"harr\"/>  The Fishes of Monterey Bay, pp 111\u2013117\n*Anderson, C. L. 1892.  Chapter IX:<ref name=\"harr\"/>  Catalogue of Flowering Plants and Ferns of Santa Cruz County, California, pp 118\u2013128\n*Anderson, C. L. 1892.  Chapter X:<ref name=\"harr\"/>  Lists and Notes of Native and other Grasses Found Growing Wild in Santa Cruz County, pp 129\u2013135\n*Anderson, C. L. 1892.  Chapter XII:<ref name=\"harr\"/>  Our Feathered Songsters, pp 144\u2013150\n*Anderson, C. L. 1894. Some New and Some Old Algae but Recently Recognized on the California Coast . . .   . Zoe 4(4):358<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=C. L.|title=Some New and Some Old Algae ... |url=https://search.proquest.com/openview/55def9da354b864bf349f5892c87f23b/1?pq-origsite=gscholar&cbl=54267}}</ref>\n\n{{botanist|C.L.Anderson}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Charles Lewis}}\n[[Category:1827 births]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Roanoke County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Botanists active in California]]\n[[Category:Botanists active in North America]]\n", "name_user": "Lblakely", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSanta Cruz, California", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Lewis_Anderson"}
{"title_page": "The Angry Birds Movie", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Ass Movie\n| image          = The Angry Birds Movie poster.png\n| caption        = ???\n| director       = call me Carson\n| producer       = Thanos\n| screenplay     = Sexy Vegan\n| story          = Dwayne Johnson\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Angry Birds (video game)|Angry Birds]]''|[[Rovio Entertainment]]}}\n| starring       = White Dr. Phil\n| music          = Nobody\n| cinematography = \n| editing        = Mike Wasowski\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Columbia Pictures]]<ref name=thr>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/angry-birds-movie-film-review-891692|title='The Angry Birds Movie': Film Review|last=Felperrin|first=Leslie|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 7, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Rovio Animation]]<ref name=thr/>\n}}\n| distributor    = Rule 34\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|5|5|[[Paris]]|2016|5|13|Finland|2016|5|20|United States}}\n| runtime        = 97 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.showcasecinemas.com/movie/angry-birds-movie|title=''The Angry Birds Movie''|publisher=Showcase Cinemas|accessdate=May 6, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160606210541/https://www.showcasecinemas.com/movie/angry-birds-movie|archivedate=June 6, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* Finland<ref name=bfi>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/579dcd44432bd|title=Angry Birds (2016)|work=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=May 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* United States<ref name=bfi/>\n}}\n| language       = Ugandan\n| budget         = $53 billion<ref name=\"SonyandRovio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-angry-birds-sony-20160517-snap-story.html|title=Sony and Rovio hope $400-million promotional blitz will help 'Angry Birds' soar|author=Ryan Faughnder|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 17, 2016|accessdate=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = $236<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=angrybirds.htm|title=The Angry Birds Movie (2016)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\nThe movie is okay. 2/50. \n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries should be no more than 700 words. IT IS NOT RECOMMENDED TO ADD EXTENDED DETAILS! -->\nRed, a bird who has been an outcast ever since he was a hatchling due to his temper, lives on Bird Island with other [[flightless bird]]s. When his temper causes a \"[[preterm birth|premature hatching]]\" of another bird's [[egg]], he is sentenced to [[anger management]] class, which is the maximum penalty allowed on the island. Red's classmates Chuck, who is hyperactive and can move at [[hypervelocity]], and Bomb, who can cause explosions with his anger and fear, try to befriend him, but he avoids them.\n\nOne day, a boat docks at the island's shore, damaging Red's house. The birds are greeted by two [[Bad Piggies|green-colored pigs]], the captain King Leonard Mudbeard and his assistant Ross, who claim to be peaceful explorers bringing offerings of friendship. The pigs introduces the birds to various innovations, including a giant [[slingshot]], but Red becomes suspicious and sneaks into Mudbeard's boat where he finds more pigs hidden below deck, contradicting Mudbeard\u2019s claim that it was just him and Ross. When he returns and shows everyone the additional pigs, the birds refuse to believe that the pigs are up to no good, and Mudbeard claims that he only lied to see if Bird Island was safe for his cousins.\n\nDetermined for help, Red recruits Chuck and Bomb to find Mighty Eagle, the protector of Bird Island and the only bird on the island who can fly, who has not been seen for many years. They find Mighty Eagle on top of Eagle Mountain, only to find that he has not flown for years, and that he is [[Obesity|overweight]], self-absorbed, and leading the life of a [[slacker]]. Red discovers the pigs planting [[dynamite]] around the island, and realizes the pigs are planning to steal the birds' eggs while the other birds are distracted with a party. Red pleads for Mighty Eagle to help him, Chuck, and Bomb, but he refuses. Red admonishes Mighty Eagle before he, Chuck, and Bomb depart. The trio race back to sound a warning to the other birds, but the pigs escape with the eggs and activate the dynamite, destroying the village. The other birds apologize to Red for not believing him and under his leadership, they organize an army and construct a boat from the rubble to follow the pigs to Piggy Island.\n\nThe birds discover the pigs living in a walled city ruled by Mudbeard. Deducing that the eggs are in the castle at the center of the city, the birds [[Angry Birds (video game)#Gameplay|use the slingshot to attack by launching themselves over the walls and into the city's buildings]], destroying them. Red, Chuck, and Bomb infiltrate the castle and discover that the eggs are inside a net; the pigs plan to lower the eggs into a giant pot, cook them, and eat them. Mighty Eagle arrives to retrieve Red's group and the eggs, having had a change of heart. One egg falls out of the net and Red battles Mudbeard for it, but learns to control his anger and distracts him long enough to retrieve the egg. A candle Mudbeard was holding ignites the pigs' reserve of dynamite, and the pot collapses and lands on top of Red, shielding him and the egg from the blast as the dynamite explodes, destroying the city.\n\nRed reunites with the other birds as the egg hatches, revealing three small blue birds. Mighty Eagle approaches Red, Chuck, and Bomb, claiming he merely appeared lazy so they could lose faith in him and find faith in themselves, and takes credit for saving the eggs. Red, now a hero, discovers the other birds have rebuilt his house in the center of the village. Moved, Red allows Chuck and Bomb to move in with him. The pigs are revealed to have survived their home's destruction, with Mudbeard plotting a new plan.\n\nIn a mid-credits scene, the three blue birds use the slingshot to launch themselves out towards the ocean.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Jason Sudeikis]] as Red<ref name=VarietyCast />{{efn|name=ab|First appeared in the ''[[Angry Birds]]'' series.}}\n** Aidan McGraw and Kallan Holley as young Red<ref>{{cite tweet | title = Chuck on Twitter: \"Kallan Holley voice as young Red. And Jason Sudeikis voice as Red. #AngryBirdsMovie\" | user=ChuckWoodSmash|number=720274989727875072 | accessdate = April 26, 2016 | date = April 13, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Josh Gad]] as Chuck<ref name=VarietyCast />{{efn|name=ab|First appeared in the ''[[Angry Birds]]'' series.}}\n* [[Danny McBride]] as Bomb<ref name=VarietyCast />{{efn|name=ab}}\n* [[Maya Rudolph]] as Matilda,<ref name=VarietyCast />{{efn|name=ab}} Poppy{{efn|name=abs|First appeared in the 2014 spin-off game ''[[Angry Birds Stella]]''.}}{{efn|name=uc|Uncredited.}}\n* [[Kate McKinnon]] as Stella,{{efn|name=ab}} Eva<ref name=CSCast>{{cite news | title = The Cast and First Image from the Angry Birds Movie Revealed! | url = https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=123574 | accessdate = October 1, 2014 | publisher  = comingsoon.net | date = October 1, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Sean Penn]] as Terence{{efn|name=ab}}\n* [[Tony Hale]] as Ross,{{efn|name=bp|The main protagonist of the 2012 spin-off game ''[[Bad Piggies]].''}} [[Mime]], Cyrus<ref name=CSCast />\n* [[Keegan-Michael Key]] as Judge Peckinpah\n* [[Bill Hader]] as King Leonard Mudbeard<ref name=DeadlineTrailerSaga>{{cite web | last1 = Pedersen | first1 = Erik | title = \u2018Angry Birds Movie\u2019 Trailer: Sony\u2019s Avians-Vs-Pigs Saga Takes Ire To New Levels | url  = http://deadline.com/2015/09/angry-birds-trailer-jason-sudeikis-josh-gad-bill-lhader-1201546162/ | publisher = Deadline | accessdate = September 23, 2015 | date = September 23, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Peter Dinklage]] as Mighty Eagle<ref name=VarietyCast />{{efn|name=ab}}\n* [[Blake Shelton]] as Earl<ref name=EWSheltonPig>{{cite news | last1 = Staskiewicz | first1 = Keith | title = Blake Shelton to sing and voice a pig in The Angry Birds Movie | url = https://www.ew.com/article/2015/12/29/blake-shelton-angry-birds-movie | accessdate = December 30, 2015 | work = Entertainment Weekly | date = December 29, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Smosh|Anthony Padilla]] as Hal<ref name=VarietyCast />{{efn|name=ab}}\n* [[Smosh|Ian Hecox]] as Bubbles<ref name=VarietyCast />{{efn|name=ab}}\n* [[Charli XCX]] as Willow<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stone|first1=Natalie|title=Charli XCX to Voice Willow in 'Angry Birds' Movie|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/charli-xcx-voice-willow-angry-880102|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=15 March 2017|language=en}}</ref>{{efn|name=abs}}\n* [[Tituss Burgess]] as Photog<ref name=CSCast />\n* [[Billy Eichner]] as Chef Pig,{{efn|name=ab}} Phillip\n* [[Hannibal Buress]] as Edward<ref name=VarietyCast />\n* [[Ike Barinholtz]] as Tiny<ref name=VarietyCast />\n* [[Max Charles]] as Bobby\n* [[Jillian Bell]] as Helene, Yoga Instructor<ref name=VarietyCast />\n* [[Cristela Alonzo]] as Shirley<ref name=VarietyCast />\n* [[Danielle Brooks]] as Monica, Olive<ref name=CSCast />\n* [[Kevin Bigley]] as Greg<ref name=CSCast />\n* Adam Brown as Hug Trader<ref name=VarietyCast />\n* [[Romeo Santos]] as Early Bird<ref name=VarietyCast />\n* [[Geoffrey Arend]] as Day Care Teacher Bird\n* [[Ava Acres]] as Timothy\n* [[Alex Borstein]] as Sophie Bird, Peggy Bird\n* [[Malena Brewer]] as Arianna Bird\n* [[Vincent Oswald]] as Dylan Hatchling\n* [[Samantha Cohen]] as Samantha Hatchling\n* [[Josh Robert Thompson]] as Brad Bird, Dane the Saxophone Bird\n* [[Matt McCarthy (comedian)|Matt McCarthy]] as Rodney Pig and John Hamm (credited as Acrobat Pig)\n* [[Maddie Taylor|Matt Taylor]] as Hamilton Pig and Oinky (credited as Acrobat Pig)\n* [[Mckenna Grace]] as Ella Bird\n* [[Ali Wong]] as Betty Bird\n* [[Fred Tatasciore]] as Monty Pig\n* [[Bella Laudiero]] as Maya Bird\n* [[John Cohen (producer)|John Cohen]] as Johnny Bird\n* [[Clay Kaytis]] as Clayton the Waiter Bird\n* [[Fergal Reilly]] as Foreman Pig\n* [[Catherine Winder]] as Billy the Sign\n* [[Carlos Alazraqui]] as Earl's 2nd Brother{{efn|name=uc}}\n* [[Pierce Gagnon]], and [[Owen Vaccaro|Owen Wilder Vaccaro]] as The Blues {{efn|name=ab}}\n* Eileen Marra, Indra Raval, Joaquin Raval and Sofie Wolfe as Hatchling Singers\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Production==\nThe film was officially announced in December 2012, although IGN noted that this was \"after months of speculation\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davis|first1=Justin|title=ANGRY BIRDS MOVIE ANNOUNCED FOR 2016|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2012/12/11/angry-birds-movie-announced-for-2016|website=IGN|accessdate=24 June 2016}}</ref> The success of the ''[[Angry Birds Toons]]'' series, according to Rovio employee Jami Laes, \"validated\" the idea of creating a feature film.<ref name=\"venturebeatvalidate\">{{cite web|last1=Takahashi|first1=Dean|title=Rovio\u2019s Jami Laes on keeping Angry Birds in the entertainment vortex (interview)|url=https://venturebeat.com/2014/01/14/rovios-jami-laes-on-keeping-angry-birds-in-the-entertainment-vortex-interview/|website=VentureBeat|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\nThe first image from the film was revealed in October 2014, with [[Jason Sudeikis]], [[Josh Gad]], [[Danny McBride]], [[Bill Hader]], [[Maya Rudolph]], and [[Peter Dinklage]] as part of its cast.<ref name=VarietyCast>{{cite news\n  | last1      = McNary\n  | first1     = Dave\n  | title      = \u2018Angry Birds\u2019 Movie Casts Jason Sudeikis, Josh Gad, Peter Dinklage, Maya Rudolph\n  | url        = https://variety.com/2014/film/news/angry-birds-movie-jason-sudeikis-josh-gad-peter-dinklage-bill-hader-1201318330/\n  | accessdate = October 1, 2014\n  | publisher  = Variety\n  | date       = October 1, 2014\n}}</ref> Gad at first refused to star in the movie, feeling it was too similar to his role as [[Olaf (Frozen)|Olaf]] in the 2013 film ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]'' but the director eventually convinced him to sign through a 30-minute \"visual pitch\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hadley|first1=Glenn|title='Angry Birds Movie': Why Actor Josh Gad Initially Said 'No' to the Film|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2442408/josh-gad-said-no-to-angry-birds-movie/|website=inquisitr|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Tilly|first1=Chris|title=JOSH GAD SAYS ANGRY BIRDS MOVIE IS \"UNEXPECTEDLY SMART\"|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/08/03/josh-gad-says-angry-birds-movie-is-unexpectedly-smart|website=IGN|accessdate=14 May 2016}}</ref>\nThe film's budget is estimated at $80 million (\u20ac75 million).<ref name=HT100Million /> Rovio and Sony Pictures announced they would spend roughly \u20ac100 million for the marketing and distribution of the film,<ref name=HT100Million /> giving it the largest budget in the film industry in Finland, outvaluing ''[[Big Game (2014 film)|Big Game]]'''s \u20ac8.5 million.<ref name=HT100Million>{{cite news\n  | last1      = Saarinen\n  | first1     = Juhani\n  | last2      = Teivainen\n  | first2     = Aleksi\n  | title      = Rovio splashes over \u20ac100m in animated feature\n  | url        = http://www.helsinkitimes.fi/business/13289-rovio-splashes-over-100m-in-animated-feature.html?ref=nl-hs-aamu\n  | accessdate = March 23, 2015\n  | work       = Helsinki Times\n  | date       = March 19, 2015\n}}</ref> Despite the massive budget, Rovio CEO Mikael Hed stated that \"it is the one that I don't ever lose any sleep over\",<ref name=Bosstalk>{{cite web\n  | last1      = Rossi\n  | first1     = Juhana\n  | last2      = Grundberg\n  | first2     = Sven\n  | title      = Angry Birds Maker Rovio Aims for the Next Level\n  | url        = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303417104579546104176570972\n  | website    = Wall Street Journal\n  | accessdate = August 28, 2015\n}}</ref> calling it \"tremendously strong as a story\".<ref name=Bosstalk /> During August 2015, Rovio announced that they were expecting to cut 250 jobs equaling 40% of the company, the only sector spared being personnel working on the movie.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last1      = Spangler\n  | first1     = Todd\n  | title      = \u2018Angry Birds\u2019 Maker Rovio to Axe 260 Jobs, But Spares Movie Staff\n  | url        = https://variety.com/2015/biz/news/angry-birds-rovio-layoffs-260-jobs-1201578622/\n  | website    = Variety\n  | accessdate = August 28, 2015\n}}</ref>\n\nWhen multiple major studios approached Rovio to discuss the production of the film adaptation in 2010, Hed eventually decided to have Rovio establish its own in-house animation studio and have it work on the film, rather than risk losing creative control in allowing a third-party studio to produce it. [[David Maisel]], the founding chairman of [[Marvel Studios]], offered to help Hed and Rovio produce the film,<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Sorensen|editor1-first=Jim|title=The Art of The Angry Birds Movie|date=June 1, 2016|publisher=IDW Publishing|page=9|quote='''Hed:''' \"We were first approached in early 2010 by Hollywood studios to discuss making Angry Birds into a feature film...I had in my mind a vision for what the world of Angry Birds was, and I wanted to make sure that we would be in control of what the story of the movie would be. If we had given Angry Birds to another studio to be developed, we would have lost that creative control. So I ultimately decided that we had to try to make the movie ourselves, even if I didn't know how to make that a reality. That is, until I met David.\"}}</ref> as well as John Cohen from [[Illumination (company)|Illumination Entertainment]] and Catherine Winder from [[Lucasfilm]], who later served as the film's producers.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Sorensen|editor1-first=Jim|title=The Art of The Angry Birds Movie|date=June 1, 2016|publisher=IDW Publishing|page=10}}</ref> Animation services were handled by [[Sony Pictures Imageworks]].<ref name=\"ABVancouver\">{{cite news |last1=Seikaly |first1=Andrea |title=\u2018Angry Birds\u2019 Pic Nests in Vancouver |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/games/angry-birds-pic-nests-in-vancouver-1201104828/ |accessdate=July 21, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Variety Media]] |date=February 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Angry Birds'' characters were not depicted in their [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphized]] cinematic designs until the film's announcement so as to avoid spoiling it for audiences.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Sorensen|editor1-first=Jim|title=The Art of The Angry Birds Movie|date=June 1, 2016|publisher=IDW Publishing|page=9|quote='''Maisel:''' \"[W]e also talked about how to make the movie as big as possible. Mikael and I agreed back in 2011 that...we should do certain things to protect the movie...Let's not let the birds have arms and legs until the movie comes out. Let's not have CGI-grade animation until the movie comes out. These were things that, we knew, if we could protect those things, then the movie had a chance to be really special...\"}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n===Soundtrack===\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Angry Birds Movie: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = Various artists\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2016|05|06}}<ref>{{cite web\n  | url   = http://www.bustle.com/articles/151921-demi-lovatos-angry-birds-soundtrack-song-could-be-the-2016-song-of-the-summer\n  | title = Demi Lovato's 'Angry Birds' Soundtrack Song Could Be The 2016 Song Of The Summer\n  | work  = Bustle|access-date = January 9, 2016\n  | date  = January 29, 2016\n}}</ref>\n| recorded   = 2015-16\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Pop music|Pop]]\n*[[Rock music|rock]]\n*[[Country music|country]]\n*[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n*[[Electronic music|electronic]]}}\n| length     = 48:43\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nThe film's soundtrack, titled '''''The Angry Birds Movie: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack,'''''<ref>{{cite web\n  | url   = https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/angry-birds-movie-original/id1098314780\n  | title = The Angry Birds Movie (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n  | work  = iTunes|access-date = January 9, 2016\n  | date  = January 29, 2016\n}}</ref> was released on May 6, 2016.<ref>{{cite web\n  | url   = http://www.idolator.com/7629314/angry-birds-movie-soundtrack-tracklist-demi-lovato-charli-xcx\n  | title = \u2018The Angry Birds Movie\u2019 Soundtrack Features Demi Lovato, Charli XCX & Rick Astley\n  | work  = Idolator|access-date = January 9, 2016\n  | date  = January 29, 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n====Track listing====\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed=no\n| extra_column     = Performed by\n| title1           = [[Friends (Blake Shelton song)|Friends]]<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z2tzzDtDw-k|title=Blake Shelton - Friends - From The Angry Birds Movie (Official Video)|date=April 8, 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n| extra1           = [[Blake Shelton]]\n| length1          = 3:04\n| title2           = [[I Will Survive]]<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Sh3EUvi9b4Y|title=Demi Lovato - \u201cI Will Survive\u201d - From The Angry Birds Movie [Official Audio]|date=May 5, 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n| extra2           = [[Demi Lovato]]\n| length2          = 4:05\n| title3           = Wonderful Life (Mi Oh My)<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a-ux_HIfZ_k|title=Matoma - Wonderful Life (Mi Oh My) - From The Angry Birds Movie [Official Audio]|date=April 22, 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n| extra3           = [[Matoma]]\n| length3          = 3:30\n| title4           = [[On Top of the World (Imagine Dragons song)|On Top of the World]]\n| extra4     